INSERT OR IGNORE INTO `lessons` (`id`,`course_id`,`title`,`section_id`,`lesson_type`,`content`,`content_format`,`video_key`,`primary_asset_id`,`intro_asset_id`,`duration_minutes`,`is_preview`,`available_after_days`,`required_watch_percent`,`transcript`,`experience_json`,`position`,`updated_at`) SELECT 'cmf-module-3-03-lesson-01','cognizen-crypto-mastery-foundations-production','What Is a Breakout? and Breakout Strategy Versus Momentum Strategy','cmf-module-3-03','text','### Learning Objectives\n\nBy the end of this module, you should be able to:\n\nExplain what breakout and momentum strategies attempt to capture\n\nDistinguish a genuine breakout from a temporary move beyond a price level\n\nUnderstand how consolidation, volatility compression and market participation can precede directional movement\n\nUse price structure, volume, volatility and relative strength to evaluate breakout quality\n\nDevelop objective entry, invalidation and exit rules\n\nExplain the risks of late entries, false breakouts and liquidity sweeps\n\nUnderstand how momentum strategies differ from trend-following and mean-reversion approaches\n\nAdjust position size for volatility, liquidity and stop distance\n\nEvaluate the influence of derivatives positioning and liquidation activity\n\nDesign and test a basic breakout or momentum framework\n\n### Introduction\n\nMarkets frequently spend long periods moving within relatively narrow areas before suddenly expanding in one direction.\n\nDuring these quieter periods, buyers and sellers may be building positions, reducing exposure or waiting for new information. Volatility contracts, trading ranges become clearer and market attention may decline.\n\nEventually, one side gains sufficient control to push price beyond the established boundary.\n\nThis movement is called a breakout when price rises above resistance and a breakdown when it falls below support.\n\nMomentum strategies attempt to participate when price is already moving strongly and the movement appears likely to continue.\n\nThe central logic is different from mean reversion.\n\nA mean-reversion participant sees an extreme move and asks whether price may return toward its average.\n\nA momentum participant sees strong movement and asks whether the market is revealing new information, demand or positioning that could push price farther.\n\nBreakout and momentum strategies can capture some of the most powerful movements in cryptocurrency markets. They can also produce repeated losses because price often moves beyond a visible level temporarily before reversing.\n\nA disciplined breakout strategy must therefore do more than identify that price crossed a line.\n\nIt should evaluate whether the market is accepting the new price area, whether genuine participation supports the move and whether the position can be entered without exposing the portfolio to excessive risk.\n\n### What Is a Breakout?\n\nA breakout occurs when price moves beyond an established area of resistance, consolidation or market structure.\n\nSuppose a cryptocurrency has repeatedly risen toward 100 units and then declined. The area around 100 has acted as resistance because sellers have repeatedly prevented price from remaining above it.\n\nIf price later moves above 100, the market may be attempting to establish a new trading range.\n\nThe move itself does not confirm that the breakout will succeed. Price must show that buyers are willing to continue transacting above the former boundary.\n\nA bearish breakdown follows the same principle in the opposite direction. If a market repeatedly holds near 80 and then falls below that support area, sellers may be gaining control.\n\nThe important issue is not whether price touched or briefly crossed the level. The important issue is whether the market can sustain activity beyond it.\n\n### What Is Momentum?\n\nMomentum describes the speed and persistence of price movement.\n\nA market with strong positive momentum may show large bullish candles, limited pullbacks, strong closes and repeated movement above previous highs.\n\nA market with negative momentum may display large bearish candles, weak recoveries and continued movement below previous lows.\n\nMomentum does not mean that price is correctly valued. It means that the balance of current market activity strongly favours one direction.\n\nA fundamentally weak token can experience powerful upward momentum because of speculation, limited supply or a short squeeze.\n\nA fundamentally strong project can experience severe negative momentum during a liquidity crisis.\n\nMomentum strategies focus on current market behaviour. Fundamental analysis remains important because it helps explain whether the movement may be sustainable or unusually dangerous.\n\n### Breakout Strategy Versus Momentum Strategy\n\nBreakout and momentum strategies overlap, but they are not identical.\n\nA breakout strategy focuses on price leaving a defined structure. The entry is usually connected to a specific level such as resistance, support or a consolidation boundary.\n\nA momentum strategy may enter even when no clear range exists. It may respond to acceleration, relative strength, rising volume or persistent directional price action.\n\nFor example, a breakout trader may wait for price to close above a three-month resistance zone.\n\nA momentum trader may enter because the asset has produced several strong closes, expanding volume and superior performance relative to the broader market.\n\nThe breakout is a structural event.\n\nMomentum is a characteristic of the movement.\n\nA high-quality setup often contains both.','markdown',NULL,NULL,NULL,6,0,0,0,'',NULL,1,1785297600000 WHERE EXISTS (SELECT 1 FROM `courses` WHERE `id`='cognizen-crypto-mastery-foundations-production');
--> statement-breakpoint
INSERT OR IGNORE INTO `lessons` (`id`,`course_id`,`title`,`section_id`,`lesson_type`,`content`,`content_format`,`video_key`,`primary_asset_id`,`intro_asset_id`,`duration_minutes`,`is_preview`,`available_after_days`,`required_watch_percent`,`transcript`,`experience_json`,`position`,`updated_at`) SELECT 'cmf-module-3-03-lesson-02','cognizen-crypto-mastery-foundations-production','How Consolidation Prepares a Breakout and Closed-Candle Confirmation','cmf-module-3-03','text','### How Consolidation Prepares a Breakout\n\nConsolidation occurs when price trades within a relatively limited area.\n\nDuring consolidation, neither buyers nor sellers maintain decisive control. Transactions continue, but directional progress is limited.\n\nThis period can serve several functions.\n\nEarly investors may take profits while new participants accumulate positions. Short sellers may enter near resistance while buyers support the lower boundary. Market makers may provide liquidity around a central value.\n\nAs the range continues, orders often accumulate beyond its boundaries.\n\nAbove resistance, there may be breakout purchases and stop losses from short positions.\n\nBelow support, there may be breakdown sells and stop losses from long positions.\n\nWhen price leaves the range, these clustered orders can accelerate the movement.\n\nA longer consolidation can therefore create the conditions for a significant breakout, but it does not determine the direction.\n\n### Volatility Compression\n\nVolatility compression occurs when the size of price movements becomes smaller.\n\nCandles may narrow, Bollinger Bands may contract and average true range may decline.\n\nCompression suggests that the market is temporarily reaching greater agreement about price or that participants are waiting for a catalyst.\n\nLow volatility does not mean low risk.\n\nIt can be the calm period before a sharp expansion.\n\nA breakout trader may monitor compression because the eventual release of stored positioning and pending orders can create rapid movement.\n\nHowever, the first move out of a compressed range may be false. Price can break one boundary, trigger orders and then reverse through the opposite side.\n\nThe strategy should therefore define what evidence is required before treating volatility expansion as genuine directional acceptance.\n\n### Market Acceptance\n\nMarket acceptance means that price moves beyond an established level and continues to trade there.\n\nEvidence of acceptance may include several candles closing beyond the level, sustained volume and the formation of new support or resistance outside the former range.\n\nSuppose price breaks above 100 and then remains between 102 and 110 for several periods. This suggests that market participants are accepting the higher area.\n\nBy contrast, if price trades briefly at 103 and then closes back below 100, the move has not demonstrated acceptance.\n\nAcceptance is more important than the first crossing.\n\nIt shows that participants are prepared to conduct meaningful business at the new prices.\n\n### Rejection and False Breakouts\n\nA false breakout occurs when price moves beyond a boundary but fails to remain there.\n\nFor example, price may rise above resistance, trigger breakout orders and then close back inside the range.\n\nThis can happen because the initial demand was insufficient, large sellers used the breakout to exit or the movement was designed to reach stop orders and liquidity.\n\nFalse breakouts can reverse sharply because recent entrants become trapped.\n\nTraders who bought above resistance may sell when price returns below it. Short sellers may also re-enter, increasing downward pressure.\n\nThe opposite process occurs after a false breakdown.\n\nA breakdown that rapidly recovers above support can trap short sellers and create a strong rebound.\n\n### Liquidity Sweeps\n\nVisible support and resistance areas attract clusters of orders.\n\nA move beyond one of these areas may be a liquidity sweep rather than the beginning of a new trend.\n\nSuppose many long traders place stops just below support. Price may fall through the level, trigger those stops and create a temporary surge of sell orders.\n\nLarge buyers may absorb that selling and push price back above support.\n\nThe move below the level was real, but the market rejected the lower price.\n\nIt is difficult to distinguish a sweep from a true breakdown in advance. Both begin with price moving beyond support.\n\nThe distinction becomes clearer through the closing position, volume, subsequent structure and whether price gains acceptance outside the range.\n\n### Closed-Candle Confirmation\n\nOne method of reducing premature entries is to wait for the relevant candle to close beyond the breakout level.\n\nAn intraday move above resistance can reverse before the candle completes.\n\nA closing price beyond the level provides more evidence that the market accepted the new area for the selected period.\n\nThe strength of the confirmation depends on the timeframe.\n\nA weekly close beyond major resistance generally contains more market information than a five-minute close beyond a minor level.\n\nWaiting for closure has a cost. The entry occurs later, the stop distance may increase and part of the move may already be complete.\n\nConfirmation improves evidence. It does not remove risk.','markdown',NULL,NULL,NULL,6,0,0,0,'',NULL,2,1785297600000 WHERE EXISTS (SELECT 1 FROM `courses` WHERE `id`='cognizen-crypto-mastery-foundations-production');
--> statement-breakpoint
INSERT OR IGNORE INTO `lessons` (`id`,`course_id`,`title`,`section_id`,`lesson_type`,`content`,`content_format`,`video_key`,`primary_asset_id`,`intro_asset_id`,`duration_minutes`,`is_preview`,`available_after_days`,`required_watch_percent`,`transcript`,`experience_json`,`position`,`updated_at`) SELECT 'cmf-module-3-03-lesson-03','cognizen-crypto-mastery-foundations-production','Multiple-Close Confirmation and Long Liquidation Breakdowns','cmf-module-3-03','text','### Multiple-Close Confirmation\n\nSome strategies require more than one close beyond the level.\n\nFor example, a system may require two daily closes above resistance before entering.\n\nThis can reduce exposure to one-period false breaks.\n\nIt can also delay participation substantially.\n\nBy the time several closes occur, price may be far from the original boundary and the risk-to-reward may have deteriorated.\n\nThe correct number of confirmation periods depends on the asset, timeframe and strategy design.\n\nThe rule should be tested rather than chosen because more confirmation appears automatically safer.\n\n### Breakout Distance\n\nA market may cross resistance by only a very small amount.\n\nSome systems require price to exceed the boundary by a minimum percentage or volatility-adjusted distance.\n\nFor example, the strategy may require a close at least half an ATR above the resistance zone.\n\nThis helps distinguish a decisive move from ordinary market noise.\n\nA fixed percentage may work poorly across assets with different volatility.\n\nA volatility-adjusted threshold is generally more adaptable, but it still cannot determine whether the move will continue.\n\n### The Quality of the Breakout Candle\n\nThe breakout candle can provide information about conviction.\n\nA stronger bullish breakout candle may have a wide body, close near its high and display limited upper rejection.\n\nA weaker candle may move above resistance but leave a long upper wick and close near or below the boundary.\n\nThe candle should be compared with recent price action.\n\nA large candle in a highly volatile market may be ordinary.\n\nA moderately sized candle after prolonged compression may represent an important change.\n\nThe candle’s location, range and close matter more than its colour alone.\n\n### Volume Confirmation\n\nVolume can help determine whether meaningful participation supports the breakout.\n\nA move beyond resistance accompanied by unusually high volume may indicate that new buyers, short covering and institutional or algorithmic activity are entering the market.\n\nA low-volume breakout may indicate limited conviction or a market moving upward simply because sellers are absent.\n\nLow volume does not automatically invalidate the move. Some strong trends begin in quiet conditions.\n\nThe question is whether the level is being accepted and whether sufficient liquidity exists to support the position.\n\nVolume should be evaluated relative to the market’s normal activity rather than through one absolute number.\n\n### Relative Volume\n\nRelative volume compares current activity with a recent average.\n\nSuppose the average hourly volume is one million units and the breakout hour records three million. Relative volume is approximately three.\n\nThis indicates unusually high participation.\n\nThe interpretation still depends on price behaviour.\n\nHigh volume with a strong close above resistance can support the breakout.\n\nHigh volume with a long upper wick and close back inside the range may indicate distribution or rejection.\n\n### Spot Volume and Derivatives Volume\n\nCryptocurrency breakouts can be driven by spot demand, derivatives positioning or both.\n\nSpot volume represents actual exchange of the underlying asset.\n\nDerivatives volume reflects contracts based on the asset.\n\nA breakout led mainly by spot buying may be considered more stable because new market demand is purchasing the asset directly.\n\nA breakout driven mainly by leveraged derivatives may be powerful but vulnerable to liquidation.\n\nThis distinction is not absolute. Spot and derivatives markets influence one another continuously.\n\nThe participant should examine whether the movement reflects durable demand or temporary leveraged pressure.\n\n### Open Interest\n\nOpen interest measures the total value or number of outstanding derivative positions.\n\nRising price and rising open interest may indicate that new leveraged positions are entering.\n\nThis can support momentum, but it also creates a larger pool of positions that may later be liquidated.\n\nRising price and falling open interest may indicate that short positions are closing rather than new buyers entering.\n\nThe movement can still be powerful, but it may weaken when the short covering is complete.\n\nOpen interest provides information about positioning, not guaranteed direction.\n\n### Short Squeezes\n\nA short squeeze occurs when rising price forces short sellers to close positions.\n\nClosing a short requires buying the asset or contract.\n\nThis buying pushes price higher and can trigger additional liquidations.\n\nA breakout above major resistance can begin or accelerate a short squeeze.\n\nThe movement may become much larger than ordinary fundamental demand would suggest.\n\nEntering late in the squeeze is dangerous because forced buying eventually ends.\n\nWhen the liquidation pressure is exhausted, price can reverse quickly.\n\n### Long Liquidation Breakdowns\n\nThe bearish equivalent occurs when long positions are liquidated.\n\nAs price falls, leveraged long traders lose collateral and their positions are closed automatically.\n\nThese liquidations create additional selling, which pushes price lower and triggers more liquidations.\n\nA breakdown driven by this process can be exceptionally fast.\n\nThe trend may continue after the cascade, but it may also rebound sharply once the forced selling ends.\n\nA trader entering after a large liquidation move should distinguish ongoing bearish demand from the final stage of forced selling.','markdown',NULL,NULL,NULL,6,0,0,0,'',NULL,3,1785297600000 WHERE EXISTS (SELECT 1 FROM `courses` WHERE `id`='cognizen-crypto-mastery-foundations-production');
--> statement-breakpoint
INSERT OR IGNORE INTO `lessons` (`id`,`course_id`,`title`,`section_id`,`lesson_type`,`content`,`content_format`,`video_key`,`primary_asset_id`,`intro_asset_id`,`duration_minutes`,`is_preview`,`available_after_days`,`required_watch_percent`,`transcript`,`experience_json`,`position`,`updated_at`) SELECT 'cmf-module-3-03-lesson-04','cognizen-crypto-mastery-foundations-production','Funding Rates and Percentage Targets','cmf-module-3-03','text','### Funding Rates\n\nPerpetual futures use funding payments to keep contract prices near spot prices.\n\nStrongly positive funding generally means long positions are paying short positions.\n\nStrongly negative funding generally means shorts are paying longs.\n\nDuring a bullish breakout, rising positive funding can indicate increasing long demand.\n\nIf funding becomes extreme, the trade may become crowded and expensive to maintain.\n\nA correct directional position can still produce a poor return after substantial funding costs.\n\nExtreme funding may also increase the risk of a reversal or liquidation cascade.\n\n### Breakout Retests\n\nAfter price breaks a level, it may return to test the former boundary.\n\nA bullish retest occurs when former resistance becomes support.\n\nA bearish retest occurs when former support becomes resistance.\n\nRetests can improve entry quality because the invalidation level is often closer.\n\nThey also provide evidence that the market recognises the role reversal.\n\nA retest is not guaranteed.\n\nSome of the strongest breakouts move immediately and never return to the original level.\n\nWaiting for a retest can reduce false entries while causing missed opportunities.\n\n### Successful Retest\n\nA successful bullish retest may show price returning toward former resistance, rejecting lower movement and forming a higher low.\n\nVolume may decline during the pullback and increase when buyers return.\n\nA failed retest occurs when price falls back through the level and gains acceptance inside the former range.\n\nThe retest should be evaluated as a zone rather than one exact price.\n\nCryptocurrency markets often move briefly beyond visible levels before reversing.\n\n### Breakout Entry Methods\n\nA breakout strategy can enter in several ways.\n\nAn aggressive entry occurs as price moves through the boundary.\n\nThis provides the earliest participation but the least confirmation.\n\nA closed-candle entry waits for the period to complete beyond the level.\n\nA retest entry waits for price to return to the boundary and demonstrate support or resistance.\n\nA momentum continuation entry waits for the breakout to develop and enters during the next period of acceleration.\n\nEach method creates a different balance between entry quality, confirmation and missed-opportunity risk.\n\n### Aggressive Breakout Entry\n\nAn aggressive entry may be appropriate when:\n\nThe range is well defined\n\nVolatility has compressed\n\nVolume expands\n\nA strong catalyst exists\n\nLiquidity is deep\n\nThe stop can be placed logically\n\nThe primary risk is that the first move is a liquidity sweep or false breakout.\n\nAggressive entries should usually use smaller position sizes or clearly defined stops because the evidence remains incomplete.\n\n### Confirmed Breakout Entry\n\nA confirmed entry waits for stronger evidence such as:\n\nCandle close beyond the level\n\nFollow-through\n\nHigher volume\n\nNew structure outside the range\n\nThis can reduce false-break exposure.\n\nThe entry price may be less favourable and the position may require a wider stop.\n\nA confirmed entry should still be rejected when price has already become excessively extended.\n\n### Retest Entry\n\nA retest entry often provides the clearest structure.\n\nFor a bullish trade, invalidation may lie below the former resistance zone or the retest low.\n\nThe potential target may be based on the next higher-timeframe resistance or a trailing trend rule.\n\nThe principal disadvantage is that the retest may not occur.\n\nThe market does not owe the trader a second opportunity.\n\n### Momentum Continuation Entry\n\nMomentum continuation entries occur after the first breakout impulse.\n\nPrice may consolidate briefly above the old level and then expand again.\n\nThis secondary breakout can confirm that the market is accepting the new area.\n\nHowever, each additional extension increases the risk of entering late.\n\nThe strategy should define how far price may move from the original boundary before the setup is considered overextended.\n\n### Measuring a Breakout Range\n\nSome traders estimate a potential target using the height of the previous range.\n\nSuppose price traded between 80 and 100.\n\nThe range height is:\n\n100 − 80 = 20 units\n\nA simple measured-move target after an upward breakout may be:\n\n100 + 20 = 120 units\n\nAfter a downward breakdown, the target might be:\n\n80 − 20 = 60 units\n\nThis method is a planning tool, not a guaranteed destination.\n\nThe target should also be compared with higher-timeframe resistance, liquidity and market conditions.\n\n### Percentage Targets\n\nA strategy may use a fixed percentage target.\n\nFor example, the trader may seek ten percent after a breakout.\n\nFixed targets are simple but may ignore:\n\nVolatility\n\nRange size\n\nMarket structure\n\nTrend potential\n\nTransaction costs\n\nA ten-percent target may be unrealistic for a low-volatility asset and too small for a highly volatile one.','markdown',NULL,NULL,NULL,6,0,0,0,'',NULL,4,1785297600000 WHERE EXISTS (SELECT 1 FROM `courses` WHERE `id`='cognizen-crypto-mastery-foundations-production');
--> statement-breakpoint
INSERT OR IGNORE INTO `lessons` (`id`,`course_id`,`title`,`section_id`,`lesson_type`,`content`,`content_format`,`video_key`,`primary_asset_id`,`intro_asset_id`,`duration_minutes`,`is_preview`,`available_after_days`,`required_watch_percent`,`transcript`,`experience_json`,`position`,`updated_at`) SELECT 'cmf-module-3-03-lesson-05','cognizen-crypto-mastery-foundations-production','Open-Ended Momentum Exits and Absolute and Relative Breakouts','cmf-module-3-03','text','### Open-Ended Momentum Exits\n\nSome momentum strategies do not use a fixed target.\n\nThey remain in the position while momentum and structure continue.\n\nPossible exit tools include:\n\nTrailing stop\n\nMoving average\n\nPrice channel\n\nStructural higher low or lower high\n\nMomentum deterioration\n\nThis allows participation in unusually large moves.\n\nIt also requires accepting that part of the unrealised profit will be surrendered before exit.\n\n### Initial Invalidation\n\nThe invalidation level should identify where the breakout thesis is no longer credible.\n\nFor a bullish breakout, invalidation may lie:\n\nBelow the breakout zone\n\nBelow the retest low\n\nInside the former range\n\nAt a volatility-adjusted distance\n\nFor a bearish breakdown, the logic is reversed.\n\nA stop placed too close may be triggered by normal volatility.\n\nA stop placed too far away increases capital risk.\n\nThe position size should be calculated after determining the logical stop.\n\n### Breakout Failure Stop\n\nA common rule exits when price closes back inside the former range.\n\nThis reflects the idea that the market failed to accept the breakout area.\n\nThe advantage is logical consistency.\n\nThe disadvantage is that price may briefly return inside the range before continuing.\n\nThe strategy can use:\n\nIntraperiod stop\n\nClosing-price stop\n\nMultiple-close stop\n\nEach method has different speed and false-exit characteristics.\n\n### Volatility-Based Stop\n\nAverage True Range can help define how much movement is normal.\n\nSuppose:\n\nEntry price: 110\n\nBreakout level: 100\n\nATR: 5\n\nStop rule: one ATR below breakout level\n\nThe stop may be placed near 95.\n\nThis provides room below the zone.\n\nThe stop distance is fifteen units from the entry, requiring a smaller position than a stop directly below 100.\n\nVolatility-based stops should be combined with structure rather than applied mechanically.\n\n### Position Sizing\n\nThe standard risk-based formula remains:\n\nPosition size = Maximum capital at risk ÷ Distance to invalidation\n\nSuppose:\n\nTrading capital: 80,000 units\n\nMaximum risk: 0.75 percent\n\nRisk amount: 600 units\n\nEntry: 120\n\nStop: 112\n\nRisk per token: 8\n\nPosition quantity:\n\n600 ÷ 8 = 75 tokens\n\nPosition value:\n\n75 × 120 = 9,000 units\n\nThe position is sized according to possible loss, not expected momentum.\n\n### Breakout Volatility\n\nBreakouts often involve expanding volatility.\n\nThis creates two competing effects.\n\nThe movement may provide greater profit potential.\n\nThe wider price ranges also increase stop distance, slippage and emotional pressure.\n\nPosition size should generally decrease as volatility increases.\n\nA strategy that uses the same token quantity during low and high volatility does not maintain consistent risk.\n\n### Liquidity and Position Size\n\nA breakout can create the appearance of high liquidity because volume rises.\n\nActual order-book depth may remain weak.\n\nThe position should be small enough to exit if the breakout fails.\n\nA trader should examine:\n\nSpread\n\nOrder-book depth\n\nDEX pool size\n\nExpected price impact\n\nVolume quality\n\nBeing able to enter during excitement does not guarantee an efficient exit during reversal.\n\n### Slippage\n\nSlippage often increases during breakout events because many participants attempt to trade simultaneously.\n\nMarket orders may execute at substantially worse prices than expected.\n\nStop orders may also slip during a failed breakout.\n\nA realistic risk calculation should include:\n\nEntry slippage\n\nExit slippage\n\nSpread\n\nFees\n\nFunding\n\nA strategy with a small theoretical advantage can become unprofitable after execution costs.\n\n### Stop-Market Versus Stop-Limit Orders\n\nA stop-market order prioritises execution after the trigger is reached.\n\nIt may fill at a worse price.\n\nA stop-limit order restricts the execution price.\n\nIt may remain unfilled during rapid movement.\n\nFor risk control, failure to exit can be more dangerous than poor execution.\n\nThe correct order type depends on liquidity, volatility and strategy.\n\nNo stop order guarantees the maximum loss.\n\n### Breakout Gaps and Rapid Movement\n\nContinuous cryptocurrency markets do not normally close overnight, but price can still move rapidly through several levels.\n\nThis can happen during:\n\nExchange outages\n\nSecurity events\n\nLiquidation cascades\n\nLow-liquidity periods\n\nSudden regulatory news\n\nA stop can execute far from its trigger or fail on one venue.\n\nPosition size should assume that extreme losses can exceed planned losses.\n\n### Relative Strength\n\nRelative strength compares the performance of one asset with another or with a benchmark.\n\nA cryptocurrency showing strong relative performance during a broad market consolidation may become a higher-quality breakout candidate.\n\nFor example, if the broader market remains flat while one asset repeatedly tests resistance and refuses to decline, demand may be accumulating.\n\nA relative-strength ratio can be calculated as:\n\nAsset price ÷ Benchmark price\n\nA rising ratio means the asset is outperforming the benchmark.\n\n### Absolute and Relative Breakouts\n\nAn asset can break out against a stable quote currency while underperforming Bitcoin.\n\nThis means the asset is rising in absolute terms but losing relative value.\n\nA stronger setup may involve:\n\nBreakout against a stable quote asset\n\nBreakout relative to a major benchmark\n\nRising volume\n\nImproving market structure\n\nRelative confirmation can help identify assets receiving genuine concentrated demand.','markdown',NULL,NULL,NULL,6,0,0,0,'',NULL,5,1785297600000 WHERE EXISTS (SELECT 1 FROM `courses` WHERE `id`='cognizen-crypto-mastery-foundations-production');
--> statement-breakpoint
INSERT OR IGNORE INTO `lessons` (`id`,`course_id`,`title`,`section_id`,`lesson_type`,`content`,`content_format`,`video_key`,`primary_asset_id`,`intro_asset_id`,`duration_minutes`,`is_preview`,`available_after_days`,`required_watch_percent`,`transcript`,`experience_json`,`position`,`updated_at`) SELECT 'cmf-module-3-03-lesson-06','cognizen-crypto-mastery-foundations-production','Sector Momentum and Late Entry Risk','cmf-module-3-03','text','### Sector Momentum\n\nMomentum can develop across a sector.\n\nSeveral related tokens may break out because capital is rotating toward:\n\nLayer 2 networks\n\nDecentralised finance\n\nGaming\n\nArtificial intelligence\n\nTokenised real-world assets\n\nSector momentum can strengthen individual breakouts.\n\nIt also increases correlation.\n\nOwning several tokens from the same narrative may create one concentrated position rather than genuine diversification.\n\n### Market Breadth\n\nMarket breadth measures how widely participation is distributed.\n\nIn cryptocurrency, breadth may examine:\n\nNumber of assets making new highs\n\nPercentage above moving averages\n\nSector participation\n\nAdvancing versus declining assets\n\nA broad market breakout supported by many assets may be more durable than a move driven by one large token.\n\nHowever, speculative phases can produce broad but unsustainable participation.\n\nBreadth provides context rather than certainty.\n\n### Bitcoin Market Context\n\nBitcoin often influences liquidity and sentiment across the digital asset market.\n\nAn altcoin breakout may be vulnerable when Bitcoin is:\n\nBreaking major support\n\nExperiencing a liquidity crisis\n\nShowing extreme volatility\n\nDrawing liquidity away from other assets\n\nAn altcoin may still outperform because of a specific catalyst.\n\nThe breakout should be evaluated within the broader market environment.\n\n### Stablecoin Liquidity\n\nGrowth in stablecoin liquidity can increase available capital for cryptocurrency trading.\n\nContraction may reduce market purchasing power.\n\nA breakout occurring alongside improving stablecoin liquidity may have stronger support.\n\nThe relationship is complex.\n\nStablecoin issuance can reflect:\n\nNew capital\n\nInternal restructuring\n\nCollateral demand\n\nExchange operations\n\nIt should not be interpreted as a direct buy signal.\n\n### Catalyst-Driven Breakouts\n\nA catalyst is an event that changes market expectations.\n\nPossible catalysts include:\n\nNetwork upgrade\n\nProduct launch\n\nRegulatory decision\n\nExchange listing\n\nInstitutional adoption\n\nToken-supply change\n\nMajor partnership\n\nSecurity resolution\n\nA catalyst can create genuine repricing.\n\nIt can also produce temporary excitement followed by profit-taking.\n\nThe participant should determine whether the news changes long-term value or only short-term attention.\n\n### Buy the Rumour, Sell the News\n\nMarkets sometimes rise before an expected event and decline when the event occurs.\n\nParticipants may have bought in anticipation.\n\nWhen the event is confirmed, early buyers take profit.\n\nA breakout immediately before a widely expected announcement may therefore be vulnerable.\n\nThe event itself can be positive while the price declines because expectations were already reflected in the market.\n\n### Unscheduled Events\n\nUnexpected events create the largest information shocks.\n\nExamples include:\n\nExploit\n\nLegal action\n\nLeadership departure\n\nExchange failure\n\nSurprise approval\n\nUnexpected institutional purchase\n\nThese movements can break historical structures immediately.\n\nMomentum can remain strong because the market must rapidly reassess value.\n\nTrading during such events carries high slippage and information risk.\n\n### Momentum Exhaustion\n\nMomentum cannot increase indefinitely.\n\nPossible signs of exhaustion include:\n\nSmaller directional candles\n\nLong rejection wicks\n\nDeclining volume\n\nFailed new highs or lows\n\nDivergence\n\nExtreme funding\n\nRapid final acceleration\n\nLarge liquidation event\n\nInability to hold breakout levels\n\nExhaustion does not guarantee immediate reversal.\n\nPrice may consolidate and continue.\n\nThe strategy should distinguish between slowing momentum and confirmed structural failure.\n\n### Momentum Divergence\n\nMomentum divergence occurs when price reaches a new extreme but an indicator does not.\n\nFor example, price may form a higher high while RSI forms a lower high.\n\nThis can indicate weakening momentum.\n\nA breakout strategy should not exit automatically because of divergence.\n\nDivergence can persist during strong trends.\n\nIt is more useful as a warning to tighten analysis, monitor structure or avoid adding late exposure.\n\n### Blow-Off Moves\n\nA blow-off move is an unusually rapid final acceleration after an extended trend.\n\nIt may involve:\n\nLarge candles\n\nExtreme volume\n\nMedia attention\n\nRetail enthusiasm\n\nHigh leverage\n\nLarge price gaps across venues\n\nThese moves can continue much farther than expected and then reverse violently.\n\nEntering near the end can create severe loss.\n\nShorting too early can be equally dangerous.\n\nThe strategy should avoid treating extreme momentum as either guaranteed continuation or guaranteed reversal.\n\n### Parabolic Movement\n\nParabolic movement occurs when the rate of price increase accelerates.\n\nThe chart begins curving upward rather than rising at a relatively stable rate.\n\nParabolic trends can create exceptional gains.\n\nThey are difficult to manage because ordinary support levels may be far below current price.\n\nTrailing exits and reduced position additions become especially important.\n\nThe later the entry, the greater the risk that a normal correction produces a severe loss.\n\n### Late Entry Risk\n\nA breakout can remain valid while the entry becomes unattractive.\n\nSuppose resistance is at 100 and price rapidly rises to 140.\n\nBuying at 140 may require a stop below 100 or a nearer but less meaningful level.\n\nThe first option creates a very wide risk distance.\n\nThe second increases the chance of being stopped by ordinary volatility.\n\nA disciplined strategy should define a maximum acceptable distance from the breakout level.\n\nMissing the trade may be preferable to entering with poor risk-to-reward.','markdown',NULL,NULL,NULL,6,0,0,0,'',NULL,6,1785297600000 WHERE EXISTS (SELECT 1 FROM `courses` WHERE `id`='cognizen-crypto-mastery-foundations-production');
--> statement-breakpoint
INSERT OR IGNORE INTO `lessons` (`id`,`course_id`,`title`,`section_id`,`lesson_type`,`content`,`content_format`,`video_key`,`primary_asset_id`,`intro_asset_id`,`duration_minutes`,`is_preview`,`available_after_days`,`required_watch_percent`,`transcript`,`experience_json`,`position`,`updated_at`) SELECT 'cmf-module-3-03-lesson-07','cognizen-crypto-mastery-foundations-production','Entry Extension Filter and Breakout Failure as an Opposite Signal','cmf-module-3-03','text','### Entry Extension Filter\n\nAn extension filter may prevent entry when price has moved too far from:\n\nBreakout level\n\nMoving average\n\nVWAP\n\nATR-based threshold\n\nFor example, a strategy may reject entries more than two ATR above the breakout boundary.\n\nThe filter reduces late chasing.\n\nIt may also exclude the strongest momentum events.\n\nThe trade-off should be evaluated through testing.\n\n### Momentum Pullbacks\n\nA strong momentum market may pause briefly before continuing.\n\nA momentum pullback often has:\n\nSmaller candles\n\nLower volume\n\nLimited retracement\n\nSupport above the original breakout\n\nRapid recovery\n\nThis can offer a secondary entry.\n\nA deep, high-volume decline may indicate that momentum has failed rather than paused.\n\n### Flags and Pennants\n\nFlags and pennants are short consolidations that occur after strong movement.\n\nA flag often forms as a small channel against the prior trend.\n\nA pennant forms as a tightening triangular structure.\n\nThe theory is that the market is pausing before continuing.\n\nThe pattern should be evaluated through:\n\nPrior impulse strength\n\nVolume\n\nDepth of pullback\n\nBreakout direction\n\nRisk-to-reward\n\nPattern names do not guarantee continuation.\n\n### Triangles\n\nTriangles form when price compresses between converging boundaries.\n\nAn ascending triangle may show horizontal resistance and rising lows.\n\nA descending triangle may show horizontal support and falling highs.\n\nA symmetrical triangle shows both boundaries converging.\n\nThe breakout direction should be confirmed.\n\nThe apparent shape can fail or break in both directions before a trend develops.\n\n### Rectangle Breakouts\n\nA rectangle is a clear horizontal range.\n\nIt provides:\n\nDefined support\n\nDefined resistance\n\nMeasurable range height\n\nClear failure point\n\nRectangles are attractive for systematic testing because the boundaries are relatively objective.\n\nThe market can still produce false moves beyond both sides.\n\n### Cup-and-Handle and Other Patterns\n\nSome breakout strategies use larger formations such as cup-and-handle structures, bases or rounded consolidations.\n\nThese patterns attempt to describe a transition from selling pressure to accumulation and renewed demand.\n\nThey are subjective.\n\nDifferent analysts may disagree about whether the pattern exists.\n\nThe strategy should focus on observable behaviour:\n\nResistance\n\nPullback quality\n\nVolume\n\nAcceptance\n\nInvalidation\n\nThe name of the pattern is less important than the market evidence.\n\n### All-Time-High Breakouts\n\nA breakout above a previous all-time high places the market into price discovery.\n\nThere is little historical resistance above the level.\n\nPotential advantages include:\n\nStrong attention\n\nShort covering\n\nMomentum participation\n\nNo trapped historical buyers above\n\nPotential risks include:\n\nEuphoria\n\nExcessive valuation\n\nLeverage\n\nBlow-off behaviour\n\nLack of clear targets\n\nA previous all-time high does not guarantee support after the breakout.\n\n### Breakouts From Long-Term Bases\n\nA long-term base can represent months or years of consolidation.\n\nA breakout may signal a significant change in market demand.\n\nHigher-timeframe breakouts often produce fewer signals and wider stop distances.\n\nThey may also create more durable trends.\n\nPosition size should reflect the wider structural risk.\n\n### Intraday Breakouts\n\nIntraday breakouts use shorter timeframes and may occur frequently.\n\nThey are more sensitive to:\n\nExchange-specific activity\n\nSpread\n\nFees\n\nNews\n\nMarket openings in traditional finance\n\nAlgorithmic trading\n\nFalse signals\n\nA strategy profitable before costs may fail after frequent execution expenses.\n\nIntraday momentum requires reliable data and disciplined order management.\n\n### Opening-Range Concepts in a Continuous Market\n\nTraditional markets have formal opening periods.\n\nCryptocurrency trades continuously, but activity still changes around:\n\nRegional trading hours\n\nFutures-market openings\n\nEconomic announcements\n\nDaily funding periods\n\nMajor exchange liquidity windows\n\nA strategy may define an opening range around a selected session.\n\nThe chosen period is conventional and should be applied consistently.\n\n### Weekend and Low-Liquidity Breakouts\n\nCryptocurrency liquidity may differ across days and hours.\n\nA breakout during a low-liquidity period can be easier to create and more vulnerable to reversal.\n\nSpreads may widen and fewer participants may support the move.\n\nA later influx of liquidity can confirm or reverse the breakout.\n\nTime-of-day and day-of-week effects should be tested rather than assumed.\n\n### Exchange-Specific Breakouts\n\nA breakout may occur on one exchange and not another.\n\nPossible reasons include:\n\nDifferent liquidity\n\nStablecoin pricing\n\nRegional users\n\nAbnormal orders\n\nExchange outage\n\nManipulation\n\nA high-quality breakout should ideally appear across several credible markets or on the venue with the greatest genuine liquidity.\n\nThe position must still be executed according to the specific exchange’s order book.\n\n### DEX Breakouts\n\nBreakouts on decentralised exchanges require special caution.\n\nA small liquidity pool can move sharply after one trade.\n\nThe chart may show strong momentum while only limited capital is involved.\n\nReview:\n\nPool depth\n\nPrice impact\n\nHolder concentration\n\nToken taxes\n\nContract restrictions\n\nCross-market confirmation\n\nA technical breakout cannot make a fraudulent token legitimate.\n\n### Breakout Failure as an Opposite Signal\n\nA failed bullish breakout may become a bearish setup.\n\nIf price moves above resistance, attracts buyers and then closes decisively back inside the range, the trapped positioning can fuel a decline.\n\nThe opposite applies to a failed breakdown.\n\nThis is not automatic.\n\nThe market may retest the level several times before choosing direction.\n\nAn opposite trade requires its own entry, stop and evidence.','markdown',NULL,NULL,NULL,6,0,0,0,'',NULL,7,1785297600000 WHERE EXISTS (SELECT 1 FROM `courses` WHERE `id`='cognizen-crypto-mastery-foundations-production');
--> statement-breakpoint
INSERT OR IGNORE INTO `lessons` (`id`,`course_id`,`title`,`section_id`,`lesson_type`,`content`,`content_format`,`video_key`,`primary_asset_id`,`intro_asset_id`,`duration_minutes`,`is_preview`,`available_after_days`,`required_watch_percent`,`transcript`,`experience_json`,`position`,`updated_at`) SELECT 'cmf-module-3-03-lesson-08','cognizen-crypto-mastery-foundations-production','Stop-and-Reverse Strategies and Spot Momentum Trading','cmf-module-3-03','text','### Stop-and-Reverse Strategies\n\nA stop-and-reverse system changes direction when one breakout fails and the opposite boundary breaks.\n\nFor example:\n\nEnter long above resistance\n\nExit when price returns into the range\n\nEnter short if support later breaks\n\nThis allows the strategy to adapt.\n\nIt can also create repeated losses in chaotic markets.\n\nThe method should define whether immediate reversal is permitted or whether new confirmation is required.\n\n### Breakout Strategy Win Rate\n\nBreakout strategies may have moderate or relatively low win rates.\n\nMany ranges produce false moves before a genuine trend begins.\n\nProfitability may depend on allowing successful breakouts to produce gains larger than the losses from failed attempts.\n\nA system that takes profit too quickly and allows false breakouts to lose too much can have negative expectancy.\n\n### Positive Skew\n\nMomentum and breakout strategies often seek positive skew.\n\nThis means:\n\nLosses are limited\n\nMany trades produce small outcomes\n\nSome trades develop into very large winners\n\nThe strategy’s long-term result may depend heavily on a small number of successful trends.\n\nMissing one large winner can materially affect performance.\n\nThis is why consistent execution matters.\n\n### Expectancy\n\nExpectancy combines win probability with average profit and loss.\n\nSuppose:\n\nWin rate: 40 percent\n\nAverage winner: 3.5 units\n\nLoss rate: 60 percent\n\nAverage loser: 1 unit\n\nExpected value:\n\n0.40 × 3.5 − 0.60 × 1\n\n1.40 − 0.60 = positive 0.80 units\n\nThe strategy loses more often than it wins but remains positive before costs.\n\n### Small Winners and Large Losses\n\nA breakout strategy can fail even with a high win rate if it takes profits too early and allows failed breakouts to grow.\n\nSuppose:\n\nWin rate: 70 percent\n\nAverage win: 100 units\n\nLoss rate: 30 percent\n\nAverage loss: 300 units\n\nExpected value:\n\n0.70 × 100 − 0.30 × 300\n\n70 − 90 = negative 20 units\n\nWin rate should never be analysed alone.\n\n### Re-Entry\n\nA breakout may fail, return to the range and later break out successfully.\n\nA systematic strategy may need to re-enter after a new valid signal.\n\nThis can be emotionally difficult.\n\nThe participant may feel that the market already proved the setup wrong.\n\nThe first signal failed. The second signal is a new event.\n\nRefusing every re-entry can cause the strategy to miss the genuine trend after several false starts.\n\nUnlimited re-entry can also create excessive losses.\n\nA strategy may define a maximum number of attempts or require additional confirmation.\n\n### Pyramiding\n\nPyramiding adds to a profitable momentum position as the trend confirms itself.\n\nA disciplined approach may add after:\n\nNew structural high\n\nSuccessful pullback\n\nSecondary breakout\n\nReduced portfolio risk through a raised stop\n\nEach addition should be smaller or risk-controlled.\n\nThe strategy should calculate total exposure after every addition.\n\nPyramiding increases participation in successful trends but can create excessive concentration late in the movement.\n\n### Adding to Losing Breakouts\n\nAdding after a breakout fails usually increases exposure to invalidated evidence.\n\nThe participant may believe that the lower price offers better value.\n\nThis changes the strategy from momentum to mean reversion without a deliberate decision.\n\nA failed breakout position should normally follow its predefined exit rule.\n\nIf the trader wants to adopt a mean-reversion thesis, it should be treated as a separate analysis and position.\n\n### Portfolio Heat\n\nBreakout signals often occur across many assets simultaneously.\n\nA broad market move may trigger long positions in several cryptocurrencies.\n\nAlthough each signal appears separate, they may all depend on one risk factor: continued digital asset market strength.\n\nPortfolio heat measures total planned loss across open positions.\n\nA strategy should limit:\n\nTotal open risk\n\nSector risk\n\nEcosystem risk\n\nExchange risk\n\nStablecoin collateral risk\n\n### Correlation\n\nCorrelations often increase during market stress.\n\nSeveral breakout positions can fail simultaneously.\n\nA portfolio containing five positions each risking one percent may lose more than five percent if:\n\nStops slip\n\nLiquidity disappears\n\nMarkets gap\n\nAll positions depend on the same catalyst\n\nRisk should be measured at both position and portfolio levels.\n\n### Leverage\n\nLeverage can make momentum trading appear highly profitable during strong trends.\n\nIt also increases:\n\nLiquidation risk\n\nFunding cost\n\nEmotional pressure\n\nSensitivity to ordinary pullbacks\n\nExchange dependence\n\nA momentum trader can be correct about the broader direction and still be liquidated during a short-term correction.\n\nThe position should be sized from acceptable loss, not maximum leverage available.\n\n### Spot Momentum Trading\n\nSpot trading avoids forced liquidation when no borrowing is involved.\n\nThe participant still faces:\n\nMarket loss\n\nExchange risk\n\nToken failure\n\nSlippage\n\nCustody risk\n\nSpot strategies may be more suitable for longer breakout horizons because they can tolerate larger corrections without automatic liquidation.','markdown',NULL,NULL,NULL,6,0,0,0,'',NULL,8,1785297600000 WHERE EXISTS (SELECT 1 FROM `courses` WHERE `id`='cognizen-crypto-mastery-foundations-production');
--> statement-breakpoint
INSERT OR IGNORE INTO `lessons` (`id`,`course_id`,`title`,`section_id`,`lesson_type`,`content`,`content_format`,`video_key`,`primary_asset_id`,`intro_asset_id`,`duration_minutes`,`is_preview`,`available_after_days`,`required_watch_percent`,`transcript`,`experience_json`,`position`,`updated_at`) SELECT 'cmf-module-3-03-lesson-09','cognizen-crypto-mastery-foundations-production','Derivative Momentum Trading and Look-Ahead Bias','cmf-module-3-03','text','### Derivative Momentum Trading\n\nFutures and perpetual contracts allow:\n\nLong exposure\n\nShort exposure\n\nLeverage\n\nCapital efficiency\n\nThey also introduce:\n\nFunding\n\nBasis\n\nLiquidation\n\nMargin requirements\n\nCounterparty risk\n\nThe breakout signal may be identical, but the instrument changes the loss distribution substantially.\n\n### Options and Breakouts\n\nOptions can be used to express a breakout view with predefined maximum loss.\n\nA call option may provide bullish exposure.\n\nA put option may provide bearish exposure.\n\nHowever, options introduce:\n\nPremium cost\n\nTime decay\n\nImplied volatility\n\nStrike selection\n\nExpiry\n\nLiquidity risk\n\nBuying options immediately after volatility has expanded can be expensive.\n\nOptions strategies will be covered later in Course 3.\n\n### Implied Volatility Around Breakouts\n\nExpected volatility often rises near major events or after large price movement.\n\nIf an options trader buys after implied volatility has already increased substantially, the underlying asset may move in the expected direction while the option still underperforms.\n\nThe cost of the instrument matters as much as the directional view.\n\n### Breakout Failure During News\n\nNews-driven breakouts can reverse when:\n\nThe information was already expected\n\nDetails are weaker than headlines suggest\n\nEarly participants take profit\n\nLiquidity is temporary\n\nThe broader market rejects the event\n\nA headline should not replace analysis of price acceptance.\n\n### Fundamental Confirmation\n\nA breakout may be more durable when supported by evidence such as:\n\nRising network usage\n\nImproving protocol revenue\n\nReduced token supply\n\nStrong developer activity\n\nRegulatory clarity\n\nMeaningful institutional participation\n\nFundamentals can support the trend.\n\nThey do not guarantee that the current price is reasonable.\n\nA positive project development can still produce a poor entry after an excessive rally.\n\n### On-Chain Confirmation\n\nPossible on-chain information may include:\n\nExchange outflows\n\nActive addresses\n\nTransaction fees\n\nRealised gains and losses\n\nLong-term holder behaviour\n\nStablecoin liquidity\n\nWhale accumulation\n\nThese metrics may help evaluate whether the breakout has broader support.\n\nOn-chain data can be delayed, ambiguous or manipulated through wallet activity.\n\nIt should support rather than replace market structure.\n\n### Breakout and Momentum Screening\n\nA screening process can identify assets meeting predefined criteria.\n\nPossible variables include:\n\nNew multi-period high\n\nRising relative volume\n\nPositive moving-average slope\n\nHigh relative strength\n\nVolatility expansion\n\nMinimum liquidity\n\nAcceptable spread\n\nNo major adverse event\n\nScreening improves efficiency.\n\nIt does not complete the analysis.\n\nEach candidate still requires review of structure, token risk, liquidity and position size.\n\n### Systematic Breakout Strategy\n\nA systematic strategy uses explicit rules.\n\nAn educational example may state:\n\nEligible assets must meet minimum liquidity requirements\n\nPrice must close above the highest close of the previous fifty periods\n\nRelative volume must exceed a defined threshold\n\nHigher-timeframe moving average must be rising\n\nInitial stop is based on recent structure or ATR\n\nRisk per position is fixed\n\nExit follows a shorter-period low or trailing stop\n\nThis framework can be tested objectively.\n\nThe exact settings are not universal.\n\n### Discretionary Momentum Strategy\n\nA discretionary strategy may consider:\n\nQuality of consolidation\n\nCatalyst\n\nSector strength\n\nVolume\n\nOrder flow\n\nDerivatives positioning\n\nRelative strength\n\nBroader market conditions\n\nThe participant has flexibility but faces greater behavioural risk.\n\nThey may interpret weak evidence as strong because they want the trade.\n\nA discretionary process should still document minimum requirements and invalidation.\n\n### Hybrid Strategy\n\nA hybrid strategy may use systematic screening and discretionary execution.\n\nFor example:\n\nA model identifies assets making new highs on strong volume\n\nThe analyst reviews liquidity, token unlocks and market context\n\nThe position size follows a fixed risk formula\n\nThe exit follows an objective trailing rule\n\nThis combines consistency with contextual judgement.\n\nThe discretionary component should not become an excuse to ignore losing signals.\n\n### Breakout Backtesting\n\nA breakout backtest should include:\n\nExact range or high-low definition\n\nClosing or intraperiod trigger\n\nEntry delay\n\nStop\n\nExit\n\nPosition size\n\nFees\n\nSlippage\n\nRe-entry rules\n\nAsset selection\n\nDelistings\n\nFunding where relevant\n\nKey metrics include:\n\nWin rate\n\nAverage winner\n\nAverage loser\n\nProfit factor\n\nExpectancy\n\nMaximum drawdown\n\nLongest losing streak\n\nTurnover\n\nTime in market\n\nPerformance by regime\n\n### Intrabar Bias\n\nA backtest may assume that a breakout and stop occurred in a favourable order within the same candle.\n\nUsing only candle data may not reveal which happened first.\n\nThis can produce unrealistic results.\n\nMore detailed data or conservative assumptions may be needed.\n\n### Look-Ahead Bias\n\nLook-ahead bias can occur when the strategy uses information unavailable at entry.\n\nExamples include:\n\nEntering at the breakout candle’s close before the close was known\n\nUsing final daily volume during the middle of the day\n\nSelecting assets known later to survive\n\nDrawing resistance with future price information\n\nThe test must reproduce the information actually available at the decision time.','markdown',NULL,NULL,NULL,6,0,0,0,'',NULL,9,1785297600000 WHERE EXISTS (SELECT 1 FROM `courses` WHERE `id`='cognizen-crypto-mastery-foundations-production');
--> statement-breakpoint
INSERT OR IGNORE INTO `lessons` (`id`,`course_id`,`title`,`section_id`,`lesson_type`,`content`,`content_format`,`video_key`,`primary_asset_id`,`intro_asset_id`,`duration_minutes`,`is_preview`,`available_after_days`,`required_watch_percent`,`transcript`,`experience_json`,`position`,`updated_at`) SELECT 'cmf-module-3-03-lesson-10','cognizen-crypto-mastery-foundations-production','Survivorship Bias and Example: Short Squeeze','cmf-module-3-03','text','### Survivorship Bias\n\nA strategy tested only on current successful cryptocurrencies excludes:\n\nFailed tokens\n\nDelistings\n\nRug pulls\n\nLiquidity collapses\n\nAbandoned projects\n\nBreakout strategies can perform especially poorly in assets that experience one final promotional rally before failure.\n\nA realistic test should include unsuccessful markets where data is available.\n\n### Slippage Modelling\n\nBreakout entries often occur when price is moving rapidly.\n\nUsing the exact trigger price in a backtest is often unrealistic.\n\nThe model should include:\n\nSpread\n\nEntry slippage\n\nExit slippage\n\nLarger costs during volatility\n\nPosition size relative to volume\n\nA system that depends on perfect execution may not be tradable.\n\n### Out-of-Sample Testing\n\nThe strategy should be developed on one data sample and evaluated on another.\n\nIt should also be tested across:\n\nBull markets\n\nBear markets\n\nSideways markets\n\nHigh-volatility periods\n\nSeveral liquid assets\n\nStrong performance in one trending period does not demonstrate robustness.\n\n### Paper Trading and Small Live Testing\n\nPaper trading can test signal generation and operational discipline.\n\nSmall live testing reveals:\n\nReal fills\n\nSlippage\n\nFees\n\nEmotional response\n\nExchange reliability\n\nData delays\n\nA strategy should not move directly from an attractive historical backtest to large capital.\n\n### Strategy Monitoring\n\nAfter deployment, monitor:\n\nSignal frequency\n\nFalse-break rate\n\nAverage slippage\n\nWin rate\n\nAverage payoff\n\nDrawdown\n\nRe-entry performance\n\nMarket-regime sensitivity\n\nRule violations\n\nPerformance deterioration may result from:\n\nMarket regime change\n\nGreater competition\n\nLower liquidity\n\nHigher costs\n\nOverfitting\n\nExecution problems\n\n### Breakout Decision Journal\n\nA journal entry may record:\n\nAsset\n\nTimeframe\n\nBreakout level\n\nRange duration\n\nRange width\n\nVolatility condition\n\nVolume\n\nRelative strength\n\nCatalyst\n\nEntry method\n\nInvalidation\n\nPosition size\n\nPortfolio heat\n\nExit method\n\nActual result\n\nRule deviations\n\nThe journal helps determine whether losses come from normal false breakouts or poor execution.\n\n### Basic Breakout Framework\n\nThe following is an educational example and not a recommendation.\n\n### Market Selection\n\nOnly liquid digital assets with reliable data and sufficient market depth are considered.\n\n### Structure\n\nPrice must consolidate below clearly identified resistance.\n\nThe range should show declining or stable volatility rather than chaotic movement.\n\n### Confirmation\n\nA valid signal requires a closed candle above the resistance zone and increased participation.\n\n### Entry\n\nThe position may be entered at the close, on the next period or after a successful retest.\n\n### Invalidation\n\nThe setup fails if price closes materially back inside the range or breaks below the retest low.\n\n### Position Size\n\nRisk is calculated from the distance between entry and invalidation.\n\n### Exit\n\nThe position is managed using a trailing structural or volatility-based stop.\n\nThis framework must be tested before use.\n\n### Example: Confirmed Breakout\n\nSuppose an asset has traded between 40 and 50 for several weeks.\n\nVolatility has declined, and resistance at 50 has been tested repeatedly.\n\nPrice closes at 52 on volume twice the recent average.\n\nThe trader plans:\n\nEntry: 52\n\nStop: 47\n\nRisk per token: 5\n\nMaximum capital risk: 500 units\n\nPosition quantity:\n\n500 ÷ 5 = 100 tokens\n\nPosition value:\n\n100 × 52 = 5,200 units\n\nThe range height is ten units, producing a possible measured target near 60.\n\nThe strategy may instead use a trailing exit if momentum remains strong.\n\n### Example: False Breakout\n\nSuppose price trades above resistance at 100 and reaches 104 during the day.\n\nIt closes at 98 with a long upper wick and unusually high volume.\n\nThe move may represent rejection rather than acceptance.\n\nA breakout entry taken intraday may reach its stop.\n\nA strategy requiring a close beyond resistance would avoid the trade.\n\nThat filter may also miss some fast breakouts that never wait for confirmation.\n\n### Example: Retest Entry\n\nSuppose price closes above resistance at 200 and reaches 220.\n\nIt later returns to 202 on declining volume.\n\nBuyers respond, and price closes at 208.\n\nThe trader enters at 209 with invalidation below the retest low at 198.\n\nRisk per token:\n\n209 − 198 = 11\n\nThe retest provides a clearer risk reference than buying at 220.\n\nThe breakout can still fail.\n\n### Example: Late Momentum Entry\n\nSuppose resistance is at 80.\n\nPrice breaks out and rises to 120 in three days.\n\nA trader enters at 118 because the momentum appears strong.\n\nThe nearest meaningful structural invalidation remains near 80 or the latest short-term low near 108.\n\nA stop near 108 may be vulnerable to ordinary volatility.\n\nA stop near 80 creates an excessive risk distance.\n\nThe trend may continue, but the entry quality is poor.\n\nThe correct decision may be to wait or not participate.\n\n### Example: Short Squeeze\n\nSuppose price breaks above long-term resistance while open interest is high and funding is negative.\n\nShort positions are crowded.\n\nAs price rises, short liquidations accelerate buying.\n\nThe move becomes extremely strong.\n\nLater, open interest falls sharply and funding becomes strongly positive.\n\nThe squeeze may be nearing exhaustion as short positions have already closed and new leveraged longs enter.\n\nThe data does not identify the exact top, but it changes the risk profile.','markdown',NULL,NULL,NULL,6,0,0,0,'',NULL,10,1785297600000 WHERE EXISTS (SELECT 1 FROM `courses` WHERE `id`='cognizen-crypto-mastery-foundations-production');
--> statement-breakpoint
INSERT OR IGNORE INTO `lessons` (`id`,`course_id`,`title`,`section_id`,`lesson_type`,`content`,`content_format`,`video_key`,`primary_asset_id`,`intro_asset_id`,`duration_minutes`,`is_preview`,`available_after_days`,`required_watch_percent`,`transcript`,`experience_json`,`position`,`updated_at`) SELECT 'cmf-module-3-03-lesson-11','cognizen-crypto-mastery-foundations-production','Breakout and Momentum Checklist and Module Summary','cmf-module-3-03','text','### Breakout and Momentum Checklist\n\nBefore entering, ask:\n\nWhich level or structure is breaking?\n\nIs the boundary clear and widely relevant?\n\nHow long did the consolidation last?\n\nWas volatility contracting before the move?\n\nHas the candle closed beyond the level?\n\nIs the market accepting the new price area?\n\nDoes volume support the breakout?\n\nIs the volume genuine?\n\nIs spot demand participating?\n\nWhat is happening to open interest?\n\nAre liquidations driving the move?\n\nIs funding becoming extreme?\n\nDoes the asset show relative strength?\n\nIs the broader market supportive?\n\nIs a catalyst involved?\n\nHas the catalyst already been priced in?\n\nIs the move excessively extended?\n\nWhich entry method will be used?\n\nWhat invalidates the breakout?\n\nWhere is the stop?\n\nWhat slippage may occur?\n\nWhat position size follows from the risk?\n\nWhat is the total portfolio heat?\n\nAre several positions highly correlated?\n\nIs leverage necessary?\n\nWhat funding and borrowing costs apply?\n\nWill the strategy use a fixed target or trailing exit?\n\nIs re-entry permitted after a false breakout?\n\nHas the method been tested after realistic costs?\n\nAm I following a defined signal or chasing excitement?\n\n### Common Breakout and Momentum Mistakes\n\nThe first major error is treating every movement beyond resistance or support as confirmation. A level can be crossed without the market accepting the new area.\n\nAnother common mistake is entering after price has already moved far from the breakout zone. The trend may remain valid, but the risk-to-reward may no longer justify participation.\n\nSome participants ignore volume quality and liquidity. A dramatic chart movement in a shallow token may represent one large order rather than broad demand.\n\nOthers use excessive leverage because the price movement appears powerful. Ordinary pullbacks can then cause liquidation even when the longer-term breakout succeeds.\n\nA further mistake is taking profits too quickly while allowing failed breakouts to produce large losses. This reverses the positive-skew profile that many momentum strategies require.\n\nFinally, traders may refuse to re-enter after one false breakout. Re-entry can be emotionally difficult, but the next signal should be evaluated independently according to the strategy rules.\n\n### Common Misunderstandings\n\n#### “A Break Above Resistance Confirms a New Trend”\n\nThe market must demonstrate acceptance and follow-through.\n\n#### “High Volume Is Always Bullish”\n\nHigh volume can reflect distribution, liquidations or a failed breakout.\n\n#### “Momentum Means the Asset Is Fundamentally Strong”\n\nMomentum describes price behaviour, not underlying value.\n\n#### “A Retest Must Occur”\n\nSome breakouts continue without returning to the original level.\n\n#### “A Strong Breakout Is Safe to Chase”\n\nLate entries can have poor invalidation and excessive downside.\n\n#### “Extreme Funding Means the Market Must Reverse”\n\nCrowded conditions can continue for longer than expected.\n\n#### “Rising Open Interest Confirms Healthy Demand”\n\nIt may reflect fragile leveraged positioning.\n\n#### “A False Breakout Makes the Opposite Trade Automatic”\n\nThe reversal requires its own confirmation and risk plan.\n\n#### “Leverage Improves a Good Momentum Strategy”\n\nIt increases both return potential and the chance of liquidation during normal volatility.\n\n#### “More Breakout Filters Always Improve Results”\n\nFilters can reduce false signals while delaying or missing successful moves.\n\n#### “A Backtest Using Current Successful Tokens Is Reliable”\n\nIt may exclude failed and delisted assets.\n\n#### “Missing a Breakout Is a Financial Loss”\n\nNot participating in an unsuitable entry preserves capital for another opportunity.\n\n### Module Summary\n\nBreakout strategies attempt to participate when price leaves an established range, support area or resistance zone.\n\nMomentum strategies attempt to benefit from strong and persistent directional movement.\n\nA breakout becomes more credible when the market demonstrates acceptance beyond the former boundary.\n\nUseful evidence may include:\n\nClosed candles beyond the level\n\nFollow-through\n\nRising relative volume\n\nVolatility expansion\n\nStrong relative performance\n\nA successful retest\n\nBroad market participation\n\nFalse breakouts occur when price moves beyond a level but rapidly returns.\n\nLiquidity sweeps can trigger clustered orders beyond visible boundaries before price reverses.\n\nBreakout entries may be aggressive, confirmed, retest-based or momentum-continuation entries.\n\nEarlier entries offer better prices but less confirmation.\n\nLater entries offer more evidence but may suffer poor risk-to-reward and extension risk.\n\nDerivatives information can provide additional context.\n\nRising open interest may indicate new leveraged participation.\n\nFunding rates can reveal crowded positioning.\n\nLiquidations can accelerate breakouts and breakdowns but may also create exhaustion.\n\nMomentum strategies often depend on positive skew. Several small failed signals may be offset by a smaller number of large directional moves.\n\nThis requires:\n\nStrict invalidation\n\nControlled position size\n\nConsistent re-entry rules\n\nPatience with profitable positions\n\nLimits on portfolio heat and correlation\n\nA valid breakout does not guarantee a good entry.\n\nThe participant must evaluate structure, liquidity, volatility, execution cost and distance from the invalidation point.\n\nThe objective is not to buy simply because price is moving.\n\nIt is to participate only when movement is supported by sufficient evidence and when failure remains financially manageable.','markdown',NULL,NULL,NULL,6,0,0,0,'',NULL,11,1785297600000 WHERE EXISTS (SELECT 1 FROM `courses` WHERE `id`='cognizen-crypto-mastery-foundations-production');
--> statement-breakpoint
INSERT OR IGNORE INTO `lessons` (`id`,`course_id`,`title`,`section_id`,`lesson_type`,`content`,`content_format`,`video_key`,`primary_asset_id`,`intro_asset_id`,`duration_minutes`,`is_preview`,`available_after_days`,`required_watch_percent`,`transcript`,`experience_json`,`position`,`updated_at`) SELECT 'cmf-module-3-03-lesson-12','cognizen-crypto-mastery-foundations-production','Key Takeaway','cmf-module-3-03','text','### Key Takeaway\n\nA breakout is not confirmed simply because price crosses a visible line.\n\nThe market must show that it can remain beyond the level and attract enough genuine participation to support continued movement.\n\nMomentum can produce exceptional opportunities, but it also creates urgency, leverage and late-entry risk.\n\nWait for the evidence required by your strategy, define where the breakout has failed and size the position so that a false move remains an ordinary loss rather than a portfolio-threatening event.\n\nThe next module is 3.4: Market Regimes and Strategy Selection.','markdown',NULL,NULL,NULL,1,0,0,0,'',NULL,12,1785297600000 WHERE EXISTS (SELECT 1 FROM `courses` WHERE `id`='cognizen-crypto-mastery-foundations-production');
--> statement-breakpoint
INSERT OR IGNORE INTO `lessons` (`id`,`course_id`,`title`,`section_id`,`lesson_type`,`content`,`content_format`,`video_key`,`primary_asset_id`,`intro_asset_id`,`duration_minutes`,`is_preview`,`available_after_days`,`required_watch_percent`,`transcript`,`experience_json`,`position`,`updated_at`) SELECT 'cmf-module-3-03-lesson-13','cognizen-crypto-mastery-foundations-production','Check your understanding','cmf-module-3-03','text','### Check your understanding\n\nAnswer these questions to self-assess your understanding before moving on.\n\n1. What is a breakout?\n\n2. What is a breakdown?\n\n3. How does momentum differ from a structural breakout?\n\n4. Why can consolidation precede a strong move?\n\n5. What is volatility compression?\n\n6. What does market acceptance mean?\n\n7. How does rejection differ from acceptance?\n\n8. What is a false breakout?\n\n9. What is a liquidity sweep?\n\n10. Why may a closed-candle signal be more reliable than an intraperiod move?\n\n11. What trade-off comes with waiting for confirmation?\n\n12. How can breakout distance be adjusted for volatility?\n\n13. What candle characteristics may support a breakout?\n\n14. How can relative volume improve analysis?\n\n15. Why is high volume not automatically bullish?\n\n16. How does spot volume differ from derivatives volume?\n\n17. What does rising open interest indicate?\n\n18. How can a short squeeze accelerate an upward breakout?\n\n19. How can long liquidations accelerate a breakdown?\n\n20. What information does the funding rate provide?\n\n21. What is a breakout retest?\n\n22. What evidence may indicate a successful retest?\n\n23. How does an aggressive entry differ from a confirmed entry?\n\n24. What are the benefits and limitations of a retest entry?\n\n25. What is a measured-move target?\n\n26. Why may an open-ended trailing exit suit momentum strategies?\n\n27. What should define breakout invalidation?\n\n28. Why should position size decline as volatility rises?\n\n29. How can slippage affect a breakout trade?\n\n30. Why can stop-limit orders fail to protect a position?\n\n31. What is relative strength?\n\n32. How can sector momentum create hidden concentration?\n\n33. What is market breadth?\n\n34. How can Bitcoin’s trend affect an altcoin breakout?\n\n35. What is a catalyst-driven breakout?\n\n36. What does “buy the rumour, sell the news” describe?\n\n37. What signs may indicate momentum exhaustion?\n\n38. What is a blow-off move?\n\n39. Why is a parabolic move difficult to manage?\n\n40. What is late-entry risk?\n\n41. What is an extension filter?\n\n42. How does a momentum pullback differ from a failed breakout?\n\n43. What is a flag or pennant?\n\n44. Why are chart-pattern names insufficient by themselves?\n\n45. What is price discovery?\n\n46. Why may low-liquidity breakouts be unreliable?\n\n47. How can a failed breakout become an opposite-direction setup?\n\n48. What is re-entry?\n\n49. Why do breakout strategies often have positive skew?\n\n50. How is expectancy calculated?\n\n51. What is pyramiding?\n\n52. Why is adding to a failed breakout dangerous?\n\n53. What is portfolio heat?\n\n54. Why should correlated breakout signals be grouped together?\n\n55. What additional risks arise when derivatives are used?\n\n56. What should a breakout backtest include?\n\n57. What is intrabar bias?\n\n58. How can survivorship bias exaggerate performance?\n\n59. Why must breakout backtests include slippage?\n\n60. What should be recorded in a breakout decision journal?','markdown',NULL,NULL,NULL,6,0,0,0,'',NULL,13,1785297600000 WHERE EXISTS (SELECT 1 FROM `courses` WHERE `id`='cognizen-crypto-mastery-foundations-production');
--> statement-breakpoint
INSERT OR IGNORE INTO `course_sections` (`id`,`course_id`,`title`,`position`,`created_at`) SELECT 'cmf-module-3-04','cognizen-crypto-mastery-foundations-production','Module 3.4: Market Regimes and Strategy Selection',5,1785297600000 WHERE EXISTS (SELECT 1 FROM `courses` WHERE `id`='cognizen-crypto-mastery-foundations-production');
--> statement-breakpoint
INSERT OR IGNORE INTO `lessons` (`id`,`course_id`,`title`,`section_id`,`lesson_type`,`content`,`content_format`,`video_key`,`primary_asset_id`,`intro_asset_id`,`duration_minutes`,`is_preview`,`available_after_days`,`required_watch_percent`,`transcript`,`experience_json`,`position`,`updated_at`) SELECT 'cmf-module-3-04-lesson-01','cognizen-crypto-mastery-foundations-production','What Is a Market Regime? and Directional Regimes','cmf-module-3-04','text','### Learning Objectives\n\nBy the end of this module, you should understand what a market regime is and why no trading or investment strategy performs equally well in every environment. You should be able to distinguish between trending, ranging, high-volatility, low-volatility, risk-on and risk-off conditions.\n\nYou should also be able to use price structure, volatility, liquidity, volume, market breadth, derivatives positioning and broader financial conditions to form a regime assessment. Most importantly, you should be able to match an appropriate strategy to the current environment, reduce exposure when the evidence is uncertain and recognise when a market is transitioning from one regime to another.\n\n---\n\n### Introduction\n\nA strategy can be logically designed, historically profitable and executed exactly according to plan—and still experience a prolonged period of losses.\n\nThis does not always mean the strategy is defective.\n\nIt may mean the market environment has changed.\n\nA trend-following strategy can perform well when prices move persistently in one direction. The same strategy may produce repeated false signals when the market becomes sideways.\n\nA mean-reversion strategy may perform consistently inside a stable range. It can suffer severe losses when the range breaks and a powerful trend develops.\n\nA breakout strategy may capture substantial gains when volatility expands after consolidation. It may lose repeatedly when every movement beyond support or resistance is rejected.\n\nThese differences arise because strategies are usually designed to exploit particular forms of market behaviour.\n\nThat broader market behaviour is known as a **market regime**.\n\nA market regime is not simply whether price is rising or falling. It includes the way price moves, the amount of volatility, the strength of liquidity, the degree of correlation between assets and the willingness of participants to accept risk.\n\nAdvanced strategy selection therefore begins with a different question.\n\nInstead of asking only:\n\n**What signal is present?**\n\nThe participant asks:\n\n**What type of market is producing this signal, and is my strategy designed for that environment?**\n\n---\n\n### What Is a Market Regime?\n\nA market regime is a period during which a collection of market characteristics remains sufficiently consistent to influence how strategies behave.\n\nThese characteristics may include direction, volatility, liquidity, market participation, correlation, leverage and investor risk appetite.\n\nA bullish trend with low volatility is a different regime from a bullish trend driven by highly leveraged speculation.\n\nBoth markets are rising, but they do not carry the same risk.\n\nSimilarly, a quiet sideways range differs from a violent sideways market in which price repeatedly moves sharply in both directions.\n\nA useful regime assessment should therefore examine more than direction alone.\n\nThe market may be described along several dimensions:\n\n- Is price trending or ranging?\n- Is volatility expanding or contracting?\n- Is liquidity deep or fragile?\n- Is participation broad or concentrated?\n- Are assets moving independently or becoming highly correlated?\n- Is leverage building or being removed?\n- Are investors seeking or avoiding risk?\n\nThe combination of these conditions determines which strategies may be appropriate.\n\n---\n\n### Regimes Are Simplifications\n\nA regime label is a model used to organise complex market behaviour.\n\nThe market itself does not announce:\n\n“This is now a low-volatility accumulation regime.”\n\nAnalysts observe evidence and assign a description.\n\nDifferent participants may classify the same market differently because they use different:\n\n- Timeframes\n- Indicators\n- Benchmarks\n- Holding periods\n- Risk objectives\n\nA weekly investor may view a decline as a correction within a bull regime.\n\nAn hourly trader may experience the same decline as a strong bearish trend.\n\nBoth interpretations can be valid within their respective timeframes.\n\nRegime classification should therefore be treated as a working hypothesis rather than an absolute truth.\n\n---\n\n### Directional Regimes\n\nThe most familiar market regimes are based on price direction.\n\nA market may be in an upward trend, downward trend or sideways range.\n\nAn upward-trending regime generally produces higher highs and higher lows. Pullbacks attract buyers, resistance levels break and price remains above rising long-term averages.\n\nA downward-trending regime generally creates lower highs and lower lows. Recoveries attract selling, support levels fail and price remains below falling long-term averages.\n\nA sideways regime develops when neither buyers nor sellers maintain directional control. Price repeatedly returns toward a central area after testing support or resistance.\n\nDirection is important, but it does not explain the complete quality of the market.\n\nA gradual uptrend and a parabolic rally require different risk controls, even though both are bullish.\n\n---','markdown',NULL,NULL,NULL,6,0,0,0,'',NULL,1,1785297600000 WHERE EXISTS (SELECT 1 FROM `courses` WHERE `id`='cognizen-crypto-mastery-foundations-production');
--> statement-breakpoint
INSERT OR IGNORE INTO `lessons` (`id`,`course_id`,`title`,`section_id`,`lesson_type`,`content`,`content_format`,`video_key`,`primary_asset_id`,`intro_asset_id`,`duration_minutes`,`is_preview`,`available_after_days`,`required_watch_percent`,`transcript`,`experience_json`,`position`,`updated_at`) SELECT 'cmf-module-3-04-lesson-02','cognizen-crypto-mastery-foundations-production','Volatility Regimes and Speculative or Parabolic Bull Regime','cmf-module-3-04','text','### Volatility Regimes\n\nVolatility describes the scale and speed of price movement.\n\nA low-volatility regime may contain narrow candles, declining average true range and contracting Bollinger Bands. Price changes are relatively limited, and market participants appear to agree more closely about value.\n\nA high-volatility regime contains larger price ranges, wider spreads and more rapid changes. It may develop during:\n\n- Breakouts\n- Liquidation cascades\n- Regulatory events\n- Security incidents\n- Market panic\n- Speculative euphoria\n\nVolatility can rise in either direction.\n\nA market may experience high-volatility gains, high-volatility losses or violent movement without sustained direction.\n\nA strategy must distinguish volatility from trend.\n\nLarge movement does not necessarily mean persistent movement.\n\n---\n\n### Liquidity Regimes\n\nLiquidity describes how easily assets can be traded near the expected price.\n\nDuring a strong-liquidity regime, order books are deep, spreads are relatively narrow and large transactions can occur with limited price impact.\n\nDuring a weak-liquidity regime, orders disappear, spreads widen and relatively small trades can move price significantly.\n\nLiquidity frequently deteriorates during market stress.\n\nThis creates an important contradiction: the ability to exit is often weakest when participants most urgently want to sell.\n\nA strategy tested under ordinary liquidity may behave very differently when:\n\n- Stops experience severe slippage\n- Stablecoin pools become imbalanced\n- Market makers withdraw\n- Exchanges suspend activity\n- Network fees increase\n- DEX liquidity disappears\n\nRegime analysis should therefore consider both price behaviour and execution conditions.\n\n---\n\n### Risk-On and Risk-Off Regimes\n\nA risk-on regime develops when investors are willing to allocate capital toward uncertain or speculative assets.\n\nWithin cryptocurrency, a risk-on environment may involve:\n\n- Rising prices across many sectors\n- Strong altcoin participation\n- Increased borrowing\n- Growing open interest\n- Greater stablecoin deployment\n- Expanding market breadth\n- Higher demand for lower-quality assets\n\nA risk-off regime develops when participants prioritise liquidity and capital preservation.\n\nIt may involve:\n\n- Selling of speculative assets\n- Rising correlations\n- Movement toward cash or stronger collateral\n- Reduced leverage\n- Wider spreads\n- Stablecoin stress\n- Lower market breadth\n\nRisk-on does not mean the market is safe.\n\nIt often encourages leverage, overconfidence and weak investment standards.\n\nRisk-off does not mean every asset is fundamentally impaired.\n\nIt means participants are reducing exposure broadly.\n\n---\n\n### Correlation Regimes\n\nCorrelation measures the degree to which assets move together.\n\nDuring calm periods, different cryptocurrencies may respond to project-specific developments.\n\nOne sector may rise while another declines.\n\nDuring a systemic crisis, correlations often increase.\n\nParticipants sell digital assets broadly, regardless of individual quality.\n\nThis can make a diversified crypto portfolio behave like one concentrated position.\n\nA correlation regime matters because strategy signals may not be independent.\n\nFive technically valid long positions can all fail simultaneously if they depend on the same broad market movement.\n\nRegime analysis should therefore consider whether assets are:\n\n- Moving independently\n- Following Bitcoin closely\n- Responding to one macroeconomic factor\n- Becoming increasingly correlated during stress\n\n---\n\n### Leverage Regimes\n\nCryptocurrency markets can also be classified according to the amount and direction of leverage.\n\nA leverage-building regime may show rising open interest, increasing borrowing and expanding speculative positioning.\n\nThis can support a trend while also making it fragile.\n\nA deleveraging regime occurs when positions are closed voluntarily or through liquidation.\n\nDeleveraging may produce rapid movement because forced transactions are not based on valuation. They are based on collateral requirements.\n\nDuring a long liquidation cascade, selling creates lower prices, which trigger further liquidations.\n\nDuring a short squeeze, forced buying pushes price higher and causes additional short positions to close.\n\nA price movement driven by leverage can be powerful but unstable.\n\n---\n\n### Broad Market Regimes\n\nMarket regimes rarely fit perfectly into one category. Several characteristics usually combine.\n\nA useful practical framework recognises a number of common environments.\n\n---\n\n### Persistent Bull Trend\n\nA persistent bull trend contains an extended sequence of higher highs and higher lows.\n\nPullbacks are relatively controlled, breakouts hold and participation may broaden over time.\n\nMoving averages generally rise, and price remains above important support.\n\nTrend-following and momentum approaches may perform well in this environment because directional persistence rewards holding profitable positions.\n\nMean-reversion strategies can still be used to enter pullbacks, but repeatedly shorting overbought conditions may be dangerous.\n\nThe main risks are late entry, excessive leverage and assuming that the trend cannot end.\n\n---\n\n### Speculative or Parabolic Bull Regime\n\nA parabolic regime contains accelerating price movement.\n\nVolatility rises, leverage expands and participants may abandon valuation discipline.\n\nThe market can travel much farther than conventional analysis expects.\n\nMomentum strategies may produce exceptional gains, but late entries become increasingly dangerous.\n\nTraditional mean-reversion signals such as overbought RSI readings may fail repeatedly.\n\nRisk management becomes more difficult because meaningful support may be far below the current price.\n\nThe appropriate response may involve smaller additions, tighter portfolio exposure and more disciplined trailing exits rather than increasingly aggressive buying.\n\n---','markdown',NULL,NULL,NULL,6,0,0,0,'',NULL,2,1785297600000 WHERE EXISTS (SELECT 1 FROM `courses` WHERE `id`='cognizen-crypto-mastery-foundations-production');
--> statement-breakpoint
INSERT OR IGNORE INTO `lessons` (`id`,`course_id`,`title`,`section_id`,`lesson_type`,`content`,`content_format`,`video_key`,`primary_asset_id`,`intro_asset_id`,`duration_minutes`,`is_preview`,`available_after_days`,`required_watch_percent`,`transcript`,`experience_json`,`position`,`updated_at`) SELECT 'cmf-module-3-04-lesson-03','cognizen-crypto-mastery-foundations-production','Persistent Bear Trend and Strategy Regimes Versus Investment Regimes','cmf-module-3-04','text','### Persistent Bear Trend\n\nA persistent bear trend produces lower highs and lower lows.\n\nRecoveries fail, support levels break and liquidity may gradually decline.\n\nTrend-following short strategies may benefit, although shorting introduces funding, borrowing and unlimited-price-risk concerns.\n\nLong-only investors may hold more liquidity and wait for structural improvement.\n\nMean-reversion rallies can occur, but they may be temporary and violent.\n\nThe greatest error in this regime is assuming that an asset must recover because it has already fallen substantially.\n\n---\n\n### Capitulation and Deleveraging Regime\n\nCapitulation occurs when fear, forced selling and withdrawal demand become extreme.\n\nPrice ranges expand, correlations rise and liquidity deteriorates.\n\nAssets may trade far below recent averages.\n\nThis environment can create significant future opportunities, but entering too early can be destructive.\n\nA mean-reversion signal based only on oversold momentum is insufficient.\n\nMore useful evidence may include stabilising liquidity, declining liquidation activity, reduced open interest, recovery in spot demand and a break in bearish market structure.\n\nThe first rebound after capitulation may be sharp without establishing a durable bull market.\n\n---\n\n### Stable Sideways Range\n\nA stable sideways regime forms when support and resistance are respected repeatedly.\n\nVolatility remains relatively controlled and price frequently returns toward a central value.\n\nMean-reversion strategies generally have their strongest logical foundation in this environment.\n\nParticipants may buy near support, sell near resistance and use the range midpoint or VWAP as a target.\n\nTrend-following and breakout strategies may experience repeated whipsaws.\n\nThe primary risk is that the range eventually breaks and the participant continues using mean-reversion rules after the regime has changed.\n\n---\n\n### Violent Sideways Regime\n\nNot every range is calm.\n\nA market can move sharply between support and resistance while failing to establish a sustained trend.\n\nThis environment may contain:\n\n- Large candles\n- Frequent stop runs\n- False breakouts\n- High funding variability\n- Rapid reversals\n\nMean reversion may remain conceptually appropriate, but execution becomes more difficult.\n\nStops need greater room, position sizes should be smaller and transaction costs may increase.\n\nTrend-following strategies can suffer from repeated directional changes.\n\n---\n\n### Low-Volatility Compression Regime\n\nDuring compression, price ranges narrow and volatility indicators decline.\n\nThis often occurs before a larger movement.\n\nMean reversion may work temporarily while price remains inside the range.\n\nHowever, the potential for regime transition is increasing.\n\nA breakout strategy may prepare for expansion but should not assume direction in advance.\n\nThe key change occurs when price gains acceptance beyond the compressed structure and volatility begins to expand.\n\n---\n\n### Volatility Expansion Regime\n\nVolatility expansion occurs when price leaves a period of compression or begins reacting strongly to new information.\n\nBreakout and momentum strategies may become more appropriate if direction persists.\n\nA strategy should determine whether expansion represents:\n\n- Genuine trend initiation\n- Temporary news reaction\n- Liquidity sweep\n- Liquidation event\n- Chaotic movement without direction\n\nHigh volatility requires smaller positions because wider stops and greater slippage increase actual capital risk.\n\n---\n\n### Recovery and Transition Regime\n\nAfter a prolonged decline, the market may stop making lower lows but remain below major resistance.\n\nThis can be a transition rather than a confirmed bull market.\n\nThe market may show:\n\n- Reduced selling momentum\n- Improving breadth\n- Higher lows on shorter timeframes\n- Declining volatility\n- Recovery in liquidity\n- Failed bearish breakdowns\n\nMean-reversion and selective tactical strategies may become viable.\n\nFull trend-following exposure may still be premature until higher-timeframe structure confirms the change.\n\nTransition regimes are particularly difficult because evidence is mixed.\n\n---\n\n### Distribution Regime\n\nDistribution may occur after a prolonged rise when early holders sell into continued demand.\n\nPrice may remain near its highs while momentum weakens.\n\nPossible signs include:\n\n- Repeated failed breakouts\n- High volume with limited progress\n- Long upper wicks\n- Weakening breadth\n- Increasing leverage\n- Strong promotional narratives\n- Insider or treasury selling\n\nDistribution cannot be identified with certainty while it is occurring.\n\nThe market may consolidate and continue higher.\n\nIt should be treated as a risk condition rather than an automatic short signal.\n\n---\n\n### Accumulation Regime\n\nAccumulation may occur after a prolonged decline when stronger participants build positions gradually.\n\nPrice may remain range-bound while selling pressure weakens.\n\nPossible evidence includes:\n\n- Repeated defence of support\n- Lower volatility\n- Recovery after failed breakdowns\n- Reduced exchange selling\n- Improving long-term ownership\n- Increasing spot demand\n\nA quiet range is not necessarily accumulation.\n\nIt may also represent disinterest before another decline.\n\nThe later breakout and subsequent acceptance help confirm which interpretation was more accurate.\n\n---\n\n### Strategy Regimes Versus Investment Regimes\n\nA trader and long-term investor may classify the same market differently.\n\nA trader may focus on whether the next several days favour breakout or mean reversion.\n\nAn investor may focus on whether the broader market is in expansion, contraction, accumulation or speculative excess.\n\nThe selected regime framework should match the decision horizon.\n\nA regime model designed for hourly trading should not govern a multi-year allocation without broader evidence.\n\n---','markdown',NULL,NULL,NULL,6,0,0,0,'',NULL,3,1785297600000 WHERE EXISTS (SELECT 1 FROM `courses` WHERE `id`='cognizen-crypto-mastery-foundations-production');
--> statement-breakpoint
INSERT OR IGNORE INTO `lessons` (`id`,`course_id`,`title`,`section_id`,`lesson_type`,`content`,`content_format`,`video_key`,`primary_asset_id`,`intro_asset_id`,`duration_minutes`,`is_preview`,`available_after_days`,`required_watch_percent`,`transcript`,`experience_json`,`position`,`updated_at`) SELECT 'cmf-module-3-04-lesson-04','cognizen-crypto-mastery-foundations-production','Identifying a Trend Regime and Derivatives Positioning','cmf-module-3-04','text','### Identifying a Trend Regime\n\nPrice structure is the first source of evidence.\n\nA bullish trend regime generally contains rising swing points, successful breakouts and support above former resistance.\n\nA bearish regime displays the opposite.\n\nMoving-average slope may support the analysis. Price above a strongly rising average is different from price repeatedly crossing a flat one.\n\nADX can help estimate directional strength, although it does not identify whether the direction is bullish or bearish.\n\nVolume may show whether participation increases during movement in the trend direction.\n\nNo single indicator defines the regime.\n\nThe goal is to observe whether several forms of evidence tell a consistent story.\n\n---\n\n### Identifying a Range Regime\n\nA range regime usually contains repeated reactions at established boundaries.\n\nMoving averages flatten, candles overlap and breakouts fail.\n\nVolume may decline near the centre and increase at the edges.\n\nMomentum oscillators frequently move between overbought and oversold zones.\n\nA range remains valid only while the market continues rejecting movement beyond its boundaries.\n\nA decisive close, follow-through and rising volatility may signal that the regime is ending.\n\n---\n\n### Measuring Volatility Regimes\n\nAverage True Range provides a direct measure of recent price-range size.\n\nA rising ATR suggests that normal movement is expanding.\n\nA falling ATR suggests contraction.\n\nBollinger Band width can provide similar information by measuring the distance between volatility bands.\n\nHistorical volatility and realised volatility can also be compared with their longer-term averages.\n\nThe absolute volatility number is less important than:\n\n- Whether volatility is rising or falling\n- How current volatility compares with history\n- Whether movement is directional\n- Whether liquidity can support execution\n\n---\n\n### Volatility Clustering\n\nVolatility often clusters.\n\nHigh-volatility periods tend to be followed by further high volatility, while quiet periods may continue for some time.\n\nThis does not mean volatility never changes.\n\nIt means a single large candle should not automatically be treated as an isolated event.\n\nA shift into a high-volatility regime may require lasting changes to:\n\n- Position size\n- Stop distance\n- Trading frequency\n- Leverage\n- Portfolio heat\n\nUsing low-volatility risk assumptions after the regime has changed can produce unexpectedly large losses.\n\n---\n\n### Volume and Participation\n\nVolume helps assess whether market movement is supported by meaningful participation.\n\nIn a healthy bullish regime, volume may expand on advances and contract during pullbacks.\n\nIn a range, volume may remain balanced or concentrate near the boundaries.\n\nDuring distribution, high volume may produce little additional price progress.\n\nVolume quality matters.\n\nArtificial volume, liquidation activity and internal exchange movements can create misleading signals.\n\nThe analyst should compare volume across credible venues and distinguish spot from derivatives where possible.\n\n---\n\n### Market Breadth\n\nMarket breadth evaluates how widely participation is distributed across the market.\n\nA broad bullish regime may involve many assets making higher highs and trading above important averages.\n\nA narrow rally may be driven by only one or two major assets while most of the market remains weak.\n\nBroad participation can support regime durability.\n\nA narrowing market may indicate that liquidity is becoming concentrated.\n\nBreadth does not identify the exact turning point, but it can reveal whether the visible market index reflects widespread strength or a small number of dominant assets.\n\n---\n\n### Relative Strength\n\nRelative strength compares one asset with another or with a market benchmark.\n\nAn asset may rise against a stable quote currency while underperforming Bitcoin.\n\nThis means it is gaining in absolute terms but losing relative value.\n\nDuring a risk-on altcoin regime, many assets may outperform Bitcoin.\n\nDuring risk-off conditions, capital may move toward Bitcoin or out of cryptocurrency entirely.\n\nRelative strength helps identify where demand is concentrated and which parts of the market are weakening first.\n\n---\n\n### Bitcoin Dominance and Market Structure\n\nBitcoin’s relative share of the cryptocurrency market can provide context about capital rotation.\n\nA rising share may occur when:\n\n- Bitcoin outperforms altcoins\n- Speculative assets decline faster\n- New capital enters Bitcoin first\n- Risk appetite decreases\n\nA falling share may occur when capital rotates toward other sectors.\n\nThis measure should not be used in isolation.\n\nChanges in stablecoin supply, token issuance and market-capitalisation calculations can affect the result.\n\n---\n\n### Derivatives Positioning\n\nOpen interest, funding rates and liquidation data can reveal whether a regime is supported by sustainable participation or excessive leverage.\n\nA rising market with moderate funding and healthy spot volume may differ from a rally driven by rapidly expanding leveraged longs.\n\nSimilarly, a decline with falling open interest may represent deleveraging, while a decline with rising short positioning may be vulnerable to a squeeze.\n\nDerivatives data does not provide a direct trading instruction.\n\nIt helps describe the structure and fragility of the market.\n\n---','markdown',NULL,NULL,NULL,6,0,0,0,'',NULL,4,1785297600000 WHERE EXISTS (SELECT 1 FROM `courses` WHERE `id`='cognizen-crypto-mastery-foundations-production');
--> statement-breakpoint
INSERT OR IGNORE INTO `lessons` (`id`,`course_id`,`title`,`section_id`,`lesson_type`,`content`,`content_format`,`video_key`,`primary_asset_id`,`intro_asset_id`,`duration_minutes`,`is_preview`,`available_after_days`,`required_watch_percent`,`transcript`,`experience_json`,`position`,`updated_at`) SELECT 'cmf-module-3-04-lesson-05','cognizen-crypto-mastery-foundations-production','Stablecoin Conditions and Trend Following in a Trend Regime','cmf-module-3-04','text','### Stablecoin Conditions\n\nStablecoins provide trading liquidity, collateral and settlement across much of the digital asset market.\n\nTheir condition can influence the regime.\n\nGrowing stablecoin availability may increase capital capable of entering the market.\n\nA stablecoin depeg can create:\n\n- Liquidity stress\n- Forced selling\n- Pool imbalance\n- Collateral problems\n- Distorted price charts\n\nA regime model should treat stablecoin stability as part of market infrastructure rather than as an unrelated asset issue.\n\n---\n\n### Macroeconomic Conditions\n\nDigital assets interact increasingly with broader financial markets.\n\nImportant influences can include:\n\n- Interest rates\n- Credit conditions\n- Currency strength\n- Global liquidity\n- Inflation expectations\n- Economic growth\n- Equity-market risk appetite\n\nTighter financial conditions may reduce demand for speculative assets.\n\nEasier conditions may encourage risk-taking.\n\nThese relationships are not stable.\n\nCryptocurrency can occasionally move independently because of sector-specific events.\n\nMacroeconomic analysis should inform scenarios without replacing direct market evidence.\n\n---\n\n### On-Chain Evidence\n\nOn-chain data may contribute to regime analysis by examining:\n\n- Exchange balances\n- Long-term holder activity\n- Realised profits and losses\n- Network fees\n- Transaction activity\n- Stablecoin movement\n- Cost-basis distribution\n\nFor example, heavy realised losses and declining exchange inflows may appear near a transition from capitulation toward stabilisation.\n\nHowever, on-chain data can be delayed and difficult to interpret.\n\nOne entity may control many addresses, and exchange wallets may move funds internally.\n\nOn-chain evidence should be combined with price, liquidity and market structure.\n\n---\n\n### Multi-Timeframe Regimes\n\nDifferent timeframes can exist in different regimes simultaneously.\n\nA monthly bull market can contain a weekly correction and an hourly sideways range.\n\nA strategy should define which timeframe controls:\n\n- Directional bias\n- Entry\n- Stop placement\n- Exit\n- Portfolio allocation\n\nA short-term mean-reversion trade may be reasonable inside a higher-timeframe uptrend.\n\nThe same long trade may be inappropriate if the higher-timeframe regime is a confirmed bear trend.\n\nMulti-timeframe analysis helps prevent local signals from being interpreted without broader context.\n\n---\n\n### Regime Transition\n\nThe greatest strategy risk often occurs during transition.\n\nA stable range begins breaking out.\n\nA mature trend loses momentum and enters consolidation.\n\nA low-volatility market becomes unstable.\n\nA risk-on market begins deleveraging.\n\nRegime transitions are difficult because indicators usually respond after conditions have started changing.\n\nThe participant may continue applying the old strategy precisely when its assumptions are becoming invalid.\n\nA robust framework should therefore include evidence that suspends or reduces strategy use during uncertainty.\n\n---\n\n### Evidence of Transition From Range to Trend\n\nA range may be transitioning into a trend when price closes beyond the boundary, volatility expands and follow-through develops.\n\nFurther confirmation may come from a successful retest, increasing volume and a moving average beginning to slope.\n\nOne breakout candle is not enough to guarantee a new regime.\n\nThe market should show acceptance outside the range.\n\nUntil then, the participant may reduce position size or wait.\n\n---\n\n### Evidence of Transition From Trend to Range\n\nA trend may be weakening when impulse moves become smaller, corrections deepen and previous highs or lows fail to break.\n\nMoving averages may flatten and price begins crossing them repeatedly.\n\nVolume may decline, and market structure becomes less directional.\n\nThe transition does not automatically mean reversal.\n\nThe market may be resting before continuation.\n\nTrend-following exposure may nevertheless need to be reduced because directional persistence has weakened.\n\n---\n\n### Evidence of Transition From Trend to Reversal\n\nA stronger reversal process may involve failure to create a new directional extreme, followed by a break of an important structural level and the formation of opposite market structure.\n\nFor example, a bullish trend may shift when:\n\n1. Price fails to make a convincing higher high  \n2. An important higher low breaks  \n3. A recovery forms a lower high  \n4. Price creates a lower low  \n\nThis process provides more evidence than one oscillator divergence.\n\n---\n\n### Strategy Selection\n\nNo strategy should be selected because it is currently fashionable or recently profitable.\n\nThe strategy should match the market behaviour it is designed to exploit.\n\nTrend following expects persistence.\n\nMean reversion expects temporary deviation.\n\nBreakout trading expects expansion from structure.\n\nMomentum expects strong movement to continue.\n\nRelative-value strategies expect relationships to normalise.\n\nYield and carry strategies expect income to compensate for market, credit and liquidity risk.\n\nOptions strategies may express views on direction, volatility or time.\n\nThe market regime determines which assumption currently has the strongest support.\n\n---\n\n### Trend Following in a Trend Regime\n\nTrend following is best aligned with persistent directional structure.\n\nThe participant may use moving averages, price channels or swing structure to remain in the position while the trend continues.\n\nThe strategy accepts that entries and exits will occur late.\n\nIt aims to capture the middle of a large move rather than predict the exact turning points.\n\nDuring a strong trend, repeated countertrend trades can create unnecessary losses.\n\nThe primary risks are late entry, trend exhaustion and excessive concentration.\n\n---','markdown',NULL,NULL,NULL,6,0,0,0,'',NULL,5,1785297600000 WHERE EXISTS (SELECT 1 FROM `courses` WHERE `id`='cognizen-crypto-mastery-foundations-production');
--> statement-breakpoint
INSERT OR IGNORE INTO `lessons` (`id`,`course_id`,`title`,`section_id`,`lesson_type`,`content`,`content_format`,`video_key`,`primary_asset_id`,`intro_asset_id`,`duration_minutes`,`is_preview`,`available_after_days`,`required_watch_percent`,`transcript`,`experience_json`,`position`,`updated_at`) SELECT 'cmf-module-3-04-lesson-06','cognizen-crypto-mastery-foundations-production','Mean Reversion in a Range Regime and Regime Scoring','cmf-module-3-04','text','### Mean Reversion in a Range Regime\n\nMean reversion is most appropriate when the market repeatedly returns toward a stable average.\n\nThe strategy may use range boundaries, VWAP, moving averages, Bollinger Bands or statistical deviation.\n\nIt should stop operating when the market begins accepting prices outside the previous structure.\n\nThe largest risk is treating a genuine breakout as another temporary deviation.\n\nA strict range-failure rule is essential.\n\n---\n\n### Breakout Strategy in Compression\n\nBreakout strategies are naturally aligned with volatility compression and well-defined boundaries.\n\nThe participant waits for expansion and evidence of acceptance.\n\nThe direction may be unknown before the breakout occurs.\n\nA strategy may prepare orders or alerts on both sides while entering only after confirmation.\n\nThe main risks are false breakouts, poor liquidity and entering after excessive extension.\n\n---\n\n### Momentum Strategy in Expansion\n\nMomentum strategies may perform well after volatility expands and price begins travelling persistently.\n\nVolume, market breadth and relative strength can support the signal.\n\nMomentum entries become less attractive as price moves farther from the original structure.\n\nThe strategy should define an extension limit and avoid interpreting every rapid move as a sustainable trend.\n\n---\n\n### Countertrend Strategy During Exhaustion\n\nCountertrend strategies may become appropriate when a mature trend shows evidence of exhaustion.\n\nHowever, identifying exhaustion is difficult.\n\nAn overbought or oversold indicator is not sufficient.\n\nStronger evidence may include failed structural continuation, changing volume, liquidation exhaustion and opposite-direction confirmation.\n\nCountertrend positions should generally be smaller because they oppose the established regime.\n\n---\n\n### Carry and Yield Strategies\n\nCarry strategies attempt to earn income through:\n\n- Staking\n- Lending\n- Futures basis\n- Funding\n- Liquidity provision\n\nThese strategies often perform best when volatility, credit conditions and liquidity remain relatively stable.\n\nThey can fail during:\n\n- Depegging\n- Liquidation cascades\n- Withdrawal pressure\n- Smart contract exploits\n- Rapid funding reversal\n- Severe price divergence\n\nA stable-looking yield can conceal exposure to a sudden regime shift.\n\nYield should be reduced or hedged when market stability deteriorates.\n\n---\n\n### Relative-Value Strategies\n\nPairs trading and statistical arbitrage may be appropriate when relationships between assets remain stable.\n\nThese strategies can reduce broad directional exposure.\n\nThey depend on the assumption that historical relationships remain meaningful.\n\nA structural change affecting one project can permanently alter the spread.\n\nRelative-value strategies may therefore perform poorly during sector disruption, protocol failure or regulatory divergence.\n\n---\n\n### Options and Volatility Regimes\n\nOptions can be used to express views about future volatility.\n\nWhen implied volatility is low and a significant event may occur, a participant may consider strategies that benefit from volatility expansion.\n\nWhen implied volatility is extremely high, selling volatility may appear attractive because option premiums are expensive.\n\nSelling volatility carries substantial risk because market movement can exceed expectations.\n\nOptions strategy requires analysis of:\n\n- Implied volatility\n- Realised volatility\n- Time decay\n- Strike\n- Expiry\n- Liquidity\n- Maximum loss\n\nLow volatility can remain low, and high volatility can become much higher.\n\n---\n\n### Cash as a Strategy\n\nRemaining in cash or a carefully evaluated liquid reserve is a valid strategy.\n\nA participant may choose not to act when:\n\n- Regime evidence conflicts\n- Liquidity is unreliable\n- Volatility exceeds risk limits\n- Strategy performance has deteriorated\n- A major event is approaching\n- No favourable risk-to-reward exists\n\nAdvanced strategy does not require constant market exposure.\n\nThe absence of a position can protect both capital and decision quality.\n\n---\n\n### A Regime-to-Strategy Framework\n\nRather than applying one strategy continuously, a participant may create a decision framework.\n\nIn a persistent trend, trend-following and pullback continuation strategies may receive priority.\n\nDuring a stable range, mean-reversion strategies may become more suitable.\n\nDuring volatility compression, the participant may reduce activity and prepare for a breakout.\n\nAfter confirmed expansion, breakout and momentum strategies may become active.\n\nDuring a liquidity crisis, leverage and strategy frequency may be reduced substantially.\n\nDuring unclear transitions, the participant may use smaller positions or remain inactive.\n\nThe framework does not need to predict every regime change. It needs to prevent a strategy from being applied blindly when its assumptions are visibly unsupported.\n\n---\n\n### Regime Confidence\n\nA regime assessment should include a level of confidence.\n\nFor example:\n\n**High confidence:** Price structure, volatility, volume and breadth all support the same interpretation.\n\n**Moderate confidence:** Most evidence agrees, but one important area is uncertain.\n\n**Low confidence:** Timeframes conflict, volatility is unstable or the market is transitioning.\n\nPosition size can be adjusted according to confidence.\n\nLow-confidence regimes should not receive the same exposure as clear, established environments.\n\nConfidence should reflect evidence, not personal conviction.\n\n---\n\n### Regime Scoring\n\nA systematic participant may create a regime score.\n\nFor example, a bullish-trend score could consider:\n\n- Higher-timeframe market structure\n- Moving-average slope\n- Price above long-term average\n- ADX\n- Market breadth\n- Relative strength\n- Volume confirmation\n\nEach condition may receive a value.\n\nThe combined score determines whether trend strategies are permitted.\n\nA scoring system improves consistency but can create false precision.\n\nThe inputs may be correlated, and the selected thresholds may be overfitted.\n\n---','markdown',NULL,NULL,NULL,6,0,0,0,'',NULL,6,1785297600000 WHERE EXISTS (SELECT 1 FROM `courses` WHERE `id`='cognizen-crypto-mastery-foundations-production');
--> statement-breakpoint
INSERT OR IGNORE INTO `lessons` (`id`,`course_id`,`title`,`section_id`,`lesson_type`,`content`,`content_format`,`video_key`,`primary_asset_id`,`intro_asset_id`,`duration_minutes`,`is_preview`,`available_after_days`,`required_watch_percent`,`transcript`,`experience_json`,`position`,`updated_at`) SELECT 'cmf-module-3-04-lesson-07','cognizen-crypto-mastery-foundations-production','Strategy Activation and Deactivation and Lagging Indicators','cmf-module-3-04','text','### Strategy Activation and Deactivation\n\nA strategy should define the conditions under which it becomes active.\n\nA mean-reversion strategy may activate only when the market remains inside an established range and trend-strength measures are low.\n\nIt may deactivate when price closes beyond the range with expanding volatility.\n\nA breakout strategy may activate only after volatility compression and a confirmed boundary break.\n\nIt may deactivate if price returns inside the range.\n\nThese rules reduce the temptation to continue using a strategy simply because it worked recently.\n\n---\n\n### Position Sizing by Regime\n\nPosition size should change when the regime changes.\n\nDuring low-volatility and deep-liquidity conditions, stops may be closer and execution more predictable.\n\nDuring high volatility, stops usually require more room, so position size should decrease.\n\nDuring weak liquidity, even a small stop distance may not reflect actual risk because slippage can be substantial.\n\nDuring high correlation, total portfolio exposure should be reduced because several positions may fail together.\n\nRegime-based sizing aims to maintain consistent capital risk rather than consistent token quantity.\n\n---\n\n### Volatility Targeting\n\nVolatility targeting adjusts exposure so that the portfolio seeks a relatively stable level of expected volatility.\n\nWhen market volatility rises, exposure decreases.\n\nWhen volatility falls, exposure may increase within predefined limits.\n\nA simplified approach may be:\n\n**Target exposure = Desired volatility ÷ Current volatility**\n\nSuppose desired volatility is ten percent and estimated current volatility is twenty percent.\n\nThe model may reduce exposure to approximately half of the normal level.\n\nThis is a simplified example.\n\nVolatility estimates can change rapidly and may underestimate extreme events.\n\n---\n\n### Risk Budgeting\n\nRisk budgeting assigns a maximum amount of portfolio risk to each strategy or asset.\n\nInstead of allocating equal capital, the portfolio allocates according to expected volatility, correlation and possible loss.\n\nFor example, a low-volatility market-neutral strategy may receive more capital than a highly volatile directional trade while contributing similar estimated risk.\n\nRisk estimates are imperfect.\n\nThey often become least reliable during crises when correlations and volatility change abruptly.\n\n---\n\n### Portfolio Heat by Regime\n\nPortfolio heat is the total risk across open positions.\n\nDuring a clear trend with broad liquidity, a framework may permit greater heat within defined limits.\n\nDuring transition or high-correlation stress, the maximum may be reduced.\n\nA portfolio with several altcoin positions should consider that all may depend on:\n\n- Bitcoin direction\n- Stablecoin liquidity\n- One exchange\n- One Layer 1 network\n- Broad investor risk appetite\n\nHeat should be measured according to economic exposure rather than the number of positions.\n\n---\n\n### Leverage by Regime\n\nLeverage should not remain constant across regimes.\n\nLow recent volatility can encourage participants to increase leverage.\n\nIf volatility then expands, liquidation risk rises rapidly.\n\nThis is particularly dangerous near the end of a compression regime.\n\nA prudent framework may reduce or prohibit leverage when:\n\n- Volatility is expanding\n- Liquidity is deteriorating\n- Correlations are increasing\n- Funding is extreme\n- Regime confidence is low\n\nLeverage should be based on acceptable loss, not a belief that the regime is predictable.\n\n---\n\n### Strategy Diversification\n\nA portfolio may combine strategies with different return patterns.\n\nFor example, it might contain:\n\n- Trend-following exposure\n- Mean-reversion strategies\n- Relative-value positions\n- Staking or carry\n- Cash reserves\n\nThe objective is not to ensure that every strategy earns money simultaneously.\n\nIt is to avoid dependence on one market behaviour.\n\nHowever, apparent strategy diversification can be misleading.\n\nA leveraged lending strategy, liquidity pool and long momentum position may all lose during the same risk-off event.\n\nThe underlying risk drivers must be mapped.\n\n---\n\n### Strategy Correlation\n\nStrategy correlations can change by regime.\n\nTrend following and momentum may be highly related during directional movement.\n\nMean reversion may perform differently during ranges.\n\nCarry strategies may appear independent until a volatility crisis causes losses across several positions.\n\nBacktests should examine not only average correlations but stress-period correlations.\n\n---\n\n### Regime Misclassification\n\nNo regime model is always correct.\n\nA range can appear stable immediately before it breaks.\n\nA new trend can appear genuine and fail.\n\nVolatility may rise for one day and then decline.\n\nMisclassification is unavoidable.\n\nThe framework should be designed so that an incorrect regime assessment produces a manageable loss.\n\nThe purpose of classification is to improve probability, not create certainty.\n\n---\n\n### Lagging Indicators\n\nMany regime indicators lag.\n\nMoving averages flatten only after directional movement has weakened.\n\nADX rises after a trend has already developed.\n\nRealised volatility increases after larger movements occur.\n\nWaiting for strong confirmation improves reliability but delays adaptation.\n\nEarly recognition provides better entry but greater uncertainty.\n\nThe strategy must accept this trade-off.\n\n---','markdown',NULL,NULL,NULL,6,0,0,0,'',NULL,7,1785297600000 WHERE EXISTS (SELECT 1 FROM `courses` WHERE `id`='cognizen-crypto-mastery-foundations-production');
--> statement-breakpoint
INSERT OR IGNORE INTO `lessons` (`id`,`course_id`,`title`,`section_id`,`lesson_type`,`content`,`content_format`,`video_key`,`primary_asset_id`,`intro_asset_id`,`duration_minutes`,`is_preview`,`available_after_days`,`required_watch_percent`,`transcript`,`experience_json`,`position`,`updated_at`) SELECT 'cmf-module-3-04-lesson-08','cognizen-crypto-mastery-foundations-production','Conflicting Evidence and Stress Testing Regime Change','cmf-module-3-04','text','### Conflicting Evidence\n\nRegime indicators frequently disagree.\n\nPrice structure may be bullish while breadth is weakening.\n\nVolatility may be low while derivatives leverage is high.\n\nThe weekly trend may be positive while the daily chart is breaking support.\n\nConflicting evidence may justify:\n\n- Smaller position size\n- Shorter holding period\n- Additional confirmation\n- No position\n\nThe participant should not select only the evidence supporting the desired trade.\n\n---\n\n### Regime Transition Whipsaws\n\nStrategies can suffer repeated losses during transition because the market alternates between old and new behaviour.\n\nFor example, a range may produce several false breakouts before a trend becomes established.\n\nA trend may break structure and then recover.\n\nPossible responses include:\n\n- Reducing position size\n- Requiring additional confirmation\n- Limiting re-entry attempts\n- Waiting for higher-timeframe acceptance\n- Temporarily suspending the strategy\n\nEvery additional filter can delay participation in the eventual move.\n\n---\n\n### Adaptive Strategies\n\nAn adaptive strategy changes rules or exposure according to regime evidence.\n\nIt may alter:\n\n- Position size\n- Stop distance\n- Holding period\n- Entry threshold\n- Strategy type\n- Asset universe\n\nAdaptation can improve alignment.\n\nIt also increases complexity and overfitting risk.\n\nA highly adaptive strategy may appear intelligent in a historical backtest because it was designed with knowledge of past regime changes.\n\nThe rules must be simple, observable and testable.\n\n---\n\n### Fixed Strategies\n\nA fixed strategy applies the same core rules across all markets.\n\nIt may accept weak performance during unsuitable regimes because profitable periods compensate over time.\n\nPotential advantages include:\n\n- Simplicity\n- Lower model risk\n- Easier testing\n- Reduced discretionary interference\n\nPotential disadvantages include:\n\n- Long drawdowns\n- Poor efficiency\n- Repeated losses in predictable adverse environments\n\nA fixed strategy can still include risk controls without attempting to classify every regime.\n\n---\n\n### Regime Filters\n\nA regime filter prevents a strategy from operating under specified conditions.\n\nA trend system may require a rising long-term moving average.\n\nA mean-reversion system may require low ADX and stable range boundaries.\n\nA breakout system may require volatility compression before entry.\n\nThe filter should improve out-of-sample performance, not merely historical appearance.\n\nA filter that eliminates every losing trade is almost certainly using future information or excessive optimisation.\n\n---\n\n### Backtesting by Regime\n\nA strategy should be evaluated separately across different market environments.\n\nA single total return can conceal major weaknesses.\n\nTrend following may produce most of its profit during a few directional periods while losing steadily elsewhere.\n\nMean reversion may generate regular gains before one range break creates a severe loss.\n\nUseful analysis compares:\n\n- Bull trends\n- Bear trends\n- Sideways periods\n- High volatility\n- Low volatility\n- Liquidity crises\n- Recovery periods\n\nThe regime definitions must use only information available at the time.\n\n---\n\n### Regime Labelling Bias\n\nHistorical regimes are easy to identify after they end.\n\nA chart clearly shows where the bull market, crash and recovery occurred.\n\nIn real time, these boundaries were uncertain.\n\nA backtest should not label the start of a regime using future data.\n\nFor example, it cannot decide that a bull market began at the exact bottom because later prices proved it.\n\nThe regime model must respond only to contemporaneous evidence.\n\n---\n\n### Hidden-State Models\n\nAdvanced quantitative approaches may treat regimes as hidden states inferred from observable data.\n\nModels may use:\n\n- Returns\n- Volatility\n- Correlation\n- Volume\n- Macroeconomic variables\n\nThese methods can estimate the probability that the market belongs to a particular state.\n\nThey do not reveal an objectively true regime.\n\nThe result depends on:\n\n- Model assumptions\n- Data\n- Number of states\n- Parameter stability\n\nComplex models can create false confidence.\n\n---\n\n### Clustering\n\nMachine-learning clustering can group historical periods with similar characteristics.\n\nFor example, one cluster may contain low-volatility positive returns, while another contains high-volatility negative returns.\n\nThe analyst may then study how strategies performed in each group.\n\nClustering can reveal patterns without predefined labels.\n\nIt may also group data according to statistically convenient but economically meaningless relationships.\n\nInterpretability remains important.\n\n---\n\n### Regime Probability\n\nInstead of assigning one definite label, a model may estimate probabilities.\n\nFor example:\n\n- 60 percent probability of trend regime\n- 30 percent probability of transition\n- 10 percent probability of stable range\n\nThis reflects uncertainty more honestly.\n\nExposure can be reduced when probabilities are widely distributed.\n\nA probability estimate is still model-dependent and should not be interpreted as objective certainty.\n\n---\n\n### Stress Testing Regime Change\n\nA strategy should be stress-tested against abrupt regime transitions.\n\nExamples include:\n\n- Stable range becomes a breakdown\n- Low volatility becomes a liquidation cascade\n- Bull trend reverses after an exploit\n- Stablecoin yield position enters depeg conditions\n- Market-neutral spread diverges permanently\n- Liquidity disappears\n\nThe stress test should estimate:\n\n- Financial loss\n- Slippage\n- Correlated position failures\n- Ability to exit\n- Funding and collateral effects\n\n---','markdown',NULL,NULL,NULL,6,0,0,0,'',NULL,8,1785297600000 WHERE EXISTS (SELECT 1 FROM `courses` WHERE `id`='cognizen-crypto-mastery-foundations-production');
--> statement-breakpoint
INSERT OR IGNORE INTO `lessons` (`id`,`course_id`,`title`,`section_id`,`lesson_type`,`content`,`content_format`,`video_key`,`primary_asset_id`,`intro_asset_id`,`duration_minutes`,`is_preview`,`available_after_days`,`required_watch_percent`,`transcript`,`experience_json`,`position`,`updated_at`) SELECT 'cmf-module-3-04-lesson-09','cognizen-crypto-mastery-foundations-production','Circuit Breakers and Market-Regime Checklist','cmf-module-3-04','text','### Circuit Breakers\n\nA regime-aware framework may pause or reduce activity when:\n\n- Volatility exceeds a threshold\n- Liquidity falls below a minimum\n- Daily loss exceeds a limit\n- Stablecoin pricing becomes unreliable\n- Exchange data fails\n- Correlation rises sharply\n- Market structure becomes unclear\n\nA circuit breaker is not a prediction.\n\nIt is a protective response to conditions outside the strategy’s normal operating range.\n\n---\n\n### Regime Journal\n\nA regime journal records the market environment assumed at each decision.\n\nA useful entry may include the date, asset, timeframe, regime classification, confidence level, volatility, liquidity, market structure and selected strategy.\n\nAfter the position closes, the participant can review:\n\n- Whether the regime was classified reasonably\n- Whether the strategy matched it\n- Whether the regime changed during the trade\n- Whether the position was adjusted appropriately\n- Whether loss resulted from misclassification or normal strategy variation\n\nThis prevents every loss from being explained vaguely as “the market changed.”\n\n---\n\n### A Practical Regime-Assessment Process\n\nBegin with the higher timeframe and identify the dominant structure. Determine whether the market is forming directional swings or remaining inside a range.\n\nNext, examine volatility. Compare current ATR, candle ranges or volatility bands with recent history. Decide whether movement is expanding or contracting.\n\nThen assess liquidity and participation. Review spread, order-book depth, trading volume and whether the movement is supported by spot demand or mainly derivatives activity.\n\nEvaluate the broader market. Consider breadth, Bitcoin’s structure, sector participation, stablecoin conditions and major financial-market influences.\n\nFinally, decide whether the evidence is sufficiently clear to activate a strategy. When evidence is mixed, reduce exposure or remain inactive.\n\nThe assessment should end with an invalidation statement:\n\n**What evidence would show that my regime classification is wrong?**\n\n---\n\n### Example: Persistent Bull Trend\n\nSuppose the weekly chart shows higher highs and higher lows. The daily chart remains above a rising long-term average, and pullbacks occur on declining volume.\n\nMarket breadth is improving, while funding remains positive but not extreme.\n\nA trend-following or pullback-continuation strategy may be appropriate.\n\nRepeatedly shorting RSI overbought readings would conflict with the regime.\n\nThe assessment changes if price breaks the higher-timeframe structural low, breadth deteriorates and leverage becomes excessive.\n\n---\n\n### Example: Stable Range\n\nSuppose price has traded between 90 and 110 for several months.\n\nMoving averages are flat, ADX is low and volume increases near the boundaries.\n\nA mean-reversion strategy may buy confirmed rejection near 90 and reduce near the midpoint or upper range.\n\nA breakout strategy may remain inactive until price closes beyond the range with follow-through.\n\nIf volatility expands and price gains acceptance above 110, the mean-reversion regime is no longer valid.\n\n---\n\n### Example: Compression Before Expansion\n\nSuppose Bollinger Bands narrow, ATR declines and price forms a tight triangle.\n\nVolume becomes lower, while open interest increases.\n\nThe market is storing potential energy, but direction remains uncertain.\n\nA participant may avoid taking repeated mean-reversion trades near the centre and instead prepare for a confirmed breakout.\n\nBecause open interest is increasing, the eventual move may be accelerated by liquidations.\n\nThe first movement beyond the triangle still requires confirmation.\n\n---\n\n### Example: Liquidity Crisis\n\nSuppose price falls rapidly across most digital assets.\n\nSpreads widen, stablecoin pools become imbalanced and open interest collapses.\n\nSeveral technically oversold assets appear attractive.\n\nThis is not an ordinary mean-reversion environment.\n\nIt is a deleveraging and weak-liquidity regime.\n\nPosition sizes should be reduced substantially. Leverage may be prohibited, and entries may require stronger evidence of stabilisation.\n\nCapital preservation takes priority over buying every statistical extreme.\n\n---\n\n### Example: Transition Into Recovery\n\nSuppose a market has been declining for months.\n\nPrice stops creating lower lows, selling volume weakens and several bearish breakdowns fail.\n\nThe market remains below major weekly resistance, so a confirmed bull trend has not yet developed.\n\nSelective mean-reversion or tactical recovery positions may be possible, but full trend exposure may remain premature.\n\nThe regime is transitional.\n\nUncertainty should be reflected in position size.\n\n---\n\n### Market-Regime Checklist\n\nBefore selecting a strategy, consider the following questions:\n\n1. What timeframe controls the decision?\n\n2. Is the market trending, ranging or transitioning?\n\n3. What does the sequence of major highs and lows show?\n\n4. Are moving averages rising, falling or flat?\n\n5. Is volatility expanding or contracting?\n\n6. How does current volatility compare with historical conditions?\n\n7. Are spreads and order-book depth normal?\n\n8. Is liquidity strengthening or deteriorating?\n\n9. Does volume support the market movement?\n\n10. Is spot activity or leveraged derivatives activity dominant?\n\n11. What is happening to open interest and funding?\n\n12. Is market participation broad or narrow?\n\n13. Are asset correlations increasing?\n\n14. Is the broader environment risk-on or risk-off?\n\n15. Are stablecoins functioning normally?\n\n16. Is a major fundamental or macroeconomic event affecting price?\n\n17. Which strategy assumption best matches the evidence?\n\n18. Which strategy should be suspended?\n\n19. How confident is the regime classification?\n\n20. How should position size change?\n\n21. What evidence would invalidate the classification?\n\n22. What happens if the regime changes immediately after entry?\n\n---','markdown',NULL,NULL,NULL,6,0,0,0,'',NULL,9,1785297600000 WHERE EXISTS (SELECT 1 FROM `courses` WHERE `id`='cognizen-crypto-mastery-foundations-production');
--> statement-breakpoint
INSERT OR IGNORE INTO `lessons` (`id`,`course_id`,`title`,`section_id`,`lesson_type`,`content`,`content_format`,`video_key`,`primary_asset_id`,`intro_asset_id`,`duration_minutes`,`is_preview`,`available_after_days`,`required_watch_percent`,`transcript`,`experience_json`,`position`,`updated_at`) SELECT 'cmf-module-3-04-lesson-10','cognizen-crypto-mastery-foundations-production','Common Market-Regime Mistakes and Key Takeaway','cmf-module-3-04','text','### Common Market-Regime Mistakes\n\nA frequent mistake is applying one favourite strategy to every environment. A trader who prefers mean reversion may continue buying declines throughout a bear trend. A breakout trader may repeatedly enter false moves during a stable range.\n\nAnother error is classifying the regime according to one indicator. A moving-average crossover, RSI reading or volatility spike cannot describe the complete market environment.\n\nParticipants may also recognise regime changes only after large losses have occurred. They continue using the old strategy because it worked during the previous period.\n\nA further mistake is increasing leverage during low volatility without considering that compression often precedes expansion.\n\nFinally, traders may overcomplicate regime analysis by using so many indicators that no clear decision can be made. A regime model should improve strategy selection, not create permanent uncertainty.\n\n---\n\n### Common Misunderstandings\n\n### “The Market Has One Regime at a Time”\n\nDifferent timeframes and sectors can experience different conditions simultaneously.\n\n### “Bullish Means Low Risk”\n\nA bullish regime may contain excessive leverage, poor liquidity and extreme valuation.\n\n### “High Volatility Means a Strong Trend”\n\nPrice can move violently in both directions without directional persistence.\n\n### “Low Volatility Means the Market Is Safe”\n\nCompression can precede a major breakout or liquidation event.\n\n### “A Regime Filter Eliminates Losing Trades”\n\nIt may improve alignment but cannot prevent misclassification or unexpected events.\n\n### “A Strategy That Stops Working Is Permanently Broken”\n\nIt may be experiencing an unfavourable regime, although genuine strategy deterioration must still be investigated.\n\n### “Historical Regimes Are Easy to Trade”\n\nThey are clear only after the outcome is known.\n\n### “More Complex Regime Models Are More Accurate”\n\nComplexity can increase overfitting and reduce interpretability.\n\n### “Cash Means Missing Opportunities”\n\nCash preserves optionality when no strategy has a favourable environment.\n\n### “Strategy Diversification Guarantees Portfolio Diversification”\n\nSeveral strategies may share the same leverage, liquidity or market-direction risk.\n\n---\n\n### Module Summary\n\nA market regime is a period during which characteristics such as direction, volatility, liquidity, correlation and risk appetite remain sufficiently consistent to influence strategy performance.\n\nImportant regimes include persistent bull and bear trends, stable ranges, volatility compression, volatility expansion, deleveraging, capitulation, recovery and transition.\n\nTrend-following strategies are generally aligned with persistent directional markets.\n\nMean-reversion strategies are better suited to stable ranges or temporary deviations.\n\nBreakout strategies may be appropriate after compression when price gains acceptance beyond a clear boundary.\n\nMomentum strategies may perform well during directional volatility expansion.\n\nCarry and yield strategies depend on stable liquidity, collateral and credit conditions and can fail abruptly during stress.\n\nMarket regimes should be assessed using several sources of evidence, including price structure, volatility, volume, liquidity, breadth, derivatives positioning, stablecoin conditions and broader financial markets.\n\nRegime classification is never certain.\n\nIndicators often lag, timeframes may conflict and transitions can produce repeated false signals.\n\nThe purpose of regime analysis is not to predict every change.\n\nIt is to avoid applying a strategy in an environment that directly contradicts its assumptions.\n\nWhen the regime is clear, use the strategy designed for it.\n\nWhen the evidence is mixed, reduce exposure.\n\nWhen the environment is outside the strategy’s normal operating conditions, preserving capital may be the most advanced decision available.\n\n---\n\n### Key Takeaway\n\nA strategy does not operate in isolation.\n\nIt succeeds or fails partly because the surrounding market rewards or punishes the behaviour it was designed to exploit.\n\nTrend strategies need persistence. Mean-reversion strategies need a stable equilibrium. Breakout strategies need expansion and acceptance. Yield strategies need functioning liquidity and credit.\n\nBefore selecting the trade, identify the environment.\n\nWhen the regime changes, the strategy must change—or step aside.\n\nThe next module is **3.5: Multi-Timeframe Analysis and Trade Planning**.','markdown',NULL,NULL,NULL,5,0,0,0,'',NULL,10,1785297600000 WHERE EXISTS (SELECT 1 FROM `courses` WHERE `id`='cognizen-crypto-mastery-foundations-production');
--> statement-breakpoint
INSERT OR IGNORE INTO `lessons` (`id`,`course_id`,`title`,`section_id`,`lesson_type`,`content`,`content_format`,`video_key`,`primary_asset_id`,`intro_asset_id`,`duration_minutes`,`is_preview`,`available_after_days`,`required_watch_percent`,`transcript`,`experience_json`,`position`,`updated_at`) SELECT 'cmf-module-3-04-lesson-11','cognizen-crypto-mastery-foundations-production','Check your understanding','cmf-module-3-04','text','### Check your understanding\n\nAnswer these questions to self-assess your understanding before moving on.\n\n1. What is a market regime?\n\n2. Why is market direction alone insufficient to define a regime?\n\n3. How does a low-volatility regime differ from a high-volatility regime?\n\n4. Why can liquidity deteriorate during market stress?\n\n5. What characterises a risk-on environment?\n\n6. What characterises a risk-off environment?\n\n7. Why do correlations often rise during crises?\n\n8. What is a deleveraging regime?\n\n9. How does a persistent bull trend differ from a parabolic bull regime?\n\n10. Why are mean-reversion strategies dangerous in a persistent bear trend?\n\n11. What is capitulation?\n\n12. Why should oversold indicators be treated cautiously during capitulation?\n\n13. What characteristics support a stable range regime?\n\n14. How does a violent sideways market differ from a stable range?\n\n15. Why can volatility compression precede a major move?\n\n16. What is market acceptance?\n\n17. What evidence may indicate transition from a range to a trend?\n\n18. What evidence may indicate transition from a trend to a range?\n\n19. Why are transition regimes difficult to trade?\n\n20. How can moving-average slope support regime analysis?\n\n21. What does ATR reveal about a market regime?\n\n22. What is volatility clustering?\n\n23. How can market breadth improve regime analysis?\n\n24. What does relative strength reveal?\n\n25. Why should derivatives open interest be examined?\n\n26. How can extreme funding reveal regime fragility?\n\n27. Why are stablecoin conditions relevant to the broader market regime?\n\n28. How can macroeconomic conditions influence digital asset risk appetite?\n\n29. Why can different timeframes produce different regime classifications?\n\n30. Which strategies are generally aligned with persistent trends?\n\n31. Which strategies are generally aligned with stable ranges?\n\n32. Why may breakout strategies be appropriate after volatility compression?\n\n33. What risks affect yield and carry strategies during a crisis?\n\n34. Why can relative-value relationships break?\n\n35. When may holding cash be an appropriate strategy?\n\n36. What is regime confidence?\n\n37. How can position size be adjusted according to regime confidence?\n\n38. What is volatility targeting?\n\n39. What is risk budgeting?\n\n40. Why should portfolio heat decline during high-correlation stress?\n\n41. What is regime misclassification?\n\n42. Why do lagging indicators delay regime recognition?\n\n43. How can conflicting evidence affect strategy selection?\n\n44. What is an adaptive strategy?\n\n45. What overfitting risks accompany adaptive systems?\n\n46. What is a regime filter?\n\n47. Why must regime labels in a backtest use only information available at the time?\n\n48. What is regime probability?\n\n49. What should a regime stress test examine?\n\n50. What information should be recorded in a regime journal?','markdown',NULL,NULL,NULL,6,0,0,0,'',NULL,11,1785297600000 WHERE EXISTS (SELECT 1 FROM `courses` WHERE `id`='cognizen-crypto-mastery-foundations-production');
--> statement-breakpoint
INSERT OR IGNORE INTO `course_sections` (`id`,`course_id`,`title`,`position`,`created_at`) SELECT 'cmf-module-3-05','cognizen-crypto-mastery-foundations-production','Module 3.5: Multi-Timeframe Analysis and Trade Planning',6,1785297600000 WHERE EXISTS (SELECT 1 FROM `courses` WHERE `id`='cognizen-crypto-mastery-foundations-production');
