INSERT OR IGNORE INTO `lessons` (`id`,`course_id`,`title`,`section_id`,`lesson_type`,`content`,`content_format`,`video_key`,`primary_asset_id`,`intro_asset_id`,`duration_minutes`,`is_preview`,`available_after_days`,`required_watch_percent`,`transcript`,`experience_json`,`position`,`updated_at`) SELECT 'cmf-module-3-05-lesson-01','cognizen-crypto-mastery-foundations-production','What Is Multi-Timeframe Analysis? and Timeframe Hierarchy','cmf-module-3-05','text','### Learning Objectives\n\nBy the end of this module, you should be able to analyse the same market across several timeframes without becoming confused by conflicting signals. You should understand how to assign a specific purpose to each timeframe, distinguish major structure from short-term noise and align a trade with the broader market regime.\n\nYou should also be able to convert an analysis into a complete trade plan containing an entry, invalidation level, position size, exit method and contingency rules. The objective is to ensure that every position is based on a coherent process rather than an isolated chart pattern or indicator signal.\n\n### Introduction\n\nA cryptocurrency can appear bullish, bearish and sideways at the same time.\n\nOn a monthly chart, it may be advancing within a long-term bull market. On a daily chart, it may be experiencing a substantial correction. On an hourly chart, it may be recovering from an oversold condition. On a five-minute chart, it may be consolidating within a narrow range.\n\nThese observations do not necessarily contradict one another.\n\nThey describe different layers of the same market.\n\nMulti-timeframe analysis is the process of examining those layers in an organised way. It allows the participant to separate the broader market context from the immediate entry decision.\n\nWithout this structure, a trader can easily make inconsistent decisions. They may enter a position because of a bullish five-minute candle while ignoring a major weekly resistance level. When the trade moves against them, they may switch to the daily chart and describe the position as a long-term investment.\n\nThis is not genuine multi-timeframe analysis.\n\nIt is changing the analytical framework after the outcome becomes uncomfortable.\n\nA disciplined approach assigns each timeframe a role before the trade begins. The higher timeframe defines the environment. The middle timeframe identifies the setup. The lower timeframe may refine execution.\n\nThe final trade plan then connects those observations to risk.\n\n### What Is Multi-Timeframe Analysis?\n\nMulti-timeframe analysis examines an asset over more than one chart interval.\n\nA timeframe determines the period represented by each candle or bar. A daily candle summarises one day of trading, while a weekly candle summarises an entire week.\n\nHigher timeframes compress more market activity into every candle. They generally reveal broader trends, major support and resistance and longer-term market cycles.\n\nLower timeframes display more detail. They may help identify short-term momentum, precise entries and immediate changes in market structure.\n\nThe purpose is not to inspect as many timeframes as possible. Too many charts can create contradictory information and decision paralysis.\n\nThe objective is to select a small number of related timeframes and assign each one a defined function.\n\n### The Fractal Nature of Markets\n\nFinancial markets are often described as fractal because similar structures appear at different scales.\n\nAn uptrend on a weekly chart may contain several daily corrections. Each daily correction may contain hourly downtrends and smaller intraday recoveries.\n\nPatterns such as ranges, breakouts, pullbacks and reversals can occur on almost every timeframe.\n\nHowever, their significance is not equal.\n\nA breakout from a weekly consolidation generally represents more trading activity than a breakout from a five-minute range. A weekly structural level is likely to attract a broader group of market participants.\n\nLower-timeframe structures can be useful, but they should be interpreted within the higher-timeframe environment.\n\n### Major and Minor Structure\n\nMajor structure refers to the swing highs, swing lows, support areas and resistance zones that define the broader market.\n\nMinor structure consists of the smaller movements occurring inside those larger boundaries.\n\nSuppose the weekly chart shows a strong uptrend. Price then begins a daily decline.\n\nThe daily decline may be significant, but it remains a correction within the larger bullish structure until an important weekly level fails.\n\nInside the daily correction, an hourly chart may show a sequence of lower highs and lower lows.\n\nA short-term trader can participate in that hourly downtrend. A long-term investor may view it as a possible opportunity to accumulate near higher-timeframe support.\n\nBoth participants can be analysing the market correctly because their objectives differ.\n\nThe error occurs when the participant does not know which structure controls the decision.\n\n### Timeframe Hierarchy\n\nA useful framework uses three analytical levels.\n\n| Analytical level | Primary purpose |\n| --- | --- |\n| Higher timeframe | Defines trend, regime and major risk areas |\n| Decision timeframe | Identifies the setup and structural invalidation |\n| Execution timeframe | Refines entry and immediate trade management |\n\nThe labels are more important than the exact chart intervals.\n\nFor a long-term investor, the higher timeframe may be monthly, the decision timeframe weekly and the execution timeframe daily.\n\nFor a swing trader, the hierarchy may be weekly, daily and four-hour.\n\nFor an intraday trader, it may be four-hour, one-hour and fifteen-minute.\n\nThe timeframes should be far enough apart to provide different information but close enough to remain connected.','markdown',NULL,NULL,NULL,6,0,0,0,'',NULL,1,1785297600000 WHERE EXISTS (SELECT 1 FROM `courses` WHERE `id`='cognizen-crypto-mastery-foundations-production');
--> statement-breakpoint
INSERT OR IGNORE INTO `lessons` (`id`,`course_id`,`title`,`section_id`,`lesson_type`,`content`,`content_format`,`video_key`,`primary_asset_id`,`intro_asset_id`,`duration_minutes`,`is_preview`,`available_after_days`,`required_watch_percent`,`transcript`,`experience_json`,`position`,`updated_at`) SELECT 'cmf-module-3-05-lesson-02','cognizen-crypto-mastery-foundations-production','Selecting Related Timeframes and Top-Down Analysis','cmf-module-3-05','text','### Selecting Related Timeframes\n\nOne common approach uses timeframes separated by approximately four to six times.\n\nFor example:\n\nWeekly, daily and four-hour\n\nDaily, four-hour and one-hour\n\nFour-hour, one-hour and fifteen-minute\n\nThis is only a guideline.\n\nThe correct combination depends on how long the position is expected to remain open.\n\nA trade intended to last several weeks should not be managed mainly through one-minute candles. Those candles contain substantial noise relative to the holding period.\n\nSimilarly, a leveraged intraday trade cannot rely only on monthly support because liquidation may occur long before that level becomes relevant.\n\n### The Higher-Timeframe Role\n\nThe higher timeframe establishes context.\n\nIt helps answer the following questions:\n\nIs the broader market trending or ranging?\n\nWhere are the major structural highs and lows?\n\nIs price near important support or resistance?\n\nIs the asset extended or correcting?\n\nWhich direction currently has the stronger evidence?\n\nIs the market in a mature or early-stage trend?\n\nThe higher timeframe should not determine every entry automatically.\n\nIt provides a directional and risk framework.\n\nFor example, a weekly uptrend may encourage the participant to prioritise long setups. It does not mean every short-term decline should be purchased immediately.\n\n### The Decision Timeframe\n\nThe decision timeframe contains the setup.\n\nThis is where the participant defines:\n\nEntry conditions\n\nMarket structure\n\nInvalidation\n\nPotential target\n\nExpected holding period\n\nSuppose the weekly market is bullish and approaching a major support area.\n\nOn the daily chart, price may form a higher low, reject support and break above short-term resistance.\n\nThat daily structure may provide the actual reason for entering.\n\nThe position should not be justified only by the weekly trend. The decision timeframe should show a specific opportunity with controllable risk.\n\n### The Execution Timeframe\n\nThe execution timeframe is optional.\n\nIt may be used to improve entry precision, reduce stop distance or observe immediate confirmation.\n\nFor example, after identifying a daily bullish setup, the participant might use the four-hour chart to wait for a higher low and breakout.\n\nThis can improve the entry.\n\nIt can also cause overanalysis.\n\nA lower-timeframe signal may prevent entry into a valid higher-timeframe setup because the participant waits for perfect confirmation that never occurs.\n\nThe execution timeframe should refine the plan, not override it without a clear rule.\n\n### Timeframe Alignment\n\nTimeframe alignment occurs when the selected charts support the same directional interpretation.\n\nFor example:\n\nWeekly chart: established uptrend\n\nDaily chart: pullback into support\n\nFour-hour chart: bullish structural reversal\n\nThis alignment may create a stronger long setup because the broader direction, setup location and execution signal support one another.\n\nPerfect alignment is uncommon.\n\nBy the time every timeframe becomes clearly bullish, much of the movement may already have occurred.\n\nAlignment improves confirmation but can reduce entry quality.\n\nThe participant must balance evidence against extension.\n\n### Timeframe Conflict\n\nTimeframes often disagree.\n\nSuppose:\n\nWeekly chart remains bullish\n\nDaily chart is in a correction\n\nFour-hour chart is bearish\n\nOne-hour chart begins recovering\n\nThe correct interpretation depends on the intended strategy.\n\nA trend-following swing trader may wait for the daily correction to stabilise before entering.\n\nA short-term trader may trade the four-hour downtrend with a target near weekly support.\n\nA long-term investor may make a limited staged purchase if the fundamental thesis remains valid.\n\nThe conflict is not a problem when the participant knows which timeframe governs the position.\n\nIt becomes dangerous when they switch timeframes to avoid admitting that the original trade failed.\n\n### Directional Bias\n\nA directional bias is a preference based on the higher-timeframe evidence.\n\nA bullish bias means long setups receive priority. A bearish bias gives preference to short or defensive strategies. A neutral bias may favour range trading or reduced exposure.\n\nBias is not certainty.\n\nA bullish higher-timeframe market can still produce successful short trades. A bearish market can produce powerful rallies.\n\nThe bias helps filter opportunities. It should not prevent the participant from recognising contradictory evidence.\n\nA useful statement might be:\n\n“The weekly structure remains bullish while the latest major higher low holds. I will prioritise long setups, but a weekly close below that level will require reassessment.”\n\nThis is conditional and testable.\n\n### Top-Down Analysis\n\nTop-down analysis begins with the broadest selected timeframe and moves toward the execution chart.\n\nA structured top-down process may begin by identifying the primary trend and major levels on the higher timeframe. The analyst then moves to the decision timeframe to evaluate whether price is trending, consolidating or reversing near those areas.\n\nOnly after a valid setup is found does the analyst move to the execution timeframe.\n\nStarting on the lowest timeframe can create tunnel vision. A small price movement may appear important because the broader context is not visible.\n\nTop-down analysis prevents a minor signal from receiving greater importance than a major structural level.','markdown',NULL,NULL,NULL,6,0,0,0,'',NULL,2,1785297600000 WHERE EXISTS (SELECT 1 FROM `courses` WHERE `id`='cognizen-crypto-mastery-foundations-production');
--> statement-breakpoint
INSERT OR IGNORE INTO `lessons` (`id`,`course_id`,`title`,`section_id`,`lesson_type`,`content`,`content_format`,`video_key`,`primary_asset_id`,`intro_asset_id`,`duration_minutes`,`is_preview`,`available_after_days`,`required_watch_percent`,`transcript`,`experience_json`,`position`,`updated_at`) SELECT 'cmf-module-3-05-lesson-03','cognizen-crypto-mastery-foundations-production','Bottom-Up Analysis and Indicator Signals Across Timeframes','cmf-module-3-05','text','### Bottom-Up Analysis\n\nBottom-up analysis begins with lower-timeframe activity and then checks the broader charts.\n\nThis may be useful for detecting early changes.\n\nFor example, a one-hour reversal may appear before the daily candle reflects any improvement.\n\nHowever, lower-timeframe reversals occur frequently and often fail.\n\nBottom-up signals should therefore be tested against the higher-timeframe environment.\n\nA short-term reversal near major weekly support is more meaningful than the same pattern in the middle of an established weekly downtrend.\n\n### Higher-Timeframe Support and Resistance\n\nHigher-timeframe levels usually represent a greater amount of historical activity.\n\nThey may be associated with:\n\nPrevious cycle highs\n\nMajor lows\n\nLong consolidations\n\nLarge-volume areas\n\nStructural breakouts\n\nPrice may react before reaching the exact level or temporarily move through it.\n\nThese areas should be treated as zones.\n\nA lower-timeframe entry near a higher-timeframe zone can provide attractive risk-to-reward because the invalidation point may be relatively close.\n\nHowever, the mere presence of support does not prove that buyers will defend it.\n\nThe decision timeframe should demonstrate actual response.\n\n### Higher-Timeframe Trend, Lower-Timeframe Pullback\n\nOne of the most common multi-timeframe setups occurs when a lower-timeframe pullback develops inside a higher-timeframe trend.\n\nSuppose the weekly chart shows an uptrend. The daily chart begins declining toward previous resistance that may now act as support.\n\nThe participant does not need to buy immediately.\n\nThey may wait for the daily selling pressure to weaken and then use a four-hour structural reversal for execution.\n\nThe analytical sequence is:\n\nHigher timeframe identifies the bullish environment.\n\nDecision timeframe identifies the pullback location.\n\nExecution timeframe confirms that buyers are returning.\n\nThe invalidation remains connected to the decision timeframe.\n\nThe stop should not be based only on a tiny execution-timeframe fluctuation when the thesis depends on a larger daily structure.\n\n### Higher-Timeframe Range, Lower-Timeframe Movement\n\nA lower timeframe can show strong trends while the higher timeframe remains inside a range.\n\nFor example, price may move rapidly from weekly support toward weekly resistance.\n\nAn hourly trend follower may profit from this movement.\n\nHowever, buying near the upper weekly boundary based solely on hourly momentum may produce poor risk-to-reward.\n\nThe higher-timeframe range helps define where the lower-timeframe trend may encounter stronger opposition.\n\nThis does not guarantee reversal. It identifies where the existing strategy requires greater caution.\n\n### Higher-Timeframe Trend Reversal\n\nA lower-timeframe reversal does not automatically change the higher-timeframe trend.\n\nA weekly downtrend may contain several bullish daily rallies.\n\nFor a genuine higher-timeframe reversal, the market may need to break an important lower high and develop higher highs and higher lows on the weekly chart.\n\nEarlier entries can be taken from lower timeframes, but they should be recognised as countertrend or transitional positions.\n\nTheir size and expectations should reflect the lower level of confirmation.\n\n### Multi-Timeframe Confirmation\n\nConfirmation may come from several sources.\n\nA higher-timeframe support area may align with a daily oversold condition and a four-hour bullish break of structure.\n\nThis is stronger than three similar momentum indicators on the same chart because the evidence comes from different analytical levels.\n\nHowever, confirmation should not become endless.\n\nIf the participant requires the weekly, daily, four-hour, hourly and fifteen-minute charts to agree perfectly, the entry may occur only after the opportunity has become overextended.\n\nThe trade plan should specify the minimum evidence required.\n\n### Timeframe Dominance\n\nWhen timeframes conflict, the higher timeframe generally deserves greater strategic weight.\n\nThis does not mean the higher timeframe always predicts the next movement.\n\nIt means the broader structure can influence:\n\nPotential target\n\nLikely opposition\n\nPosition duration\n\nMaximum expected movement\n\nA daily short trade against a weekly uptrend may be reasonable, but it should recognise that strong weekly support could limit the decline.\n\nThe lower timeframe may control execution, while the higher timeframe controls expectations.\n\n### The Error of Timeframe Switching\n\nTimeframe switching occurs when a participant changes the analytical horizon after entering a losing position.\n\nA short-term trade may fail, but the trader opens a daily or weekly chart and decides to hold.\n\nThis usually means that the original invalidation was ignored.\n\nA legitimate change in time horizon must occur through a new analysis. The position should be closed or resized according to the original plan before a separate investment decision is made.\n\nA trade should not become an investment simply because selling would realise a loss.\n\n### Indicator Signals Across Timeframes\n\nAn indicator can produce different readings on each timeframe.\n\nRSI may be overbought on an hourly chart while remaining neutral on a daily chart.\n\nA short-term moving average may be rising while the weekly average continues falling.\n\nThese signals describe different periods.\n\nThe analyst should not combine them without understanding what each one measures.\n\nA useful rule is that higher-timeframe indicators define context, while decision-timeframe indicators may support the setup.\n\nLower-timeframe indicators should not be used to invalidate a higher-timeframe thesis unless the plan specifically gives them that authority.','markdown',NULL,NULL,NULL,6,0,0,0,'',NULL,3,1785297600000 WHERE EXISTS (SELECT 1 FROM `courses` WHERE `id`='cognizen-crypto-mastery-foundations-production');
--> statement-breakpoint
INSERT OR IGNORE INTO `lessons` (`id`,`course_id`,`title`,`section_id`,`lesson_type`,`content`,`content_format`,`video_key`,`primary_asset_id`,`intro_asset_id`,`duration_minutes`,`is_preview`,`available_after_days`,`required_watch_percent`,`transcript`,`experience_json`,`position`,`updated_at`) SELECT 'cmf-module-3-05-lesson-04','cognizen-crypto-mastery-foundations-production','Volume Across Timeframes and Invalidation','cmf-module-3-05','text','### Volume Across Timeframes\n\nVolume should be interpreted according to the chart interval and trading venue.\n\nA large hourly volume spike may reflect a short liquidation event. A sustained increase in weekly spot volume may indicate broader participation.\n\nWhen a lower-timeframe breakout occurs near a higher-timeframe level, volume can help determine whether the move has enough participation to change the larger structure.\n\nOne brief spike is less convincing than sustained activity and follow-through.\n\n### Volatility Across Timeframes\n\nShort-term volatility may expand while long-term volatility remains relatively low.\n\nFor example, a large intraday movement may appear dramatic but remain small compared with the weekly range.\n\nStop distance and position size should be connected to the timeframe controlling the trade.\n\nA daily trade using a stop based on five-minute volatility may exit repeatedly.\n\nA short-term trade using weekly volatility may create an unnecessarily large loss.\n\n### From Analysis to Trade Plan\n\nAnalysis describes the market.\n\nA trade plan states what the participant will do.\n\nA market view is incomplete until it includes:\n\nConditions required for entry\n\nInvalidation\n\nPosition size\n\nTarget or exit method\n\nAlternative scenarios\n\nFor example, saying “Bitcoin looks bullish” is an opinion.\n\nA trade plan might state:\n\n“The weekly structure remains bullish above the last major higher low. The daily chart is pulling back toward former resistance. I will enter only if the four-hour chart forms a higher low and closes above short-term resistance. The trade is invalid below the daily support zone. Position size will limit loss to the predefined risk allowance.”\n\nThe second statement is actionable and testable.\n\n### The Components of a Trade Plan\n\nA complete plan should define the market, strategy and timeframe.\n\nIt should explain why the opportunity exists, where the participant will enter and what evidence would prove the analysis wrong.\n\nIt should also define the amount of capital exposed, the expected exit method and what happens if the market moves differently from the preferred scenario.\n\nThe plan should be written before the order is placed.\n\nOnce capital is at risk, emotional pressure makes objective decision-making more difficult.\n\n### Define the Instrument\n\nThe plan should identify the exact instrument.\n\nThis includes:\n\nSpot asset\n\nFutures contract\n\nPerpetual contract\n\nOption\n\nExchange\n\nTrading pair\n\nBlockchain network\n\nTrading BTC against a stablecoin is different from trading a leveraged perpetual contract.\n\nThe chart may look similar, but the instrument introduces different funding, liquidation, custody and counterparty risks.\n\nThe plan should never refer only to the asset name when the actual position uses a derivative.\n\n### Define the Strategy\n\nThe plan should state whether the position is based on:\n\nTrend following\n\nMean reversion\n\nBreakout\n\nMomentum\n\nRelative value\n\nHedge\n\nLong-term investment\n\nThis prevents the strategy from changing after entry.\n\nA failed breakout should not become a mean-reversion trade unless the original position is managed according to its rules and a new analysis is completed.\n\nEach strategy has different expectations and exit logic.\n\n### Define the Time Horizon\n\nThe expected holding period influences:\n\nChart selection\n\nStop distance\n\nTarget\n\nTransaction costs\n\nMonitoring frequency\n\nA position expected to last hours should have a different management process from one expected to last months.\n\nThe time horizon can be approximate. It should still be stated.\n\nA time stop may be used when the expected movement does not begin within a reasonable period.\n\n### Entry Trigger\n\nThe entry trigger is the specific event that authorises the position.\n\nExamples include:\n\nCandle close above resistance\n\nSuccessful retest\n\nHigher low at support\n\nReturn inside a volatility band\n\nMoving-average crossover\n\nBreak of short-term structure\n\nThe trigger should be observable.\n\n“Enter when the market feels strong” is too vague to evaluate consistently.\n\nA precise trigger reduces impulsive entries and improves backtesting.\n\n### Entry Zone Versus Exact Price\n\nSome plans use an exact price.\n\nOthers define a zone.\n\nA zone may be more realistic when support or resistance covers a range of prices.\n\nFor example, a plan may permit entry between 98 and 101 after confirmation.\n\nThe position-size calculation should use the actual execution price.\n\nIf the market moves beyond the acceptable zone, the participant should not chase it unless the plan defines an alternative entry.\n\n### Invalidation\n\nInvalidation is the market evidence that shows the trade thesis is no longer sufficiently credible.\n\nFor a breakout, invalidation may occur when price closes back inside the range.\n\nFor a pullback trade, it may occur when important support fails.\n\nFor a mean-reversion trade, it may occur when the market gains acceptance beyond the previous boundary.\n\nInvalidation should be connected to the strategy.\n\nA random five-percent stop has no analytical meaning unless five percent represents a relevant volatility or structural distance.','markdown',NULL,NULL,NULL,6,0,0,0,'',NULL,4,1785297600000 WHERE EXISTS (SELECT 1 FROM `courses` WHERE `id`='cognizen-crypto-mastery-foundations-production');
--> statement-breakpoint
INSERT OR IGNORE INTO `lessons` (`id`,`course_id`,`title`,`section_id`,`lesson_type`,`content`,`content_format`,`video_key`,`primary_asset_id`,`intro_asset_id`,`duration_minutes`,`is_preview`,`available_after_days`,`required_watch_percent`,`transcript`,`experience_json`,`position`,`updated_at`) SELECT 'cmf-module-3-05-lesson-05','cognizen-crypto-mastery-foundations-production','Stop-Loss Placement and No-Trade Conditions','cmf-module-3-05','text','### Stop-Loss Placement\n\nThe stop is the execution mechanism intended to limit loss after invalidation.\n\nThe stop may be based on:\n\nMarket structure\n\nVolatility\n\nClosing price\n\nIntraperiod price\n\nTime\n\nA combination of conditions\n\nThe stop and invalidation are related but not always identical.\n\nFor example, a strategy may consider the setup invalid after a daily close below support but maintain an emergency stop farther away to protect against a severe intraday event.\n\nThe plan should state which rule has priority.\n\n### Position Sizing\n\nOnce entry and stop levels are defined, position size can be calculated.\n\nThe simplified formula is:\n\nPosition quantity = Maximum capital at risk ÷ Risk per unit\n\nSuppose:\n\nAccount capital: 100,000 units\n\nMaximum risk: 0.75 percent\n\nRisk allowance: 750 units\n\nEntry: 250\n\nStop: 235\n\nRisk per token: 15\n\nPosition quantity:\n\n750 ÷ 15 = 50 tokens\n\nPosition value:\n\n50 × 250 = 12,500 units\n\nThis calculation should include expected fees and slippage.\n\n### Planned Risk Versus Actual Risk\n\nPlanned risk assumes the stop executes near the expected price.\n\nActual loss may be larger because of:\n\nSlippage\n\nPrice gaps\n\nExchange outages\n\nNetwork congestion\n\nLiquidity withdrawal\n\nStop failure\n\nA trade in a liquid spot market may track planned risk more closely than a leveraged position in an illiquid token.\n\nPosition size should reflect execution uncertainty.\n\n### Target Selection\n\nTargets may be based on:\n\nPrevious high or low\n\nHigher-timeframe support or resistance\n\nRange projection\n\nMoving average\n\nVWAP\n\nRisk multiple\n\nValuation\n\nTrailing exit\n\nThe target should be realistic relative to the strategy.\n\nA mean-reversion trade may target the range midpoint.\n\nA trend-following position may avoid a fixed target and use a trailing stop.\n\nThe higher timeframe can reveal major barriers that are invisible on the entry chart.\n\n### Risk-to-Reward\n\nBefore entry, compare the potential loss with the plausible gain.\n\nSuppose:\n\nEntry: 100\n\nStop: 94\n\nTarget: 115\n\nRisk:\n\n100 − 94 = 6\n\nReward:\n\n115 − 100 = 15\n\nRisk-to-reward:\n\n6 to 15, or 1 to 2.5\n\nA favourable ratio does not guarantee a good trade.\n\nThe target must be credible and the probability must justify the risk.\n\n### Multiple Targets\n\nA plan may contain more than one target.\n\nThe participant might reduce part of the position at the first resistance level and manage the remainder with a trailing stop.\n\nThis can reduce risk while preserving exposure to a larger move.\n\nHowever, partial exits change the realised payoff ratio.\n\nThe strategy should evaluate the weighted result rather than describing the most distant target as though the entire position will reach it.\n\n### Time Stop\n\nA time stop exits when the expected movement fails to develop within a specified period.\n\nFor example, a breakout may be expected to show follow-through within three daily candles.\n\nIf price remains stagnant, the position may be closed even though the price stop has not been reached.\n\nA time stop releases capital and recognises that the original timing assumption may have been wrong.\n\n### Scenario Planning\n\nA robust trade plan contains more than one possible outcome.\n\nThe preferred scenario explains what should happen if the trade works.\n\nAn adverse scenario describes what will happen if the invalidation level is reached.\n\nA neutral scenario addresses consolidation or lack of follow-through.\n\nAn unexpected-event scenario considers:\n\nSecurity incident\n\nExchange outage\n\nSudden regulatory announcement\n\nStablecoin depeg\n\nNetwork failure\n\nThe participant does not need a response to every imaginable event. The major risks should not be considered for the first time after they occur.\n\n### The “If–Then” Format\n\nAn effective plan can be written using conditional statements.\n\nFor example:\n\n“If price closes above resistance on the daily chart and the four-hour retest holds, I will enter within the defined zone.”\n\n“If price closes back below the former resistance, I will exit.”\n\n“If price reaches the first target, I will reduce one-third of the position and adjust the stop according to the written rule.”\n\nConditional language reduces impulsive interpretation.\n\nIt makes clear that no action occurs until the evidence is present.\n\n### No-Trade Conditions\n\nA plan should identify conditions that cancel the opportunity.\n\nThese may include:\n\nEntry occurs too far from the planned zone\n\nSpread widens beyond the permitted limit\n\nMajor news is released\n\nLiquidity falls\n\nStablecoin pricing becomes unreliable\n\nPortfolio heat is already at its maximum\n\nAnother correlated position creates excessive exposure\n\nRisk-to-reward falls below the minimum\n\nA trade can be invalid before it is entered.\n\nNot participating is part of disciplined execution.','markdown',NULL,NULL,NULL,6,0,0,0,'',NULL,5,1785297600000 WHERE EXISTS (SELECT 1 FROM `courses` WHERE `id`='cognizen-crypto-mastery-foundations-production');
--> statement-breakpoint
INSERT OR IGNORE INTO `lessons` (`id`,`course_id`,`title`,`section_id`,`lesson_type`,`content`,`content_format`,`video_key`,`primary_asset_id`,`intro_asset_id`,`duration_minutes`,`is_preview`,`available_after_days`,`required_watch_percent`,`transcript`,`experience_json`,`position`,`updated_at`) SELECT 'cmf-module-3-05-lesson-06','cognizen-crypto-mastery-foundations-production','Monitoring Frequency and Reviewing Timeframe Errors','cmf-module-3-05','text','### Monitoring Frequency\n\nThe position should be monitored according to its timeframe.\n\nA weekly investment does not need to be reviewed every minute.\n\nConstantly watching lower-timeframe price changes can create emotional interference.\n\nA leveraged intraday position requires more active monitoring because liquidation and volatility risks are immediate.\n\nThe plan should state when the position will be reviewed, such as at the close of each decision-timeframe candle.\n\n### Alerts\n\nPrice and indicator alerts can reduce unnecessary chart watching.\n\nAn alert may be set near:\n\nEntry area\n\nInvalidation\n\nTarget\n\nMajor structural level\n\nVolatility threshold\n\nAlerts support discipline, but they should be configured carefully.\n\nA notification should trigger review rather than automatic emotional action unless the strategy is explicitly automated.\n\n### Trade Management\n\nTrade management begins after entry.\n\nA well-designed plan should minimise discretionary decisions during the position.\n\nThe participant should know in advance whether:\n\nStops may be moved\n\nAdditions are permitted\n\nPartial profits will be taken\n\nA time stop applies\n\nThe position may remain open through major events\n\nThe strategy permits overnight or weekend exposure\n\nUnplanned management usually reflects emotion rather than new evidence.\n\n### Moving the Stop\n\nA stop may be adjusted only according to predefined rules.\n\nPossible methods include:\n\nMoving below a new higher low\n\nTrailing by ATR\n\nMoving to break even after a defined profit\n\nFollowing a moving average\n\nTightening near major resistance\n\nMoving the stop farther away increases risk and generally violates the original plan.\n\nMoving it too quickly toward the entry may remove the position during normal volatility.\n\nThe market does not recognise the trader’s break-even price as a technical level.\n\n### Adding to the Position\n\nAdditional entries should be planned.\n\nA trend strategy may permit pyramiding after price confirms continuation.\n\nA staged investment may allow purchases at several predefined levels.\n\nThe plan should define:\n\nMaximum total size\n\nConditions for each addition\n\nRevised average price\n\nNew total risk\n\nUpdated invalidation\n\nAn addition should not cause the total loss at the stop to exceed the portfolio risk limit.\n\n### Reducing the Position\n\nReduction may occur when:\n\nFirst target is reached\n\nPosition becomes too large\n\nMomentum weakens\n\nHigher-timeframe resistance approaches\n\nEvent risk increases\n\nPortfolio correlation rises\n\nA reduction is not necessarily a statement that the entire thesis has failed.\n\nIt may simply control risk.\n\n### Event Management\n\nCryptocurrency markets operate continuously and can react sharply to scheduled and unscheduled events.\n\nA trade plan should consider whether the position will remain open through:\n\nNetwork upgrade\n\nToken unlock\n\nGovernance vote\n\nEconomic announcement\n\nRegulatory decision\n\nOptions expiry\n\nHolding through an event may produce a large favourable movement.\n\nIt may also cause slippage beyond the planned stop.\n\nThe decision should be intentional.\n\n### Overnight and Weekend Risk\n\nCryptocurrency trades continuously, but liquidity changes across hours and days.\n\nA position may face weaker liquidity during periods when fewer institutions and market makers are active.\n\nSpreads can widen and abnormal movements can occur more easily.\n\nAn intraday plan should specify whether positions may remain open beyond the intended session.\n\n### Trade Cancellation\n\nA pending plan should be cancelled when the evidence changes before entry.\n\nFor example, a bullish pullback setup may be invalidated when the higher-timeframe support breaks before the entry trigger occurs.\n\nThe participant should not continue waiting for the original signal simply because time was invested in the analysis.\n\nA planned trade has no financial or emotional entitlement to be executed.\n\n### Post-Trade Review\n\nAfter the trade closes, evaluate the quality of the process.\n\nThe relevant questions are not limited to whether money was made.\n\nReview whether:\n\nTimeframes were selected appropriately\n\nThe higher-timeframe bias was clear\n\nEntry matched the trigger\n\nPosition size was correct\n\nStop and target rules were followed\n\nAny timeframe switching occurred\n\nActual costs differed from assumptions\n\nThe market regime changed\n\nA profitable trade can contain poor decisions.\n\nA losing trade can be correctly planned and executed.\n\n### Trade Journal\n\nA trade journal converts experience into evidence.\n\nA useful entry should record the market, instrument, strategy and selected timeframes. It should include screenshots from the higher, decision and execution charts.\n\nThe journal should preserve the analysis as it existed before the outcome was known.\n\nIt can also record the participant’s emotional state. Fear, urgency, frustration and overconfidence can affect execution even when the technical plan is sound.\n\nOver time, the journal may reveal that certain timeframe combinations, market regimes or entry methods perform better than others.\n\n### Reviewing Timeframe Errors\n\nCommon timeframe errors include entering from a very low timeframe directly into major higher-timeframe resistance, placing the stop according to a chart too small for the thesis and managing a long-term position through short-term noise.\n\nThe journal should identify which timeframe controlled each decision.\n\nIf the answer changes after the trade begins, the process may be inconsistent.','markdown',NULL,NULL,NULL,6,0,0,0,'',NULL,6,1785297600000 WHERE EXISTS (SELECT 1 FROM `courses` WHERE `id`='cognizen-crypto-mastery-foundations-production');
--> statement-breakpoint
INSERT OR IGNORE INTO `lessons` (`id`,`course_id`,`title`,`section_id`,`lesson_type`,`content`,`content_format`,`video_key`,`primary_asset_id`,`intro_asset_id`,`duration_minutes`,`is_preview`,`available_after_days`,`required_watch_percent`,`transcript`,`experience_json`,`position`,`updated_at`) SELECT 'cmf-module-3-05-lesson-07','cognizen-crypto-mastery-foundations-production','Example: Trend-Aligned Pullback and Common Multi-Timeframe Mistakes','cmf-module-3-05','text','### Example: Trend-Aligned Pullback\n\nSuppose the weekly chart shows an established uptrend. Price is approaching a former resistance area around 1,000 that may now act as support.\n\nThe daily chart begins stabilising in the 980-to-1,020 zone. Selling momentum weakens and a higher low develops.\n\nOn the four-hour chart, price breaks above a short-term lower high at 1,040.\n\nThe plan may state:\n\nHigher-timeframe bias: bullish while weekly support holds\n\nEntry trigger: four-hour close above 1,040\n\nEntry zone: 1,040 to 1,050\n\nInvalidation: daily close below 970\n\nTarget: previous daily high near 1,180, with a trailing remainder\n\nMaximum portfolio risk: 0.75 percent\n\nThe four-hour chart refines entry. The daily support controls invalidation. The weekly chart provides the broader context.\n\n### Example: Countertrend Short\n\nSuppose the weekly market remains bullish but price has become extremely extended.\n\nThe daily chart reaches major resistance and forms repeated failed breakouts.\n\nThe four-hour chart breaks an important higher low.\n\nA short-term trader may consider a countertrend short.\n\nThe plan should recognise that the position opposes the weekly trend. This may justify:\n\nSmaller size\n\nCloser target\n\nFaster management\n\nNo assumption of a complete bear-market reversal\n\nThe target may be the daily moving average rather than a distant weekly support level.\n\n### Example: Range Trade\n\nSuppose the weekly chart is neutral and price has traded between 80 and 120 for several months.\n\nThe daily chart reaches the lower range boundary.\n\nThe four-hour chart briefly moves below 80 and then closes back above it with a higher low.\n\nA mean-reversion plan may enter after the structural recovery, use the sweep low as invalidation and target the range midpoint near 100.\n\nIf price gains acceptance below 80, the regime and trade thesis are invalid.\n\n### Example: Conflicting Timeframes\n\nSuppose the weekly chart is bullish, the daily chart has broken support and the four-hour chart produces a small bullish reversal.\n\nThe evidence is conflicted.\n\nEntering a full-sized long position because of the four-hour signal may be premature.\n\nPossible responses include:\n\nWait for daily structure to recover\n\nUse a reduced position\n\nTreat the trade as a short-term tactical rebound\n\nTake no position\n\nAdvanced analysis does not require forcing a directional answer when the evidence is mixed.\n\n### Example: Failed Breakout Plan\n\nSuppose the daily chart closes above resistance at 200.\n\nThe trader enters at 204 with invalidation after a daily close below 195.\n\nThe next day closes at 192.\n\nThe trade is closed according to the plan.\n\nThe trader then notices that the weekly chart remains bullish and decides to hold.\n\nThis would be timeframe switching.\n\nA new long-term investment can be considered later, but the breakout trade has already failed.\n\n### A Practical Multi-Timeframe Process\n\nBegin by opening the higher-timeframe chart without lower-timeframe indicators. Mark only the major trend, support, resistance and structural invalidation.\n\nMove to the decision timeframe and determine whether a setup exists. Identify the exact market behaviour required before entry.\n\nUse the execution timeframe only when it provides a measurable improvement. If it adds confusion without changing entry or risk, it is unnecessary.\n\nWrite the trade plan, calculate position size and define no-trade conditions.\n\nAfter entry, manage the position using the timeframe specified in the plan.\n\nThis process should be repeatable.\n\n### Multi-Timeframe Trade Plan Template\n\n\n\n### Market and Instrument\n\nRecord the exact asset, trading pair, exchange and whether the position uses spot or derivatives.\n\n### Strategy\n\nState whether the trade is trend following, mean reverting, breakout based, momentum driven or another defined approach.\n\n### Higher-Timeframe Context\n\nDescribe the broader regime, major trend and important structural levels.\n\n### Decision-Timeframe Setup\n\nExplain the setup and why the opportunity exists.\n\n### Execution Trigger\n\nState the precise condition that permits entry.\n\n### Entry Zone\n\nRecord the acceptable execution range.\n\n### Invalidation and Stop\n\nIdentify the level or event that proves the thesis wrong and the order used to control loss.\n\n### Position Size\n\nRecord the maximum risk, quantity and total exposure.\n\n### Target and Exit\n\nDefine fixed targets, partial exits, trailing rules or time stops.\n\n### Alternative Scenarios\n\nExplain what happens if price consolidates, moves immediately against the trade or becomes excessively extended before entry.\n\n### No-Trade Conditions\n\nState what cancels the setup.\n\n### Review Schedule\n\nIdentify when the position will be reassessed.\n\n### Common Multi-Timeframe Mistakes\n\nOne common mistake is using too many timeframes. More charts do not necessarily produce better analysis. They often provide enough conflicting information to justify any desired trade.\n\nAnother error is allowing the lowest timeframe to dominate the decision. Small candles and indicators can appear urgent while remaining irrelevant to the broader thesis.\n\nParticipants also place stops using a timeframe much smaller than the setup. This creates frequent exits from normal price movement.\n\nThe most damaging mistake is switching to a higher timeframe after a stop should have been accepted. This changes the position’s risk after entry and can turn a controlled loss into an uncontrolled investment.\n\nA final mistake is seeking complete alignment. Waiting until every timeframe confirms the same trend can result in entering after the move has become severely extended.','markdown',NULL,NULL,NULL,6,0,0,0,'',NULL,7,1785297600000 WHERE EXISTS (SELECT 1 FROM `courses` WHERE `id`='cognizen-crypto-mastery-foundations-production');
--> statement-breakpoint
INSERT OR IGNORE INTO `lessons` (`id`,`course_id`,`title`,`section_id`,`lesson_type`,`content`,`content_format`,`video_key`,`primary_asset_id`,`intro_asset_id`,`duration_minutes`,`is_preview`,`available_after_days`,`required_watch_percent`,`transcript`,`experience_json`,`position`,`updated_at`) SELECT 'cmf-module-3-05-lesson-08','cognizen-crypto-mastery-foundations-production','Common Misunderstandings and Key Takeaway','cmf-module-3-05','text','### Common Misunderstandings\n\n#### “The Higher Timeframe Is Always Correct”\n\nThe higher timeframe provides broader context, but short-term movement can still oppose it for meaningful periods.\n\n#### “More Timeframes Create More Confirmation”\n\nThey can create redundancy and confusion. Each timeframe should have a specific role.\n\n#### “A Lower-Timeframe Entry Always Reduces Risk”\n\nIt may reduce the apparent stop distance while placing the stop inside ordinary noise.\n\n#### “A Weekly Uptrend Makes Every Long Trade Attractive”\n\nEntry quality, valuation, liquidity and short-term structure still matter.\n\n#### “A Trade Can Become an Investment if the Higher-Timeframe Chart Looks Good”\n\nChanging time horizon after invalidation is usually an attempt to avoid accepting loss.\n\n#### “Perfect Timeframe Alignment Produces a Safe Trade”\n\nBy the time alignment is perfect, price may be overextended and risk-to-reward poor.\n\n#### “A Detailed Analysis Is a Trade Plan”\n\nThe plan must specify entry, invalidation, size and exit.\n\n#### “Once a Plan Is Written, It Should Never Change”\n\nIt may be cancelled before entry or adjusted according to predefined rules when new evidence appears.\n\n#### “A Profitable Trade Proves the Analysis Was Correct”\n\nProfit can result from luck, poor risk or an outcome unrelated to the original reasoning.\n\n### Module Summary\n\nMulti-timeframe analysis examines the same market across several analytical levels.\n\nThe higher timeframe defines the broader trend, regime and major support or resistance.\n\nThe decision timeframe identifies the setup and structural invalidation.\n\nThe execution timeframe may refine the entry, but it should not override the broader plan without a defined rule.\n\nDifferent timeframes can produce different trends simultaneously. This is normal.\n\nThe participant must decide which timeframe controls the position before entering.\n\nTimeframe alignment can improve confidence, but complete alignment often occurs after much of the movement has already happened.\n\nWhen evidence conflicts, the appropriate response may be a smaller position, additional confirmation or no trade.\n\nAnalysis becomes useful only when it is converted into a trade plan.\n\nThe plan should identify the instrument, strategy, time horizon, entry trigger, invalidation, position size, target and no-trade conditions.\n\nTrade management should follow the written rules rather than short-term emotion.\n\nA failed short-term trade should not be converted into a long-term investment merely to avoid accepting a loss.\n\nThe purpose of multi-timeframe analysis is not to find a chart that agrees with the participant’s opinion.\n\nIt is to connect broad market context with precise execution and controlled risk.\n\n### Key Takeaway\n\nEvery timeframe tells part of the market’s story, but not every timeframe should control the same decision.\n\nUse the higher timeframe to understand the environment, the decision timeframe to define the opportunity and the execution timeframe only when it improves entry without changing the original thesis.\n\nThen convert the analysis into a written plan.\n\nBefore entering, know what must happen, where the idea is wrong, how much can be lost and how the position will end.\n\nThe next module is 3.6: Advanced Order Types and Trade Execution.','markdown',NULL,NULL,NULL,4,0,0,0,'',NULL,8,1785297600000 WHERE EXISTS (SELECT 1 FROM `courses` WHERE `id`='cognizen-crypto-mastery-foundations-production');
--> statement-breakpoint
INSERT OR IGNORE INTO `lessons` (`id`,`course_id`,`title`,`section_id`,`lesson_type`,`content`,`content_format`,`video_key`,`primary_asset_id`,`intro_asset_id`,`duration_minutes`,`is_preview`,`available_after_days`,`required_watch_percent`,`transcript`,`experience_json`,`position`,`updated_at`) SELECT 'cmf-module-3-05-lesson-09','cognizen-crypto-mastery-foundations-production','Check your understanding','cmf-module-3-05','text','### Check your understanding\n\nAnswer these questions to self-assess your understanding before moving on.\n\n1. What is multi-timeframe analysis?\n\n2. Why can one asset appear bullish and bearish simultaneously?\n\n3. What is the difference between major and minor market structure?\n\n4. What role does the higher timeframe perform?\n\n5. What is the purpose of the decision timeframe?\n\n6. When is an execution timeframe useful?\n\n7. Why should timeframes be selected according to the expected holding period?\n\n8. What is timeframe alignment?\n\n9. Why is perfect alignment not always desirable?\n\n10. How should timeframe conflict be handled?\n\n11. What is directional bias?\n\n12. How does top-down analysis work?\n\n13. Why may higher-timeframe support be more significant than a lower-timeframe level?\n\n14. How can a lower-timeframe pullback exist within a higher-timeframe trend?\n\n15. Why should lower-timeframe indicators not automatically invalidate a higher-timeframe thesis?\n\n16. What is timeframe switching?\n\n17. Why is converting a failed trade into an investment dangerous?\n\n18. What distinguishes market analysis from a trade plan?\n\n19. What should an entry trigger describe?\n\n20. How does an entry zone differ from an exact entry price?\n\n21. What is invalidation?\n\n22. How should a stop relate to the trade thesis?\n\n23. How is position quantity calculated?\n\n24. Why can actual risk exceed planned risk?\n\n25. How can higher-timeframe levels assist with target selection?\n\n26. What is a time stop?\n\n27. Why should a plan include alternative scenarios?\n\n28. What is the value of writing rules in an if–then format?\n\n29. What are no-trade conditions?\n\n30. Why should monitoring frequency match the decision timeframe?\n\n31. Under what conditions may a stop be moved?\n\n32. How should planned additions affect total position risk?\n\n33. What should be reviewed after a trade closes?\n\n34. Why can a losing trade still represent a good decision?\n\n35. What information belongs in a multi-timeframe trade journal?','markdown',NULL,NULL,NULL,6,0,0,0,'',NULL,9,1785297600000 WHERE EXISTS (SELECT 1 FROM `courses` WHERE `id`='cognizen-crypto-mastery-foundations-production');
--> statement-breakpoint
INSERT OR IGNORE INTO `course_sections` (`id`,`course_id`,`title`,`position`,`created_at`) SELECT 'cmf-module-3-06','cognizen-crypto-mastery-foundations-production','Module 3.6: Advanced Order Types and Trade Execution',7,1785297600000 WHERE EXISTS (SELECT 1 FROM `courses` WHERE `id`='cognizen-crypto-mastery-foundations-production');
--> statement-breakpoint
INSERT OR IGNORE INTO `lessons` (`id`,`course_id`,`title`,`section_id`,`lesson_type`,`content`,`content_format`,`video_key`,`primary_asset_id`,`intro_asset_id`,`duration_minutes`,`is_preview`,`available_after_days`,`required_watch_percent`,`transcript`,`experience_json`,`position`,`updated_at`) SELECT 'cmf-module-3-06-lesson-01','cognizen-crypto-mastery-foundations-production','The Difference Between a Trading Decision and an Order and Order-Book Depth','cmf-module-3-06','text','### Learning Objectives\n\nBy the end of this module, you should understand how different order types control price, timing and execution certainty. You should be able to distinguish market, limit, stop-market, stop-limit, trailing-stop and conditional orders, and understand when each may be appropriate.\n\nYou should also be able to assess bid-ask spreads, order-book depth, slippage, partial fills and liquidity before entering a position. The module will show how execution differs between centralised exchanges, decentralised exchanges and derivative markets, and how tools such as reduce-only instructions, bracket orders, time-in-force settings and algorithmic execution can support disciplined risk management.\n\n### Introduction\n\nA profitable strategy can be damaged by poor execution.\n\nAn analyst may identify the correct market direction, calculate a suitable position size and define a logical invalidation level. Yet the final result may still be disappointing if the position is entered through a wide spread, filled at an unfavourable price or closed with excessive slippage.\n\nExecution is the process through which an investment or trading decision becomes an actual market position.\n\nIt includes decisions about:\n\nWhich exchange or protocol to use\n\nWhich trading pair to select\n\nWhich order type to submit\n\nHow much liquidity is available\n\nWhether to enter immediately or wait\n\nHow to manage partial fills\n\nHow the exit will be executed\n\nThese decisions can materially affect realised return.\n\nA market order offers execution certainty but limited price control. A limit order offers price control but may never execute. A stop order can help control loss, but it may fill far beyond the trigger during rapid market movement.\n\nThere is no universally best order type.\n\nThe correct choice depends on the strategy, market liquidity, urgency, volatility and consequences of not being filled.\n\n### The Difference Between a Trading Decision and an Order\n\nA trading decision describes what the participant wants to achieve.\n\nFor example:\n\n“I want to buy this asset if it breaks above resistance.”\n\nAn order translates that intention into instructions that an exchange or smart contract can process.\n\nThe instruction must specify matters such as:\n\nAsset\n\nDirection\n\nQuantity\n\nPrice\n\nTrigger\n\nDuration\n\nExecution conditions\n\nPoorly designed orders can produce outcomes different from the original intention.\n\nA participant may intend to risk one percent of capital but submit an order that opens a larger position than expected. A stop-limit order may trigger without executing, leaving the position open while price continues moving adversely.\n\nUnderstanding the distinction between the strategy and the order is essential.\n\nThe strategy defines the desired exposure.\n\nThe order defines how the market will attempt to create or close it.\n\n### The Order Book\n\nMany centralised exchanges and some decentralised platforms operate through an order book.\n\nAn order book displays current intentions to buy and sell.\n\nBuy orders are known as bids.\n\nSell orders are known as asks or offers.\n\nThe highest current bid represents the best price a buyer is willing to pay.\n\nThe lowest current ask represents the best price a seller is willing to accept.\n\nA trade occurs when a new or existing order matches with an order on the opposite side.\n\nThe order book is dynamic. Orders can be added, changed, cancelled or executed continuously.\n\nVisible liquidity therefore represents current intention, not a guarantee that every order will remain available.\n\n### Bid, Ask and Spread\n\nSuppose the highest bid is 99 and the lowest ask is 101.\n\nA participant selling immediately may receive approximately 99.\n\nA participant buying immediately may pay approximately 101.\n\nThe difference is the bid-ask spread:\n\n101 − 99 = 2 units\n\nThe midpoint is:\n\n(101 + 99) ÷ 2 = 100 units\n\nThe percentage spread is approximately:\n\n2 ÷ 100 × 100 = 2 percent\n\nA participant who buys at 101 and immediately sells at 99 loses approximately two percent before fees.\n\nThe spread is therefore an execution cost.\n\nIt tends to be narrower in deep, active markets and wider in illiquid or volatile markets.\n\n### Order-Book Depth\n\nOrder-book depth shows how many units are available at different prices.\n\nSuppose an asset has the following sell orders:\n\n| Price | Quantity available |\n| --- | --- |\n| 100.00 | 100 tokens |\n| 100.20 | 200 tokens |\n| 100.50 | 400 tokens |\n| 101.00 | 800 tokens |\n\nA market purchase of fifty tokens may execute entirely at 100.\n\nA purchase of one thousand tokens must consume several price levels.\n\nIts average price will be higher than 100.\n\nThe displayed best price therefore applies only to the quantity available at that level.\n\nPosition size should be compared with market depth before the order is submitted.','markdown',NULL,NULL,NULL,6,0,0,0,'',NULL,1,1785297600000 WHERE EXISTS (SELECT 1 FROM `courses` WHERE `id`='cognizen-crypto-mastery-foundations-production');
--> statement-breakpoint
INSERT OR IGNORE INTO `lessons` (`id`,`course_id`,`title`,`section_id`,`lesson_type`,`content`,`content_format`,`video_key`,`primary_asset_id`,`intro_asset_id`,`duration_minutes`,`is_preview`,`available_after_days`,`required_watch_percent`,`transcript`,`experience_json`,`position`,`updated_at`) SELECT 'cmf-module-3-06-lesson-02','cognizen-crypto-mastery-foundations-production','Market Orders and Maker and Taker Orders','cmf-module-3-06','text','### Market Orders\n\nA market order instructs the platform to execute immediately against the best available prices.\n\nIt prioritises execution over price.\n\nA market buy consumes available sell orders.\n\nA market sell consumes available buy orders.\n\nMarket orders may be useful when:\n\nImmediate entry or exit is more important than precise price\n\nThe market is highly liquid\n\nThe position is small relative to available depth\n\nA risk limit must be enforced quickly\n\nWaiting creates greater risk than slippage\n\nThe participant does not control the final average execution price.\n\nDuring rapid movement, the result may be substantially worse than the price visible when the order was submitted.\n\n### Market-Order Slippage\n\nSuppose the current ask is 50.\n\nA participant submits a market order for 2,000 tokens.\n\nOnly 200 tokens are available near 50. The remainder executes progressively at 50.20, 50.50, 51 and higher.\n\nThe final average execution may be 51.10.\n\nExpected price:\n\n50\n\nActual average price:\n\n51.10\n\nSlippage:\n\n1.10 units per token\n\nOn 2,000 tokens, this represents 2,200 units of additional cost before trading fees.\n\nThe market order succeeded operationally but may have damaged the trade’s expected value.\n\n### When Market Orders Are Dangerous\n\nMarket orders are especially risky when:\n\nThe asset is illiquid\n\nThe order is large\n\nThe spread is wide\n\nVolatility is expanding\n\nA liquidation cascade is occurring\n\nThe exchange order book is shallow\n\nTrading resumes after an outage\n\nThe token contains unusual transfer rules\n\nThe instruction effectively tells the market:\n\n“Complete this transaction at the best prices currently available, regardless of how far those prices extend.”\n\nThat may be appropriate during an emergency exit.\n\nIt is rarely appropriate without first checking liquidity.\n\n### Limit Orders\n\nA limit order specifies the worst price the participant is willing to accept.\n\nA buy limit sets the maximum purchase price.\n\nA sell limit sets the minimum sale price.\n\nSuppose an asset trades near 100.\n\nA buy limit at 98 will execute only at 98 or lower.\n\nA sell limit at 105 will execute only at 105 or higher.\n\nLimit orders prioritise price control over execution certainty.\n\nThey may remain unfilled if the market never reaches the selected price.\n\n### Passive and Marketable Limit Orders\n\nA passive limit order is placed away from the current market and waits for another participant to trade against it.\n\nFor example, when the best bid is 99 and the best ask is 100, a buy limit at 98 is passive.\n\nA marketable limit order crosses the spread but places a boundary on the worst acceptable price.\n\nFor example, a buy limit at 100.50 may immediately execute against sell orders up to 100.50 but refuse prices above it.\n\nThis can provide a balance between:\n\nFast execution\n\nProtection from extreme slippage\n\nA marketable limit order is often useful when urgency exists but unlimited price deterioration is unacceptable.\n\n### Partial Fills\n\nA limit order may execute only partially.\n\nSuppose a participant submits a buy limit for 1,000 tokens at 20.\n\nOnly 300 tokens are sold at that price.\n\nThe result is:\n\n300 tokens purchased\n\n700 tokens still waiting\n\nThe participant must decide whether to:\n\nLeave the remaining order active\n\nCancel it\n\nAdjust the price\n\nEnter the remainder elsewhere\n\nAccept the smaller position\n\nThe trade plan should address partial fills before they occur.\n\nA partially filled position may carry less risk than planned, but it can also create complications when stop and target orders are based on the full intended quantity.\n\n### Queue Priority\n\nLimit orders placed at the same price may execute according to queue priority.\n\nThe order submitted earlier may be filled before a later order at the same level.\n\nLarge quantities ahead in the queue can reduce the probability of execution.\n\nSome exchanges may also use different matching rules.\n\nA participant should not assume that price touching the limit guarantees a fill.\n\nThere must be sufficient opposing volume to reach that position in the queue.\n\n### Maker and Taker Orders\n\nA maker order adds liquidity to the order book.\n\nA taker order removes existing liquidity.\n\nA passive limit order generally acts as a maker.\n\nA market order acts as a taker.\n\nA marketable limit order may also act as a taker because it executes immediately against existing orders.\n\nPlatforms may apply different fee structures to makers and takers.\n\nMaker fees may be lower because the order contributes liquidity.\n\nTaker fees may be higher because the order demands immediate execution.\n\nThe fee difference should not determine the order type by itself.\n\nSaving a small fee is not useful when the order misses a major movement or exposes the participant to uncontrolled risk.','markdown',NULL,NULL,NULL,6,0,0,0,'',NULL,2,1785297600000 WHERE EXISTS (SELECT 1 FROM `courses` WHERE `id`='cognizen-crypto-mastery-foundations-production');
--> statement-breakpoint
INSERT OR IGNORE INTO `lessons` (`id`,`course_id`,`title`,`section_id`,`lesson_type`,`content`,`content_format`,`video_key`,`primary_asset_id`,`intro_asset_id`,`duration_minutes`,`is_preview`,`available_after_days`,`required_watch_percent`,`transcript`,`experience_json`,`position`,`updated_at`) SELECT 'cmf-module-3-06-lesson-03','cognizen-crypto-mastery-foundations-production','Post-Only Orders and Trigger Prices','cmf-module-3-06','text','### Post-Only Orders\n\nA post-only instruction ensures that an order is added to the order book rather than immediately executing as a taker.\n\nIf the order would cross the spread, the exchange may reject or adjust it according to platform rules.\n\nPost-only orders are useful when:\n\nThe participant wants maker execution\n\nFee control matters\n\nImmediate execution is unnecessary\n\nThe strategy depends on passive liquidity provision\n\nThe risk is non-execution.\n\nThe market may move away before the order fills.\n\n### Time-in-Force Instructions\n\nTime-in-force determines how long an order remains active and how it may execute.\n\nAvailability and exact behaviour vary between platforms.\n\n### Good-Till-Cancelled\n\nA good-till-cancelled order, commonly abbreviated as GTC, remains active until:\n\nIt executes\n\nThe participant cancels it\n\nThe platform removes it under specified conditions\n\nGTC orders are useful for planned entries or exits that may take time.\n\nThey also create forgotten-order risk.\n\nAn old order may execute after market conditions or the investment thesis have changed.\n\nOpen orders should be reviewed regularly.\n\n### Immediate-or-Cancel\n\nAn immediate-or-cancel order, or IOC, attempts to execute immediately.\n\nAny quantity that cannot execute at once within the price conditions is cancelled.\n\nSuppose an IOC buy order requests 1,000 tokens at no more than 50.\n\nIf 600 tokens are available, those 600 may execute and the remaining 400 are cancelled.\n\nIOC can be useful when partial execution is acceptable but waiting is not.\n\n### Fill-or-Kill\n\nA fill-or-kill order, or FOK, must execute the entire requested quantity immediately or be cancelled completely.\n\nIt avoids partial fills.\n\nThis may be useful when:\n\nThe strategy requires the complete position\n\nPartial exposure creates undesirable risk\n\nSeveral transaction legs must remain balanced\n\nFOK orders may fail frequently when the market lacks sufficient depth.\n\n### Day and Expiry Orders\n\nSome platforms allow an order to expire at a specified time.\n\nThis reduces the risk of old orders remaining active after their strategic purpose has ended.\n\nIn continuous cryptocurrency markets, “day” boundaries may depend on the exchange’s time standard.\n\nThe participant should verify the precise expiry time.\n\n### Stop Orders\n\nA stop order becomes active only after a trigger price is reached.\n\nIt is commonly used for:\n\nRisk control\n\nBreakout entry\n\nTrend confirmation\n\nConditional execution\n\nThe trigger price is not necessarily the execution price.\n\nThis distinction is critical.\n\nA stop order is an instruction to create another order when the market reaches a specified condition.\n\n### Stop-Market Orders\n\nA stop-market order becomes a market order after the stop price is triggered.\n\nSuppose a participant owns an asset at 100 and sets a sell stop at 92.\n\nWhen the trigger condition is reached, the platform submits a market sell order.\n\nThe advantage is that the order prioritises closing the position.\n\nThe disadvantage is that execution may occur below 92.\n\nDuring a rapid decline, the average fill might be 90, 87 or lower.\n\nThe stop defines the trigger, not the guaranteed exit price.\n\n### Stop-Limit Orders\n\nA stop-limit order creates a limit order after the stop price is triggered.\n\nSuppose:\n\nStop trigger: 92\n\nSell limit: 91\n\nWhen price reaches the trigger, the exchange submits a sell limit at 91.\n\nThe order can execute at 91 or higher.\n\nIt will not sell below 91.\n\nThis controls the minimum price.\n\nIt also creates the risk that the position remains open if the market moves directly below 91.\n\nA stop-limit order provides price protection but not exit certainty.\n\n### Stop-Market Versus Stop-Limit\n\nA stop-market order asks:\n\nHow can I leave the position as quickly as possible after invalidation?\n\nA stop-limit order asks:\n\nHow can I avoid selling below a specified price?\n\nDuring ordinary liquid conditions, either may work as expected.\n\nDuring a fast market, the difference becomes significant.\n\nFor risk exits, non-execution may be more damaging than slippage. In other situations, such as a thin temporary wick, accepting any price may be undesirable.\n\nThe order type should reflect which risk matters more.\n\n### Trigger Prices\n\nDerivative platforms may allow stops to be triggered by different price references.\n\nThese may include:\n\nLast traded price\n\nMark price\n\nIndex price\n\nThe last traded price reflects the latest exchange transaction.\n\nThe index price may combine external spot-market prices.\n\nThe mark price is often designed to estimate a fair contract value and reduce unnecessary liquidations caused by temporary exchange-specific movement.\n\nA stop triggered by one price reference may behave differently from a liquidation mechanism using another.\n\nThe participant should know exactly which price controls each instruction.','markdown',NULL,NULL,NULL,6,0,0,0,'',NULL,3,1785297600000 WHERE EXISTS (SELECT 1 FROM `courses` WHERE `id`='cognizen-crypto-mastery-foundations-production');
--> statement-breakpoint
INSERT OR IGNORE INTO `lessons` (`id`,`course_id`,`title`,`section_id`,`lesson_type`,`content`,`content_format`,`video_key`,`primary_asset_id`,`intro_asset_id`,`duration_minutes`,`is_preview`,`available_after_days`,`required_watch_percent`,`transcript`,`experience_json`,`position`,`updated_at`) SELECT 'cmf-module-3-06-lesson-04','cognizen-crypto-mastery-foundations-production','Buy-Stop Entries and Close-Position Instructions','cmf-module-3-06','text','### Buy-Stop Entries\n\nA buy stop is placed above the current market price.\n\nIt may be used to enter after bullish confirmation.\n\nSuppose resistance is at 100 and the participant wants to enter only if price moves above 102.\n\nA buy-stop order can trigger at 102.\n\nIf it becomes a market order, the final fill may be higher.\n\nA buy stop can automate breakout participation.\n\nIt can also be triggered by a brief liquidity sweep and produce a poor entry.\n\n### Sell-Stop Entries\n\nA sell stop is placed below the current market price.\n\nIt may be used to enter a bearish position after support breaks.\n\nAs with a buy stop, the market may move rapidly after the trigger.\n\nThe trader should consider:\n\nLiquidity\n\nSlippage\n\nDerivative funding\n\nBorrow availability\n\nStop distance\n\nA breakdown order does not confirm that the new trend will persist.\n\n### Trailing Stops\n\nA trailing stop adjusts as price moves favourably.\n\nFor a long position, the stop rises as the market reaches higher prices.\n\nFor a short position, the stop moves downward as price falls.\n\nThe trailing distance may be defined as:\n\nFixed amount\n\nPercentage\n\nATR multiple\n\nStructural level\n\nIndicator value\n\nSuppose a long position uses a ten-percent trailing stop.\n\nIf price rises from 100 to 150, the trailing reference may move to approximately 135.\n\nIf price then falls to the trigger, an exit order is submitted.\n\n### Advantages and Limitations of Trailing Stops\n\nA trailing stop can help:\n\nProtect part of a gain\n\nRemain in a trend\n\nReduce emotional exit decisions\n\nIt cannot:\n\nIdentify the exact market top\n\nGuarantee execution at the trigger\n\nDistinguish normal volatility from reversal\n\nPrevent slippage\n\nA trailing distance that is too tight creates frequent premature exits.\n\nA distance that is too wide gives back a large part of the unrealised gain.\n\nThe distance should match the asset’s volatility and the strategy’s timeframe.\n\n### Exchange-Managed and Strategy-Managed Trailing Stops\n\nSome platforms provide automatic trailing-stop orders.\n\nA participant may instead update a conventional stop according to a written strategy.\n\nThe first method reduces manual work but depends on the exchange’s order system.\n\nThe second allows greater flexibility but increases operational and behavioural risk.\n\nA manually managed stop is only useful if the participant follows the rule consistently.\n\n### Bracket Orders\n\nA bracket order surrounds a position with an intended profit exit and a protective stop.\n\nFor a long position, the bracket may include:\n\nBuy entry\n\nSell target above\n\nSell stop below\n\nThe target and stop are linked to the position.\n\nWhen one exit executes, the other should normally be cancelled.\n\nBracket orders help translate the complete trade plan into market instructions.\n\nTheir exact implementation varies by platform.\n\nThe participant should verify whether the platform automatically adjusts quantities after partial fills.\n\n### One-Cancels-the-Other Orders\n\nA one-cancels-the-other order, or OCO, links two orders.\n\nWhen one executes, the other is cancelled.\n\nA common use is combining:\n\nProfit-taking limit order\n\nProtective stop order\n\nSuppose an asset is purchased at 100.\n\nThe participant places:\n\nSell limit at 120\n\nSell stop at 92\n\nIf the target fills, the stop is cancelled.\n\nIf the stop fills, the target is cancelled.\n\nWithout this linkage, both orders might remain active and create an unintended position later.\n\n### One-Triggers-the-Other Orders\n\nA one-triggers-the-other instruction activates a second order only after the first order executes.\n\nFor example:\n\nEntry limit order fills\n\nProtective stop becomes active\n\nProfit target becomes active\n\nThis can prevent exit orders from operating before the position exists.\n\nParticipants should understand how partial entry fills affect the linked orders.\n\n### Reduce-Only Orders\n\nA reduce-only instruction ensures that an order can reduce or close an existing derivative position but cannot increase it or open a position in the opposite direction.\n\nSuppose a trader holds a long position of ten contracts.\n\nA reduce-only sell order can close some or all of those contracts.\n\nIt should not create a short position if the long has already been closed elsewhere.\n\nReduce-only instructions are important when several exit orders exist.\n\nWithout them, a target or stop remaining active after closure may accidentally create a new position.\n\n### Close-Position Instructions\n\nSome platforms provide a close-position instruction that attempts to close the entire current position when triggered.\n\nThis can simplify exits when the quantity changes because of partial reductions.\n\nThe participant should verify whether it:\n\nUses market or limit execution\n\nApplies reduce-only behaviour\n\nCancels other orders\n\nUses last, mark or index price as the trigger\n\nPlatform terminology can appear similar while producing different results.','markdown',NULL,NULL,NULL,6,0,0,0,'',NULL,4,1785297600000 WHERE EXISTS (SELECT 1 FROM `courses` WHERE `id`='cognizen-crypto-mastery-foundations-production');
--> statement-breakpoint
INSERT OR IGNORE INTO `lessons` (`id`,`course_id`,`title`,`section_id`,`lesson_type`,`content`,`content_format`,`video_key`,`primary_asset_id`,`intro_asset_id`,`duration_minutes`,`is_preview`,`available_after_days`,`required_watch_percent`,`transcript`,`experience_json`,`position`,`updated_at`) SELECT 'cmf-module-3-06-lesson-05','cognizen-crypto-mastery-foundations-production','Hidden and Iceberg Orders and Centralised Exchange Versus DEX Execution','cmf-module-3-06','text','### Hidden and Iceberg Orders\n\nA hidden order does not display its full quantity publicly.\n\nAn iceberg order displays only part of the total amount.\n\nAs the visible portion executes, more quantity is revealed.\n\nLarge participants may use iceberg orders to reduce visible market impact.\n\nFor example, an order for 100,000 tokens may display only 5,000 at a time.\n\nThis means visible order-book depth may understate genuine liquidity.\n\nIt can also overstate reliability because visible orders may be cancelled.\n\nOrder-book analysis should therefore be treated as incomplete.\n\n### Spoofing\n\nSpoofing involves placing orders intended to influence other participants rather than to execute.\n\nA trader may display a large buy wall to create the appearance of support, then cancel it as price approaches.\n\nSpoofing can distort:\n\nOrder-book imbalance\n\nPerceived supply and demand\n\nShort-term execution decisions\n\nVisible liquidity is less reliable than sustained executed activity.\n\nParticipants should avoid making major decisions based on one apparent wall.\n\n### Layering\n\nLayering is a related manipulation technique involving several misleading orders at different price levels.\n\nThe objective may be to create the impression of substantial buying or selling interest.\n\nOrders can disappear rapidly.\n\nRegulated markets may prohibit such conduct, but cryptocurrency enforcement and market structure vary.\n\nThe correct defence is not to attempt to imitate manipulation.\n\nIt is to avoid assuming that every visible order represents genuine intent.\n\n### Order-Book Imbalance\n\nOrder-book imbalance compares available bid and ask quantities near the current price.\n\nA large bid imbalance may suggest greater visible demand.\n\nA large ask imbalance may suggest stronger visible supply.\n\nThe metric can provide short-term context.\n\nIt remains vulnerable to:\n\nCancellation\n\nSpoofing\n\nHidden orders\n\nExchange fragmentation\n\nLarge market orders\n\nIt should not replace executed-volume and price-structure analysis.\n\n### Market Depth Charts\n\nA depth chart visualises cumulative buy and sell orders at different prices.\n\nIt can help participants estimate:\n\nSpread\n\nNearby liquidity\n\nPotential price impact\n\nLarge visible order clusters\n\nDepth charts are snapshots.\n\nThey can change immediately.\n\nA large order should be planned using live market information and conservative assumptions.\n\n### Slippage Tolerance on Decentralised Exchanges\n\nA DEX swap commonly requires a maximum slippage tolerance.\n\nSuppose the expected output is 1,000 tokens and tolerance is one percent.\n\nThe minimum acceptable amount may be approximately 990 tokens.\n\nIf execution would produce less, the transaction reverts.\n\nA wider tolerance improves the chance of completion.\n\nIt also permits a worse exchange rate and may increase exposure to sandwich attacks.\n\nThe participant should not raise slippage repeatedly without understanding why the transaction is failing.\n\nThe underlying problem may be:\n\nWeak liquidity\n\nRapid price movement\n\nTransfer tax\n\nFraudulent token\n\nPoor route\n\n### Minimum Amount Received\n\nThe minimum amount received is the practical protection created by the slippage setting.\n\nBefore signing a swap, the participant should compare:\n\nExpected amount\n\nMinimum amount\n\nMarket value\n\nPrice impact\n\nNetwork fee\n\nProtocol fee\n\nA transaction can be technically successful and economically poor.\n\n### DEX Price Impact\n\nOn an automated market maker, a large swap changes the pool ratio.\n\nThis creates price impact.\n\nPrice impact differs from slippage caused by external movement, although DEX interfaces may display the concepts together.\n\nA participant should compare the intended order with:\n\nPool liquidity\n\nActive price range\n\nRoute\n\nAvailable aggregators\n\nSplitting a trade or using a deeper route may improve execution.\n\n### MEV and Transaction Ordering\n\nPending blockchain transactions may be visible before confirmation.\n\nSpecialised participants can react to them.\n\nThis creates maximum extractable value, or MEV.\n\nA large swap may attract:\n\nFront-running\n\nBack-running\n\nArbitrage\n\nSandwich attacks\n\nThe user may receive a worse price even though the transaction remains within the selected slippage tolerance.\n\nProtected routing, private transaction submission and tighter slippage settings may reduce certain forms of MEV exposure.\n\nThey add their own dependencies and do not remove all execution risk.\n\n### DEX Aggregators\n\nA DEX aggregator searches across several liquidity sources.\n\nIt may split the transaction into several routes to improve output.\n\nFor example, a swap may be divided between:\n\nTwo liquidity pools\n\nDifferent fee tiers\n\nAn intermediate stablecoin\n\nMore than one exchange protocol\n\nThe route may improve price but increase:\n\nSmart contract interactions\n\nGas usage\n\nRoute complexity\n\nDependency risk\n\nThe best headline quote is not always the safest total execution.\n\n### Centralised Exchange Versus DEX Execution\n\nA centralised exchange may offer:\n\nFaster order matching\n\nAdvanced conditional orders\n\nDeeper order books\n\nLower network costs\n\nCounterparty and custody risk\n\nA DEX may offer:\n\nSelf-custodial settlement\n\nPermissionless assets\n\nOn-chain transparency\n\nSmart contract and MEV risk\n\nNetwork fees\n\nAMM price impact\n\nThe appropriate venue depends on the asset, position size, custody requirements and execution strategy.','markdown',NULL,NULL,NULL,6,0,0,0,'',NULL,5,1785297600000 WHERE EXISTS (SELECT 1 FROM `courses` WHERE `id`='cognizen-crypto-mastery-foundations-production');
--> statement-breakpoint
INSERT OR IGNORE INTO `lessons` (`id`,`course_id`,`title`,`section_id`,`lesson_type`,`content`,`content_format`,`video_key`,`primary_asset_id`,`intro_asset_id`,`duration_minutes`,`is_preview`,`available_after_days`,`required_watch_percent`,`transcript`,`experience_json`,`position`,`updated_at`) SELECT 'cmf-module-3-06-lesson-06','cognizen-crypto-mastery-foundations-production','Fragmented Liquidity and Execution Around Major Events','cmf-module-3-06','text','### Fragmented Liquidity\n\nCryptocurrency liquidity is distributed across:\n\nCentralised exchanges\n\nDecentralised exchanges\n\nDifferent stablecoin pairs\n\nSeveral blockchain networks\n\nDerivative and spot markets\n\nOne venue may display an abnormal price because of local liquidity.\n\nA participant should compare credible markets before submitting a large order.\n\nA position that appears small relative to global volume may be large relative to the selected venue.\n\n### Cross-Exchange Execution\n\nLarge participants may split orders across several venues.\n\nThis can reduce price impact and access deeper combined liquidity.\n\nIt also introduces:\n\nMultiple counterparty exposures\n\nAsset-transfer requirements\n\nOperational complexity\n\nDifferent fee structures\n\nExecution mismatch\n\nA participant should not open offsetting positions on several exchanges without understanding how they will be reconciled if one platform becomes unavailable.\n\n### Time-Weighted Average Price Execution\n\nA Time-Weighted Average Price strategy, or TWAP, divides a large order into smaller transactions executed over time.\n\nSuppose a participant wants to buy 100,000 units over ten hours.\n\nThe strategy may purchase approximately 10,000 units per hour.\n\nTWAP can reduce immediate market impact.\n\nIt introduces timing risk.\n\nPrice may rise throughout the execution period, causing later portions to become more expensive.\n\n### Volume-Weighted Average Price Execution\n\nA Volume-Weighted Average Price strategy, or VWAP, attempts to execute more heavily during periods of greater market volume.\n\nThe objective is to reduce the order’s visibility and impact relative to normal market activity.\n\nVWAP execution requires reliable estimates of volume patterns.\n\nCryptocurrency volume varies across venues and may include artificial activity.\n\nThe benchmark should not be treated as objective proof of execution quality when the underlying data is weak.\n\n### Percentage-of-Volume Execution\n\nA percentage-of-volume strategy attempts to represent a fixed share of market activity.\n\nFor example, the algorithm may seek to execute approximately five percent of observed trading volume.\n\nIf market activity rises, execution accelerates.\n\nIf activity declines, execution slows.\n\nThe approach may reduce market impact.\n\nIt can take too long in weak markets and may follow artificial or unstable volume.\n\n### Implementation Shortfall\n\nImplementation shortfall measures the difference between the theoretical decision price and the actual final execution result.\n\nSuppose the decision to buy occurs when price is 100.\n\nAfter delays, spread, fees and slippage, the average execution is 103.\n\nThe implementation shortfall includes the lost value created between decision and completion.\n\nIt may contain:\n\nMarket movement\n\nSlippage\n\nFees\n\nMissed quantity\n\nOpportunity cost\n\nExecution quality should be evaluated against the original decision, not only against the last visible quote.\n\n### Opportunity Cost of Non-Execution\n\nA limit order may provide excellent price control but never fill.\n\nIf the asset then rises significantly, the participant misses the opportunity.\n\nThis is the opportunity cost of non-execution.\n\nIt is difficult to measure because no actual position existed.\n\nA strategy must decide whether missing the trade is acceptable.\n\nFor patient mean-reversion strategies, non-execution may be normal.\n\nFor urgent risk exits, it may be unacceptable.\n\n### Urgency Versus Price Control\n\nExecution decisions often involve a trade-off.\n\nGreater urgency generally requires accepting:\n\nSpread\n\nSlippage\n\nTaker fees\n\nMarket impact\n\nGreater price control generally requires accepting:\n\nDelayed execution\n\nPartial fills\n\nMissed trades\n\nQueue uncertainty\n\nThe strategy should determine which risk is more important.\n\nA trader entering a discretionary setup may prefer a limit order.\n\nA leveraged trader facing liquidation may prioritise immediate market execution.\n\n### Execution During High Volatility\n\nDuring rapid market movement:\n\nSpreads widen\n\nOrders disappear\n\nSlippage rises\n\nStop orders cluster\n\nPlatform latency increases\n\nPrice feeds may differ\n\nAn order type that performs well under normal conditions may behave poorly.\n\nPosition sizes should be reduced when execution uncertainty rises.\n\nThe participant may also:\n\nDivide orders\n\nUse price limits\n\nAvoid thin venues\n\nWait for stabilisation\n\nAccept no trade\n\n### Execution During Low Liquidity\n\nLow liquidity creates a different risk.\n\nThe market may appear calm because little activity is occurring.\n\nA relatively small order can then cause a large price movement.\n\nLimit orders may reveal the participant’s interest.\n\nMarket orders may consume most available depth.\n\nStops may experience severe slippage.\n\nA position should not be opened merely because the chart looks orderly.\n\nExecution capacity must be verified.\n\n### Execution Around Major Events\n\nScheduled events can cause spreads and volatility to change before and after the announcement.\n\nExamples include:\n\nRegulatory decisions\n\nNetwork upgrades\n\nEconomic announcements\n\nToken unlocks\n\nGovernance votes\n\nA limit order may fill immediately before adverse information.\n\nA stop-market order may execute far from the trigger.\n\nA strategy should decide whether to:\n\nEnter before the event\n\nWait until afterward\n\nReduce size\n\nCancel resting orders\n\nAccept the event risk\n\nOrders should not remain active through major events unintentionally.','markdown',NULL,NULL,NULL,6,0,0,0,'',NULL,6,1785297600000 WHERE EXISTS (SELECT 1 FROM `courses` WHERE `id`='cognizen-crypto-mastery-foundations-production');
--> statement-breakpoint
INSERT OR IGNORE INTO `lessons` (`id`,`course_id`,`title`,`section_id`,`lesson_type`,`content`,`content_format`,`video_key`,`primary_asset_id`,`intro_asset_id`,`duration_minutes`,`is_preview`,`available_after_days`,`required_watch_percent`,`transcript`,`experience_json`,`position`,`updated_at`) SELECT 'cmf-module-3-06-lesson-07','cognizen-crypto-mastery-foundations-production','Execution During Exchange Outages and Scaling Out of a Position','cmf-module-3-06','text','### Execution During Exchange Outages\n\nAn exchange may become unavailable during intense volatility.\n\nPossible consequences include:\n\nInability to cancel orders\n\nStops not functioning as expected\n\nDelayed market data\n\nWithdrawal suspension\n\nDifference from external prices\n\nHolding a position on one exchange creates operational concentration.\n\nRisk reduction may include:\n\nLower leverage\n\nSmaller platform exposure\n\nIndependent price monitoring\n\nPredefined emergency procedures\n\nNo arrangement removes exchange risk completely.\n\n### Order Errors\n\nOperational mistakes can create immediate financial loss.\n\nExamples include:\n\nBuying instead of selling\n\nEntering the wrong quantity\n\nUsing the wrong trading pair\n\nMisplacing a decimal point\n\nSelecting leverage unintentionally\n\nUsing cross margin instead of isolated margin\n\nSetting stop above rather than below entry\n\nSending an asset on the wrong network\n\nA confirmation checklist can prevent many of these errors.\n\nUrgency should not override basic verification.\n\n### Fat-Finger Risk\n\nA fat-finger error is an accidental order caused by incorrect typing or selection.\n\nFor example, a participant intends to buy 0.1 token but enters 10 tokens.\n\nInterface safeguards may include:\n\nOrder confirmation\n\nMaximum quantity\n\nPrice-deviation warnings\n\nPosition limits\n\nThe participant should pause before confirming any unusually large order.\n\n### Position Quantity and Contract Size\n\nDerivative contracts may not equal one unit of the underlying asset.\n\nA contract may represent:\n\nOne token\n\nA fraction of a token\n\nA fixed currency value\n\nAn inverse exposure\n\nThe participant must understand:\n\nContract multiplier\n\nMargin currency\n\nNotional value\n\nLeverage\n\nTick size\n\nEntering ten contracts does not necessarily mean exposure to ten tokens.\n\n### Notional Exposure\n\nNotional exposure is the full market value controlled by the position.\n\nSuppose a trader deposits 2,000 units and uses five-times leverage.\n\nNotional exposure is approximately:\n\n2,000 × 5 = 10,000 units\n\nFees, funding and profit or loss are generally connected to the notional exposure rather than only the deposited collateral.\n\nOrder size should be checked in both:\n\nContract quantity\n\nCurrency value\n\n### Reduce-Only Risk Control\n\nReduce-only is particularly important in derivatives execution.\n\nSuppose a trader has:\n\nStop order\n\nProfit target\n\nManual exit\n\nIf the position is closed manually but the target remains active without reduce-only protection, it may later open a new short position.\n\nLinked and reduce-only exits help prevent this unintended reversal.\n\nThe participant should still verify that all stale orders are cancelled.\n\n### Margin Mode and Execution\n\nIn isolated margin, a defined amount of collateral supports a specific position.\n\nIn cross margin, broader account equity may support several positions.\n\nAn order error in cross margin can expose more capital than expected.\n\nExecution review should confirm:\n\nMargin mode\n\nLeverage\n\nCollateral asset\n\nLiquidation level\n\nPosition quantity\n\nThese subjects will be explored further in the derivatives modules.\n\n### Execution Checklist Before Entry\n\nBefore submitting an order, confirm the exact asset, trading pair, platform and market type. Check whether the instrument is spot, futures, perpetual or another derivative.\n\nReview the spread and available depth. Determine whether the order is small enough to execute without unacceptable impact.\n\nConfirm the quantity, notional exposure and maximum planned loss.\n\nVerify the order type, limit price, trigger price and time-in-force.\n\nIf using derivatives, confirm leverage, margin mode and reduce-only settings.\n\nFinally, check whether any existing orders could interact with the new position unexpectedly.\n\n### Execution Checklist After Entry\n\nAfter execution, confirm the actual average fill rather than relying on the intended price.\n\nCheck the final quantity, fees, leverage and liquidation information.\n\nEnsure that protective orders match the actual filled quantity.\n\nCancel duplicate or stale entry orders.\n\nRecord the execution in the trade journal.\n\nIf the order filled only partially, recalculate total risk before attempting to complete the position.\n\n### Exit Execution\n\nClosing a position deserves the same attention as opening it.\n\nA participant should consider:\n\nCurrent liquidity\n\nUrgency\n\nSpread\n\nTax consequences\n\nPartial exit plan\n\nRemaining linked orders\n\nMarket event risk\n\nA profitable position can lose substantial value during a poorly executed exit.\n\nThe desire to maximise the final price can also prevent execution entirely.\n\nExit strategy should balance price improvement with the risk of continued market movement.\n\n### Scaling Into a Position\n\nScaling in divides the intended entry into several orders.\n\nThis may reduce timing risk and market impact.\n\nFor example, a 30,000-unit position may be entered through three 10,000-unit orders.\n\nThe plan should state:\n\nConditions for each entry\n\nMaximum total quantity\n\nUpdated average price\n\nCombined stop\n\nTotal capital at risk\n\nScaling in should not become uncontrolled averaging down.\n\nIf the original thesis is invalidated, remaining entry orders should be cancelled.\n\n### Scaling Out of a Position\n\nScaling out closes the position gradually.\n\nThis may reduce market impact and realise profit at several levels.\n\nThe participant should know how each partial exit affects:\n\nRemaining quantity\n\nStop quantity\n\nAverage realised price\n\nRisk\n\nLinked orders\n\nA platform may not automatically update every order after a partial fill.\n\nManual verification is essential.','markdown',NULL,NULL,NULL,6,0,0,0,'',NULL,7,1785297600000 WHERE EXISTS (SELECT 1 FROM `courses` WHERE `id`='cognizen-crypto-mastery-foundations-production');
--> statement-breakpoint
INSERT OR IGNORE INTO `lessons` (`id`,`course_id`,`title`,`section_id`,`lesson_type`,`content`,`content_format`,`video_key`,`primary_asset_id`,`intro_asset_id`,`duration_minutes`,`is_preview`,`available_after_days`,`required_watch_percent`,`transcript`,`experience_json`,`position`,`updated_at`) SELECT 'cmf-module-3-06-lesson-08','cognizen-crypto-mastery-foundations-production','Order Cancellation Risk and Common Execution Mistakes','cmf-module-3-06','text','### Order Cancellation Risk\n\nCancelling an order is not always instantaneous.\n\nThe order may execute before the cancellation reaches the matching engine or blockchain.\n\nA participant should wait for confirmed cancellation before assuming that the order is inactive.\n\nOn-chain cancellations may require a transaction and network fee.\n\nDuring congestion, the cancellation may be delayed.\n\n### Stale Orders\n\nA stale order remains active after its strategic purpose has ended.\n\nExamples include:\n\nOld buy limit below the market\n\nStop belonging to a closed position\n\nTarget for a previous trade\n\nDEX approval or intent remaining valid\n\nStale orders can create unintended positions.\n\nOpen orders and permissions should be reviewed routinely.\n\n### Execution Journal\n\nAn execution journal should record:\n\nDecision price\n\nOrder type\n\nIntended quantity\n\nActual quantity\n\nIntended price\n\nAverage fill\n\nSpread\n\nSlippage\n\nFees\n\nTime to complete\n\nPartial fills\n\nOrder amendments\n\nPlatform issues\n\nThis information helps distinguish strategy performance from execution performance.\n\nA sound strategy may appear weak because of poor fills.\n\nA marginal strategy may appear profitable temporarily because of unrealistic backtest execution assumptions.\n\n### Execution Quality Metrics\n\nUseful measurements include:\n\n### Average Fill Price\n\nThe quantity-weighted average price of all fills.\n\n### Slippage\n\nThe difference between expected and actual execution.\n\n### Effective Spread\n\nThe cost relative to the market midpoint.\n\n### Fill Rate\n\nThe proportion of the intended quantity executed.\n\n### Time to Fill\n\nHow long the order required.\n\n### Implementation Shortfall\n\nThe total difference between the original decision and final result.\n\nThese metrics should be reviewed across a meaningful sample rather than one trade.\n\n### Example: Market Versus Limit Entry\n\nSuppose the best bid is 99 and the best ask is 100.\n\nA participant wants 1,000 tokens.\n\nA market order produces an average fill of 100.80.\n\nA passive limit at 99.50 may not fill.\n\nA marketable limit at 100.20 may fill 600 tokens and leave the rest unfilled.\n\nNone of these outcomes is automatically correct.\n\nThe appropriate choice depends on:\n\nExpected opportunity\n\nUrgency\n\nTolerance for partial execution\n\nAvailable liquidity\n\nStrategy edge\n\n### Example: Stop-Market Exit\n\nA trader buys at 50 and places a stop-market trigger at 45.\n\nUnexpected news causes price to fall rapidly.\n\nThe stop triggers at 45, but the average execution is 42.50.\n\nThe intended risk was five units per token.\n\nThe realised loss is 7.50 units per token before fees.\n\nThe stop reduced loss relative to remaining in the position, but it did not guarantee the planned amount.\n\n### Example: Stop-Limit Failure\n\nA trader uses:\n\nStop trigger: 45\n\nSell limit: 44.50\n\nPrice falls directly from 46 to 42.\n\nThe order triggers, but no buyers are available at 44.50 or higher.\n\nThe position remains open while the market continues falling.\n\nThe price boundary worked as designed.\n\nThe exit did not occur.\n\n### Example: OCO Exit\n\nA participant buys 100 tokens at 20.\n\nThey place an OCO order containing:\n\nProfit limit at 26\n\nStop-market trigger at 17\n\nPrice reaches 26 and the sell limit fills.\n\nThe stop should be cancelled automatically.\n\nThe participant verifies that the stop no longer exists.\n\nWithout the cancellation, a later decline could trigger a new unintended short position on a derivative platform.\n\n### Example: DEX Swap\n\nA participant wants to exchange assets worth 20,000 units.\n\nThe interface displays:\n\nExpected output: 19,800 units\n\nMinimum output: 19,404 units\n\nPrice impact: 1.2 percent\n\nNetwork and protocol costs: 150 units\n\nThe difference between the original value and minimum possible output is material.\n\nThe participant may compare other pools, divide the trade or decide that available liquidity is insufficient.\n\nThe ability to press “swap” does not mean the execution is economically acceptable.\n\n### Example: TWAP Entry\n\nAn investor wants to purchase 120,000 units of a liquid asset without placing one large order.\n\nThey divide the purchase into twelve hourly orders of approximately 10,000 units.\n\nThis reduces immediate price impact.\n\nIf price rises steadily throughout the twelve hours, the average fill becomes higher.\n\nTWAP reduces one type of execution risk while accepting timing risk.\n\n### Common Execution Mistakes\n\nA frequent mistake is using market orders without checking depth. The displayed price may be available for only a small quantity.\n\nAnother is assuming that a stop price is a guaranteed exit price. Stop-market orders can slip, while stop-limit orders can remain unfilled.\n\nParticipants may also forget that limit orders can execute partially. Their protective exits then cover the wrong quantity.\n\nIn derivative markets, failing to use reduce-only instructions can turn an intended exit into a new opposite position.\n\nOn decentralised exchanges, increasing slippage repeatedly can expose the trade to poor pricing, transfer taxes or MEV.\n\nFinally, many traders evaluate only the strategy signal and ignore execution costs. Small edges can disappear after spreads, fees, funding and slippage.','markdown',NULL,NULL,NULL,6,0,0,0,'',NULL,8,1785297600000 WHERE EXISTS (SELECT 1 FROM `courses` WHERE `id`='cognizen-crypto-mastery-foundations-production');
--> statement-breakpoint
INSERT OR IGNORE INTO `lessons` (`id`,`course_id`,`title`,`section_id`,`lesson_type`,`content`,`content_format`,`video_key`,`primary_asset_id`,`intro_asset_id`,`duration_minutes`,`is_preview`,`available_after_days`,`required_watch_percent`,`transcript`,`experience_json`,`position`,`updated_at`) SELECT 'cmf-module-3-06-lesson-09','cognizen-crypto-mastery-foundations-production','Common Misunderstandings and Key Takeaway','cmf-module-3-06','text','### Common Misunderstandings\n\n#### “A Market Order Executes at the Displayed Price”\n\nIt executes against the available order book and may receive several prices.\n\n#### “A Limit Order Guarantees a Fill”\n\nIt guarantees only that execution will not be worse than the limit.\n\n#### “Price Touching My Limit Means I Must Have Been Filled”\n\nOther orders may have had queue priority, and insufficient quantity may have traded.\n\n#### “A Stop-Loss Defines My Maximum Loss”\n\nThe final loss can be greater because of slippage, gaps or platform failure.\n\n#### “A Stop-Limit Is Safer Than a Stop-Market”\n\nIt offers greater price control but may fail to exit.\n\n#### “Maker Orders Are Always Better”\n\nThey may have lower fees but can miss the trade.\n\n#### “Reduce-Only Is Relevant Only to Professional Traders”\n\nIt helps prevent unintended derivative positions whenever several exit orders exist.\n\n#### “A DEX Swap Has No Order-Execution Risk”\n\nIt remains exposed to price impact, slippage, MEV, network delay and smart contract risk.\n\n#### “The Largest Exchange Always Provides the Best Execution”\n\nExecution depends on the exact asset, pair, position size and available depth.\n\n#### “Splitting an Order Always Improves the Price”\n\nIt can reduce impact while increasing fees and exposure to market movement.\n\n#### “Advanced Order Types Remove the Need for Monitoring”\n\nOrders can fail, fill partially or behave differently during abnormal conditions.\n\n### Module Summary\n\nTrade execution determines how an analytical decision becomes a real position.\n\nMarket orders prioritise immediate execution but provide limited price control.\n\nLimit orders provide price control but may remain unfilled or execute only partially.\n\nStop-market orders prioritise closing after a trigger but can experience significant slippage.\n\nStop-limit orders control the permitted price but may fail to close the position.\n\nTrailing stops adjust as the market moves favourably, while bracket and OCO orders combine protective and profit-taking instructions.\n\nReduce-only orders help ensure that derivative exits do not accidentally create new positions.\n\nTime-in-force settings control whether orders remain active, execute partially or expire.\n\nExecution quality depends on more than order type. Participants must also assess:\n\nBid-ask spread\n\nOrder-book depth\n\nLiquidity\n\nVolatility\n\nPartial fills\n\nTrading fees\n\nFunding\n\nSlippage\n\nMarket impact\n\nOn decentralised exchanges, execution involves liquidity pools, slippage tolerance, minimum amounts received, transaction ordering and MEV.\n\nLarge orders may be divided through TWAP, VWAP or percentage-of-volume methods. These approaches can reduce immediate market impact but introduce timing and operational risk.\n\nThe best order type is not the most advanced one.\n\nIt is the instruction that most closely reflects the strategy’s priorities while controlling the most important execution risk.\n\nA good analysis identifies the opportunity.\n\nGood execution determines how much of that opportunity survives contact with the market.\n\n### Key Takeaway\n\nThe market does not execute your intention. It executes your order.\n\nBefore submitting that order, decide whether price control or execution certainty matters more. Check the spread, available liquidity, order quantity, trigger rules and possible slippage.\n\nA sound strategy can survive an ordinary losing trade.\n\nIt may not survive an order that creates exposure the strategy never intended.\n\nThe next module is 3.7: Futures and Perpetual Contracts.','markdown',NULL,NULL,NULL,4,0,0,0,'',NULL,9,1785297600000 WHERE EXISTS (SELECT 1 FROM `courses` WHERE `id`='cognizen-crypto-mastery-foundations-production');
--> statement-breakpoint
INSERT OR IGNORE INTO `lessons` (`id`,`course_id`,`title`,`section_id`,`lesson_type`,`content`,`content_format`,`video_key`,`primary_asset_id`,`intro_asset_id`,`duration_minutes`,`is_preview`,`available_after_days`,`required_watch_percent`,`transcript`,`experience_json`,`position`,`updated_at`) SELECT 'cmf-module-3-06-lesson-10','cognizen-crypto-mastery-foundations-production','Check your understanding','cmf-module-3-06','text','### Check your understanding\n\nAnswer these questions to self-assess your understanding before moving on.\n\n1. What is the difference between a trading decision and an order?\n\n2. What are the bid and ask?\n\n3. How is the bid-ask spread calculated?\n\n4. Why can a large market order execute at several prices?\n\n5. What is order-book depth?\n\n6. How does a market order differ from a limit order?\n\n7. What is a marketable limit order?\n\n8. Why may a limit order be partially filled?\n\n9. What is queue priority?\n\n10. How do maker and taker orders differ?\n\n11. What does a post-only instruction do?\n\n12. How does GTC differ from IOC and FOK?\n\n13. What is a stop order?\n\n14. How does a stop-market order work?\n\n15. Why can a stop-market order execute beyond its trigger?\n\n16. How does a stop-limit order work?\n\n17. What is the principal risk of a stop-limit exit?\n\n18. Why do last price, index price and mark price matter?\n\n19. What is a trailing stop?\n\n20. What is an OCO order?\n\n21. How does a bracket order support trade planning?\n\n22. What does reduce-only mean?\n\n23. Why can hidden and iceberg orders make visible depth incomplete?\n\n24. What is spoofing?\n\n25. How does DEX slippage tolerance affect execution?\n\n26. What is the minimum amount received?\n\n27. How does price impact differ from general market slippage?\n\n28. What is a sandwich attack?\n\n29. What does a DEX aggregator do?\n\n30. How does TWAP execution work?\n\n31. How does VWAP execution differ from TWAP?\n\n32. What is implementation shortfall?\n\n33. What is the opportunity cost of non-execution?\n\n34. Why does high volatility increase execution risk?\n\n35. Why should derivative traders confirm contract size and notional exposure?\n\n36. What should be checked after an order fills?\n\n37. How can scaling into a position reduce market impact?\n\n38. Why must protective orders be updated after partial exits?\n\n39. What is a stale order?\n\n40. Which metrics can be recorded to evaluate execution quality?','markdown',NULL,NULL,NULL,6,0,0,0,'',NULL,10,1785297600000 WHERE EXISTS (SELECT 1 FROM `courses` WHERE `id`='cognizen-crypto-mastery-foundations-production');
--> statement-breakpoint
INSERT OR IGNORE INTO `course_sections` (`id`,`course_id`,`title`,`position`,`created_at`) SELECT 'cmf-module-3-07','cognizen-crypto-mastery-foundations-production','Module 3.7: Futures and Perpetual Contracts',8,1785297600000 WHERE EXISTS (SELECT 1 FROM `courses` WHERE `id`='cognizen-crypto-mastery-foundations-production');
