INSERT OR IGNORE INTO `lessons` (`id`,`course_id`,`title`,`section_id`,`lesson_type`,`content`,`content_format`,`video_key`,`primary_asset_id`,`intro_asset_id`,`duration_minutes`,`is_preview`,`available_after_days`,`required_watch_percent`,`transcript`,`experience_json`,`position`,`updated_at`) SELECT 'cmf-module-3-07-lesson-01','cognizen-crypto-mastery-foundations-production','What Is a Derivative? and Spot Exposure Versus Derivative Exposure','cmf-module-3-07','text','### Learning Objectives\n\nBy the end of this module, you should understand how futures and perpetual contracts create exposure to cryptocurrency prices without requiring direct ownership of the underlying asset.\n\nYou should be able to distinguish dated futures from perpetual contracts, explain long and short positions, calculate notional exposure and basic profit or loss, and understand how margin and leverage affect portfolio risk.\n\nYou should also be able to explain futures basis, contango, backwardation, funding rates, mark prices and liquidation. Most importantly, you should recognise how a position can be directionally correct over the longer term but still fail because of leverage, funding costs, weak liquidity or poor margin management.\n\n### Introduction\n\nA spot-market participant buys or sells an actual digital asset.\n\nIf a person buys one Bitcoin through a spot exchange, they acquire a claim to one Bitcoin, subject to the exchange’s custody and withdrawal arrangements.\n\nA derivatives participant does not necessarily buy the underlying asset.\n\nThey enter a contract whose value changes according to the asset’s price.\n\nFutures and perpetual contracts make it possible to gain:\n\nLong exposure when expecting price to rise\n\nShort exposure when expecting price to fall\n\nLeveraged exposure larger than the deposited capital\n\nHedging protection for an existing portfolio\n\nRelative-value exposure between spot and derivatives markets\n\nThese instruments are powerful because they separate market exposure from direct asset ownership.\n\nThey are dangerous for the same reason.\n\nA trader may control a position worth many times the capital deposited. A relatively small adverse price movement can therefore consume a large percentage of the trader’s margin.\n\nThe market does not need to move to zero for the trader to lose the full amount committed to a leveraged position.\n\nLiquidation can occur after a comparatively ordinary fluctuation.\n\nUnderstanding derivatives requires more than predicting direction. The participant must understand contract design, collateral, funding, margin, execution and the rules used by the trading platform.\n\n### What Is a Derivative?\n\nA derivative is a financial contract whose value is linked to an underlying asset, rate, index or event.\n\nIn cryptocurrency markets, the underlying reference may be:\n\nBitcoin\n\nEther\n\nAnother digital asset\n\nA cryptocurrency index\n\nA volatility measure\n\nA funding or interest rate\n\nThe derivative does not always provide ownership of the referenced asset.\n\nInstead, it creates a contractual financial exposure.\n\nFor example, a Bitcoin futures contract may gain value when Bitcoin rises and lose value when Bitcoin falls, even though no Bitcoin is delivered to the trader’s wallet.\n\nThe precise rights and obligations depend on the contract specification.\n\n### What Is a Futures Contract?\n\nA futures contract is an agreement to buy or sell an underlying asset, or settle its value, at a specified future date according to defined contract terms.\n\nA futures contract normally has an expiry date.\n\nAt or before expiry, the contract may be:\n\nClosed through an offsetting trade\n\nSettled in cash\n\nSettled in cryptocurrency\n\nRolled into a later contract\n\nPhysically delivered, depending on the product\n\nMost cryptocurrency traders close or roll positions rather than taking delivery.\n\nThe contract’s price may differ from the current spot price before expiry.\n\nAs expiry approaches, the futures price generally converges toward the spot price used for settlement.\n\n### What Is a Perpetual Contract?\n\nA perpetual contract, often called a perpetual future or perpetual swap, resembles a futures contract but has no fixed expiry date.\n\nA position can theoretically remain open indefinitely, provided the trader:\n\nMaintains sufficient margin\n\nPays any required funding\n\nAvoids liquidation\n\nContinues using a functioning trading platform\n\nBecause the contract has no expiry date, it cannot rely on expiry-based convergence to remain near the spot price.\n\nPerpetual markets use a funding mechanism to encourage the contract price to remain aligned with the underlying market.\n\nPerpetual contracts are among the most actively used instruments in cryptocurrency trading.\n\nTheir convenience can disguise the fact that they combine leverage, funding, counterparty and liquidation risks.\n\n### Spot Exposure Versus Derivative Exposure\n\nSpot and derivative positions can produce similar directional results while creating different legal and economic exposures.\n\n| Characteristic | Spot Asset | Futures or Perpetual Contract |\n| --- | --- | --- |\n| Ownership | Direct or custodial claim to asset | Contractual price exposure |\n| Expiry | None | Futures expire; perpetuals do not |\n| Leverage | Usually none unless borrowed funds are used | Commonly available |\n| Liquidation | Not normally applicable without borrowing | Possible when margin becomes insufficient |\n| Funding | No perpetual funding payment | Perpetual funding may apply |\n| Custody | Wallet or exchange custody | Exchange or protocol collateral system |\n| Short exposure | Requires borrowing or another structure | Commonly available |\n| Withdrawal | Underlying asset may be withdrawn | Contract itself is not ordinarily withdrawn |\n\nA participant should not assume that derivative exposure is equivalent to owning the underlying cryptocurrency.','markdown',NULL,NULL,NULL,6,0,0,0,'',NULL,1,1785297600000 WHERE EXISTS (SELECT 1 FROM `courses` WHERE `id`='cognizen-crypto-mastery-foundations-production');
--> statement-breakpoint
INSERT OR IGNORE INTO `lessons` (`id`,`course_id`,`title`,`section_id`,`lesson_type`,`content`,`content_format`,`video_key`,`primary_asset_id`,`intro_asset_id`,`duration_minutes`,`is_preview`,`available_after_days`,`required_watch_percent`,`transcript`,`experience_json`,`position`,`updated_at`) SELECT 'cmf-module-3-07-lesson-02','cognizen-crypto-mastery-foundations-production','Long Positions and Maintenance Margin','cmf-module-3-07','text','### Long Positions\n\nA long position benefits when the contract price rises.\n\nSuppose a trader opens a long Bitcoin perpetual position when Bitcoin trades at 50,000 units.\n\nIf the position is later closed at 55,000, the trader earns a profit before fees and funding.\n\nIf Bitcoin falls to 45,000, the position loses value.\n\nThe basic logic is:\n\nLong profit = Exit price − Entry price\n\nThe actual monetary result depends on:\n\nPosition quantity\n\nContract multiplier\n\nMargin denomination\n\nFees\n\nFunding\n\nSettlement method\n\nA long position can lose the margin deposited long before the underlying asset reaches zero.\n\n### Short Positions\n\nA short position benefits when the contract price falls.\n\nSuppose a trader opens a short position at 50,000 and closes it at 45,000.\n\nThe price difference is favourable to the short.\n\nIf price instead rises to 55,000, the short position loses value.\n\nThe simplified logic is:\n\nShort profit = Entry price − Exit price\n\nA short position carries a particularly important risk: the underlying asset has no fixed maximum price.\n\nA long spot position can lose no more than the amount invested if no borrowing is involved.\n\nA short derivative position can produce losses that grow as price continues rising, subject to liquidation and margin rules.\n\n### Contract Specifications\n\nEvery futures or perpetual contract has defined specifications.\n\nThese may include:\n\nUnderlying reference asset\n\nContract size\n\nTick size\n\nSettlement currency\n\nMargin currency\n\nExpiry date\n\nFunding interval\n\nIndex composition\n\nMaintenance margin\n\nMaximum leverage\n\nTrading hours\n\nSettlement procedure\n\nTwo contracts referencing the same cryptocurrency may behave differently because their specifications differ.\n\nBefore entering, the trader should know exactly what one contract represents.\n\nTen contracts do not necessarily equal ten tokens.\n\n### Contract Size\n\nA contract may represent:\n\nOne full token\n\nA fraction of a token\n\nA fixed amount of national currency\n\nA fixed cryptocurrency value\n\nSuppose one futures contract represents 0.01 Bitcoin.\n\nA position of 100 contracts represents exposure to:\n\n100 × 0.01 = 1 Bitcoin\n\nIf one Bitcoin is worth 60,000 units, the position’s notional exposure is approximately 60,000 units.\n\nThe contract count alone does not reveal the financial exposure.\n\n### Notional Exposure\n\nNotional exposure is the total market value controlled by the derivative position.\n\nFor a simple linear contract:\n\nNotional exposure = Asset quantity × Market price\n\nSuppose a trader controls 2 Bitcoin at a price of 50,000 units.\n\nThe notional exposure is:\n\n2 × 50,000 = 100,000 units\n\nIf the trader deposits only 10,000 units of margin, the position is leveraged ten times relative to the initial collateral.\n\nProfit, loss and trading costs are generally influenced by the full 100,000-unit exposure, not merely the 10,000-unit deposit.\n\n### Leverage\n\nLeverage allows a trader to control exposure larger than the capital deposited.\n\nThe simplified relationship is:\n\nLeverage = Notional exposure ÷ Margin committed\n\nSuppose:\n\nPosition exposure: 50,000 units\n\nInitial margin: 5,000 units\n\nLeverage:\n\n50,000 ÷ 5,000 = 10 times\n\nA one-percent movement in the underlying asset creates an approximate ten-percent change relative to the initial margin before fees, funding and margin adjustments.\n\nA ten-percent adverse movement may consume approximately the full initial margin, although actual liquidation generally occurs earlier because the platform requires maintenance margin.\n\n### Leverage Does Not Increase Market Predictability\n\nLeverage does not make a market signal more reliable.\n\nIt only magnifies the financial consequence of the movement.\n\nA technically strong setup can still experience an ordinary pullback.\n\nWithout leverage, the participant may remain in the position.\n\nWith excessive leverage, the same pullback may cause liquidation.\n\nThe correct sequence is:\n\nDefine the strategy.\n\nIdentify invalidation.\n\nDecide the maximum acceptable loss.\n\nCalculate position size.\n\nUse only the leverage required to create that position.\n\nStarting with the maximum leverage available reverses the risk-management process.\n\n### Initial Margin\n\nInitial margin is the collateral required to open a leveraged position.\n\nIf a platform requires ten-percent initial margin, the trader may control a position worth ten times the margin deposit.\n\nSuppose:\n\nPosition notional value: 20,000 units\n\nInitial margin requirement: 10 percent\n\nRequired margin:\n\n20,000 × 10 percent = 2,000 units\n\nInitial margin allows the position to open.\n\nIt does not define how much collateral must remain available afterward.\n\nThat is determined partly by maintenance margin.\n\n### Maintenance Margin\n\nMaintenance margin is the minimum collateral required to keep a position open.\n\nAs an adverse market movement reduces account equity, the position approaches the maintenance threshold.\n\nWhen available margin falls below the required level, the platform may begin liquidation.\n\nMaintenance margin can vary according to:\n\nPosition size\n\nContract\n\nRisk tier\n\nLeverage\n\nPlatform\n\nMarket volatility\n\nLarger positions may face higher maintenance requirements because they are more difficult to liquidate safely.','markdown',NULL,NULL,NULL,6,0,0,0,'',NULL,2,1785297600000 WHERE EXISTS (SELECT 1 FROM `courses` WHERE `id`='cognizen-crypto-mastery-foundations-production');
--> statement-breakpoint
INSERT OR IGNORE INTO `lessons` (`id`,`course_id`,`title`,`section_id`,`lesson_type`,`content`,`content_format`,`video_key`,`primary_asset_id`,`intro_asset_id`,`duration_minutes`,`is_preview`,`available_after_days`,`required_watch_percent`,`transcript`,`experience_json`,`position`,`updated_at`) SELECT 'cmf-module-3-07-lesson-03','cognizen-crypto-mastery-foundations-production','Margin Balance and Equity and Stablecoin-Margined Contracts','cmf-module-3-07','text','### Margin Balance and Equity\n\nA derivatives account may display several related values.\n\nWallet balance generally reflects deposited collateral and realised profit or loss.\n\nUnrealised profit or loss reflects the current estimated value of open positions.\n\nAccount equity may be calculated as:\n\nWallet balance + Unrealised profit or loss\n\nAvailable margin is the portion still available for new positions or to absorb further losses.\n\nThe exact terminology differs across platforms.\n\nThe trader should understand the platform’s definitions rather than relying on assumptions from another exchange.\n\n### Isolated Margin\n\nUnder isolated margin, a specified amount of collateral is assigned to one position.\n\nIf the position is liquidated, the loss is generally limited to the margin allocated to it, subject to fees and platform rules.\n\nPotential advantages include:\n\nClearer position-level risk\n\nReduced contagion to other trades\n\nEasier liquidation analysis\n\nPotential limitations include:\n\nThe position may liquidate even when unused capital exists elsewhere\n\nAdditional margin may need to be transferred manually\n\nMultiple isolated positions require separate management\n\nIsolated margin can help prevent one trade from consuming the entire derivatives account.\n\n### Cross Margin\n\nUnder cross margin, available account equity supports multiple positions.\n\nProfits and unused collateral elsewhere may help keep a losing position open.\n\nThis can improve capital efficiency.\n\nIt can also spread one position’s loss across the entire account.\n\nA severe loss in one contract may threaten collateral intended for other positions.\n\nCross margin should not be interpreted as safer simply because the liquidation price appears farther away.\n\nMore capital is exposed.\n\n### Portfolio Margin\n\nSome advanced platforms calculate margin according to the combined risk of several positions.\n\nA hedged portfolio may require less margin because gains in one position may offset losses in another.\n\nFor example, a long spot position and short futures position may have lower net directional risk.\n\nPortfolio margin introduces model risk.\n\nIf correlations or hedges behave differently during stress, the required margin may increase or the portfolio may lose more than expected.\n\nThe trader must understand both individual and combined exposures.\n\n### Unrealised and Realised Profit or Loss\n\nAn open position has unrealised profit or loss.\n\nThe result becomes realised when the position is closed or settled.\n\nFor a simple linear long:\n\nProfit or loss = Position quantity × (Exit price − Entry price)\n\nSuppose:\n\nLong quantity: 2 tokens\n\nEntry: 1,500\n\nExit: 1,650\n\nProfit:\n\n2 × (1,650 − 1,500) = 300 units\n\nThis excludes:\n\nTrading fees\n\nFunding\n\nBorrowing costs\n\nSlippage\n\nA position may show an unrealised gain while producing a smaller realised gain after these costs.\n\n### Percentage Return on Margin\n\nReturn on margin compares profit or loss with the collateral committed.\n\nSuppose:\n\nMargin: 2,000 units\n\nPosition profit: 400 units\n\nReturn on margin:\n\n400 ÷ 2,000 × 100 = 20 percent\n\nThis can make leveraged returns appear impressive.\n\nThe corresponding loss is equally amplified.\n\nReturn on margin should not be confused with the percentage movement of the underlying asset.\n\n### Linear Contracts\n\nA linear contract calculates profit and loss in a stable or national-currency-linked unit.\n\nFor example, a contract may be margined and settled in a stablecoin.\n\nThe basic profit calculation is relatively intuitive:\n\nQuantity × Price difference\n\nPotential benefits include:\n\nClear profit and loss\n\nStable collateral value under normal conditions\n\nEasier accounting\n\nRisks include:\n\nStablecoin depegging\n\nIssuer risk\n\nExchange custody\n\nContract liquidation\n\n### Inverse Contracts\n\nAn inverse contract is margined or settled in the underlying cryptocurrency.\n\nIts profit and loss calculation is based on the inverse of price.\n\nFor example, a Bitcoin inverse contract may use Bitcoin as collateral and settlement.\n\nThe contract allows a participant to trade Bitcoin exposure while holding Bitcoin margin.\n\nHowever, when Bitcoin falls, the position’s collateral may also decline in national-currency value.\n\nThis creates different risk behaviour from a stablecoin-margined contract.\n\nInverse contracts require careful understanding of the platform’s formula.\n\n### Coin-Margined Contracts\n\nCoin-margined contracts use a cryptocurrency as collateral.\n\nA trader may use Bitcoin to margin Bitcoin futures or another contract.\n\nPotential advantages include:\n\nNo stablecoin requirement\n\nAccumulation of the underlying asset when profitable\n\nNatural use for some hedging strategies\n\nPotential risks include:\n\nCollateral value changes with the market\n\nAdverse price movement can weaken both the position and margin\n\nProfit and loss may be less intuitive\n\nA trader shorting Bitcoin using Bitcoin collateral may see the short gain while the national-currency value of the collateral falls.\n\nThe combined portfolio result should be evaluated.\n\n### Stablecoin-Margined Contracts\n\nStablecoin-margined contracts use a stable-value token as collateral and settlement.\n\nPotential advantages include:\n\nMore intuitive profit and loss\n\nStable unit of account under normal conditions\n\nEasier comparison across positions\n\nPotential risks include:\n\nStablecoin depegging\n\nIssuer freezing\n\nReserve failure\n\nPlatform concentration\n\nA derivatives portfolio that appears diversified across assets may still depend entirely on one stablecoin.','markdown',NULL,NULL,NULL,6,0,0,0,'',NULL,3,1785297600000 WHERE EXISTS (SELECT 1 FROM `courses` WHERE `id`='cognizen-crypto-mastery-foundations-production');
--> statement-breakpoint
INSERT OR IGNORE INTO `lessons` (`id`,`course_id`,`title`,`section_id`,`lesson_type`,`content`,`content_format`,`video_key`,`primary_asset_id`,`intro_asset_id`,`duration_minutes`,`is_preview`,`available_after_days`,`required_watch_percent`,`transcript`,`experience_json`,`position`,`updated_at`) SELECT 'cmf-module-3-07-lesson-04','cognizen-crypto-mastery-foundations-production','Futures Expiry and Calendar Spreads','cmf-module-3-07','text','### Futures Expiry\n\nA dated futures contract has a settlement date.\n\nAt expiry, the contract is closed or settled according to its rules.\n\nSettlement may use an index price calculated over a defined period.\n\nA trader who wishes to maintain exposure beyond expiry must close the expiring contract and open a later one.\n\nThis process is known as rolling the position.\n\nRolling can create costs or gains depending on the relationship between contract prices.\n\n### Futures Basis\n\nThe futures basis is the difference between the futures price and the current spot price.\n\nA simple basis calculation is:\n\nBasis = Futures price − Spot price\n\nSuppose:\n\nSpot price: 50,000\n\nThree-month futures price: 52,000\n\nBasis:\n\n52,000 − 50,000 = 2,000 units\n\nPercentage basis:\n\n2,000 ÷ 50,000 × 100 = 4 percent\n\nThe futures trades four percent above spot.\n\n### Contango\n\nContango occurs when futures trade above the current spot price.\n\nIt may reflect:\n\nFinancing costs\n\nBullish demand\n\nStorage or custody considerations\n\nInstitutional positioning\n\nTime value\n\nMarket leverage\n\nIn cryptocurrency, contango is common during bullish or high-demand conditions.\n\nA high positive basis may create a carry opportunity.\n\nIt can also indicate crowded leveraged optimism.\n\n### Backwardation\n\nBackwardation occurs when futures trade below the current spot price.\n\nIt may reflect:\n\nBearish positioning\n\nImmediate spot demand\n\nMarket stress\n\nShortage of collateral\n\nDeleveraging\n\nExpectations of lower future prices\n\nBackwardation is not automatically a buy or sell signal.\n\nIt describes the relationship between two markets.\n\nThe basis may normalise through movement in spot, futures or both.\n\n### Convergence at Expiry\n\nAs a futures contract approaches settlement, its price should converge toward the settlement index.\n\nIf the futures remained far above or below spot at expiry, arbitrage opportunities would generally encourage convergence.\n\nThe exact settlement mechanism matters.\n\nA contract may settle against a multi-exchange index rather than the last traded price on the derivatives platform.\n\nConvergence creates the foundation for several basis strategies.\n\n### Annualised Basis\n\nA futures premium covering only a few months can be converted into an approximate annualised rate.\n\nSuppose:\n\nSpot price: 50,000\n\nThree-month futures price: 51,500\n\nBasis: 3 percent\n\nTime to expiry: approximately one-quarter year\n\nSimple annualised basis:\n\n3 percent ÷ 0.25 = approximately 12 percent\n\nThis approximation excludes:\n\nCompounding\n\nTrading fees\n\nCustody costs\n\nMargin changes\n\nTax\n\nCounterparty risk\n\nAn annualised basis is not a guaranteed return.\n\n### Cash-and-Carry Strategy\n\nA cash-and-carry strategy attempts to capture positive futures basis.\n\nA simplified version involves:\n\nBuying the spot asset\n\nSelling an equivalent futures contract\n\nHolding both until convergence or expiry\n\nThe spot position gains when price rises and loses when price falls.\n\nThe futures short produces the opposite directional result.\n\nThe combined position aims to reduce price exposure and capture the futures premium.\n\nThe strategy is often described as market neutral.\n\nIt remains exposed to:\n\nExchange failure\n\nMargin calls\n\nBasis movement\n\nExecution mismatch\n\nStablecoin risk\n\nCustody risk\n\nFees\n\nTax\n\nInability to maintain both legs\n\n### Reverse Cash-and-Carry\n\nWhen futures trade below spot, a reverse cash-and-carry strategy may involve:\n\nShorting or borrowing the spot asset\n\nBuying the discounted futures contract\n\nHolding toward convergence\n\nThis can be difficult because:\n\nSpot borrowing may be expensive\n\nThe asset may be unavailable to borrow\n\nThe lender may recall it\n\nShort-selling creates additional risk\n\nExchange and settlement conditions may differ\n\nThe theoretical arbitrage may not be practically executable.\n\n### Rolling Futures\n\nA trader maintaining long-term futures exposure must roll from an expiring contract into a later one.\n\nDuring contango, the later contract may be more expensive.\n\nA long trader may repeatedly sell the cheaper expiring contract and buy the more expensive later one.\n\nThis creates negative roll yield.\n\nA short trader may benefit from the same structure, all else equal.\n\nDuring backwardation, the effects reverse.\n\nThe total return of a futures strategy therefore depends on both price movement and the term structure.\n\n### Futures Term Structure\n\nThe term structure compares futures prices across several expiry dates.\n\nAn upward-sloping curve generally shows later contracts trading at higher prices.\n\nA downward-sloping curve shows later contracts trading lower.\n\nChanges in the curve may reveal:\n\nDemand for leverage\n\nMarket stress\n\nFinancing conditions\n\nExpectations\n\nRelative scarcity\n\nThe curve can change without a large movement in spot price.\n\nAdvanced traders may trade relationships between different maturities rather than the outright asset direction.\n\n### Calendar Spreads\n\nA calendar spread takes opposite positions in futures with different expiries.\n\nFor example:\n\nLong a near-term contract\n\nShort a longer-term contract\n\nThe strategy focuses on changes in the relationship between maturities.\n\nRisks include:\n\nCurve movement\n\nDifferent liquidity across contracts\n\nMargin changes\n\nExecution mismatch\n\nExpiry behaviour\n\nA calendar spread is not automatically low risk because the positions reference the same asset.','markdown',NULL,NULL,NULL,6,0,0,0,'',NULL,4,1785297600000 WHERE EXISTS (SELECT 1 FROM `courses` WHERE `id`='cognizen-crypto-mastery-foundations-production');
--> statement-breakpoint
INSERT OR IGNORE INTO `lessons` (`id`,`course_id`,`title`,`section_id`,`lesson_type`,`content`,`content_format`,`video_key`,`primary_asset_id`,`intro_asset_id`,`duration_minutes`,`is_preview`,`available_after_days`,`required_watch_percent`,`transcript`,`experience_json`,`position`,`updated_at`) SELECT 'cmf-module-3-07-lesson-05','cognizen-crypto-mastery-foundations-production','Perpetual Funding and Liquidation','cmf-module-3-07','text','### Perpetual Funding\n\nPerpetual contracts use funding payments to encourage alignment with spot prices.\n\nFunding is exchanged between long and short position holders.\n\nThe trading platform normally facilitates the payment but may not receive it as revenue, although platform structures differ.\n\nWhen the perpetual price trades above its reference market, funding is often positive.\n\nLongs may pay shorts.\n\nWhen the perpetual price trades below the reference, funding may be negative.\n\nShorts may pay longs.\n\nThe objective is to encourage traders to take the side that pushes the perpetual price back toward spot.\n\n### Positive Funding\n\nPositive funding commonly indicates that long exposure is more expensive to maintain.\n\nSuppose a trader holds a long perpetual position worth 100,000 units.\n\nIf the funding rate for the interval is 0.01 percent, the payment is approximately:\n\n100,000 × 0.01 percent = 10 units\n\nIf this occurs several times each day, the cost can accumulate.\n\nA long position can be correct about direction but underperform because of persistent funding payments.\n\n### Negative Funding\n\nNegative funding generally means short positions pay long positions.\n\nThis may occur when bearish demand pushes the perpetual below its reference price.\n\nReceiving funding does not make the long position safe.\n\nPrice can continue falling faster than the funding income.\n\nSimilarly, a short paying negative funding can remain profitable if the price decline is sufficiently large.\n\nFunding is one component of return.\n\n### Funding Is Applied to Notional Exposure\n\nFunding is generally calculated on the full position notional.\n\nSuppose:\n\nMargin deposited: 5,000 units\n\nLeverage: 10 times\n\nPosition notional: 50,000 units\n\nFunding: 0.02 percent\n\nFunding payment:\n\n50,000 × 0.02 percent = 10 units\n\nRelative to the 5,000-unit margin, the payment represents 0.2 percent for that interval.\n\nLeverage magnifies the effect of recurring funding on the trader’s capital.\n\n### Funding Intervals\n\nFunding may be exchanged at defined intervals.\n\nThe interval differs by platform and contract.\n\nA trader who opens and closes before the funding timestamp may avoid that specific payment, depending on platform rules.\n\nThe market can adjust before funding because participants anticipate the transfer.\n\nAttempting to capture one funding payment without considering price movement can create greater loss than the income received.\n\n### Predicted Funding Rates\n\nPlatforms often display an estimated future funding rate.\n\nThis estimate can change before the funding interval ends.\n\nIt may depend on:\n\nPerpetual premium\n\nInterest-rate component\n\nPlatform formula\n\nTime-weighted calculations\n\nRate caps\n\nThe predicted value is not always the final value.\n\nA strategy should not rely on one estimate without understanding the calculation.\n\n### Funding-Rate Arbitrage\n\nA simplified funding strategy may involve:\n\nBuying the spot asset\n\nShorting an equivalent perpetual contract\n\nReceiving positive funding from long traders\n\nThe spot and short positions reduce net directional exposure.\n\nThe strategy may earn funding if it remains positive.\n\nRisks include:\n\nFunding reversing\n\nBasis movement\n\nExchange failure\n\nMargin liquidation\n\nExecution mismatch\n\nTransfer delays\n\nStablecoin or collateral risk\n\nFees\n\nA market-neutral description does not eliminate platform and funding uncertainty.\n\n### Mark Price\n\nThe mark price is an estimated fair value used by many derivatives platforms to calculate unrealised profit, margin and liquidation.\n\nIt may be derived from:\n\nSpot index\n\nPerpetual premium\n\nSmoothing mechanism\n\nFunding basis\n\nThe mark price helps reduce unnecessary liquidations caused by one abnormal trade on the derivatives exchange.\n\nA trader may see the last traded price at one level and the mark price at another.\n\nLiquidation can be triggered by the mark price even when the last price has not touched the displayed liquidation level, depending on platform presentation.\n\n### Index Price\n\nThe index price is generally calculated from prices across one or more spot exchanges.\n\nThe methodology may:\n\nRemove outliers\n\nWeight venues\n\nUse median prices\n\nAdjust stale data\n\nExclude failed exchanges\n\nThe index provides an external market reference.\n\nIts reliability depends on the quality of the included exchanges and the calculation rules.\n\nDuring a stablecoin depeg or exchange outage, index construction becomes especially important.\n\n### Last Traded Price\n\nThe last traded price is the most recent transaction on the derivatives venue.\n\nIt may move briefly because of:\n\nThin liquidity\n\nOne large order\n\nLiquidation\n\nExchange-specific activity\n\nPlatforms may allow stop orders to trigger from the last price, mark price or index price.\n\nThe trader should choose the reference deliberately.\n\n### Liquidation\n\nLiquidation occurs when a leveraged position no longer has sufficient margin to meet the platform’s maintenance requirements.\n\nThe platform closes part or all of the position to prevent the account from developing a deficit.\n\nLiquidation is not the same as a trader-controlled stop-loss.\n\nIt is a risk-control process designed primarily to protect the platform and other market participants.\n\nThe liquidation price may change as:\n\nFunding is paid\n\nFees accrue\n\nMargin changes\n\nPosition size changes\n\nMaintenance requirements change\n\nCollateral value changes\n\nA trader should never use liquidation as the planned exit.','markdown',NULL,NULL,NULL,6,0,0,0,'',NULL,5,1785297600000 WHERE EXISTS (SELECT 1 FROM `courses` WHERE `id`='cognizen-crypto-mastery-foundations-production');
--> statement-breakpoint
INSERT OR IGNORE INTO `lessons` (`id`,`course_id`,`title`,`section_id`,`lesson_type`,`content`,`content_format`,`video_key`,`primary_asset_id`,`intro_asset_id`,`duration_minutes`,`is_preview`,`available_after_days`,`required_watch_percent`,`transcript`,`experience_json`,`position`,`updated_at`) SELECT 'cmf-module-3-07-lesson-06','cognizen-crypto-mastery-foundations-production','Simplified Liquidation Logic and Volume Versus Open Interest','cmf-module-3-07','text','### Simplified Liquidation Logic\n\nSuppose a trader opens a highly leveraged long position.\n\nAs price falls, unrealised losses reduce equity.\n\nWhen account equity approaches the maintenance margin requirement, the liquidation engine intervenes.\n\nThe exact calculation may include:\n\nEntry price\n\nLeverage\n\nPosition size\n\nMaintenance margin\n\nFees\n\nFunding\n\nCollateral type\n\nThe displayed liquidation price should be treated as an estimate under current conditions, not a permanent fixed boundary.\n\n### Liquidation and Leverage\n\nHigher leverage generally moves the liquidation price closer to the entry.\n\nA five-times leveraged position has more room than a fifty-times leveraged position, assuming the same margin structure.\n\nAt very high leverage, a small price movement can trigger liquidation.\n\nCryptocurrency markets commonly experience intraday movements larger than the margin available under extreme leverage.\n\nA trader can therefore be correct about the broader daily or weekly direction but liquidated by short-term noise.\n\n### Partial Liquidation\n\nSome platforms reduce a position gradually when margin becomes insufficient.\n\nThe system may close part of the exposure and lower the maintenance requirement.\n\nThis can preserve the remaining position.\n\nIt also realises losses and incurs fees.\n\nOther platforms may close the complete position depending on size and risk tier.\n\nThe participant should know how the venue handles liquidation before trading.\n\n### Liquidation Fees\n\nA liquidated position may incur additional charges.\n\nThese can include:\n\nLiquidation fee\n\nTaker fee\n\nInsurance-fund contribution\n\nBankruptcy-price adjustment\n\nThe realised loss may therefore exceed the amount suggested by ordinary price movement.\n\nLiquidation is generally more expensive and less controlled than a planned exit.\n\n### Bankruptcy Price\n\nThe bankruptcy price is the approximate level at which the position’s remaining margin would be exhausted.\n\nThe liquidation engine normally attempts to close the position before or around this level.\n\nIf the market moves too quickly and the position is closed beyond the bankruptcy price, a deficit can occur.\n\nInsurance funds and automatic deleveraging systems may be used to manage this deficit.\n\n### Insurance Funds\n\nA derivatives platform may maintain an insurance fund to absorb losses when liquidated positions cannot be closed without creating a deficit.\n\nThe fund may be built from:\n\nLiquidation proceeds\n\nPlatform contributions\n\nFees\n\nPrevious surplus\n\nAn insurance fund can reduce the need to socialise losses.\n\nIts effectiveness depends on:\n\nSize\n\nTransparency\n\nAsset quality\n\nStress conditions\n\nPlatform governance\n\nA large fund does not make the exchange or contract risk-free.\n\n### Automatic Deleveraging\n\nAutomatic deleveraging, or ADL, may occur when a profitable trader’s position is reduced because the platform cannot absorb losses from liquidated counterparties.\n\nThe system may select positions according to:\n\nProfitability\n\nLeverage\n\nRanking rules\n\nA trader can therefore have a profitable position closed involuntarily during extreme market conditions.\n\nADL is an important reminder that derivative profits remain dependent on the platform’s ability to manage counterparties and liquidations.\n\n### Socialised Losses\n\nSome derivative systems distribute unresolved losses across profitable users or a wider participant pool.\n\nThis is known as socialised loss.\n\nModern platforms often use insurance funds and liquidation systems to reduce this risk.\n\nIt remains possible under extreme conditions or weaker platform designs.\n\nContract terms should explain who bears losses when the liquidation process fails.\n\n### Liquidation Cascades\n\nA liquidation cascade develops when forced position closures amplify market movement.\n\nDuring a decline:\n\nLong positions lose margin.\n\nLiquidations create market sell orders.\n\nSelling pushes price lower.\n\nMore long positions become liquidatable.\n\nThe cycle continues.\n\nDuring a short squeeze, forced buying produces the opposite process.\n\nCascades can cause sharp deviations from normal valuation and liquidity.\n\nThey can also create temporary opportunities after forced activity ends.\n\nEntering during the cascade is highly risky because the extent of remaining leverage is uncertain.\n\n### Open Interest\n\nOpen interest measures the total outstanding derivative positions that remain open.\n\nIt increases when new contracts are created and decreases when positions are closed or liquidated.\n\nOpen interest does not reveal direction by itself because every contract has both a long and a short side.\n\nIts interpretation depends on price, volume, funding and market context.\n\n### Price and Open-Interest Combinations\n\nRising price with rising open interest may suggest new leveraged participation supporting the move.\n\nRising price with falling open interest may indicate short covering.\n\nFalling price with rising open interest may indicate new bearish positioning or hedging.\n\nFalling price with falling open interest may indicate long liquidation or broad deleveraging.\n\nThese interpretations are possibilities rather than guaranteed conclusions.\n\nThe identity and motivation of participants remain uncertain.\n\n### Volume Versus Open Interest\n\nVolume measures how much trading occurred during a period.\n\nOpen interest measures how many derivative positions remain outstanding.\n\nA market can have high volume and stable open interest if positions change hands frequently without net creation.\n\nA market can have rising open interest with moderate volume when participants build positions gradually.\n\nBoth metrics provide useful but different information.','markdown',NULL,NULL,NULL,6,0,0,0,'',NULL,6,1785297600000 WHERE EXISTS (SELECT 1 FROM `courses` WHERE `id`='cognizen-crypto-mastery-foundations-production');
--> statement-breakpoint
INSERT OR IGNORE INTO `lessons` (`id`,`course_id`,`title`,`section_id`,`lesson_type`,`content`,`content_format`,`video_key`,`primary_asset_id`,`intro_asset_id`,`duration_minutes`,`is_preview`,`available_after_days`,`required_watch_percent`,`transcript`,`experience_json`,`position`,`updated_at`) SELECT 'cmf-module-3-07-lesson-07','cognizen-crypto-mastery-foundations-production','Long-Short Ratios and Reduce-Only Exits','cmf-module-3-07','text','### Long-Short Ratios\n\nSome platforms publish measures of long and short positioning.\n\nThese may reflect:\n\nNumber of accounts\n\nPosition value\n\nSelected trader groups\n\nTop traders\n\nExchange-specific data\n\nA ratio showing more long accounts does not mean greater total long exposure.\n\nA small number of large short positions may offset many small longs.\n\nThe measure may also represent only one platform.\n\nLong-short ratios should be treated cautiously.\n\n### Futures for Hedging\n\nA hedge reduces the effect of an adverse price movement on another position.\n\nSuppose an investor owns 2 Bitcoin in spot and is concerned about a temporary decline.\n\nThey may short futures representing 1 Bitcoin.\n\nIf Bitcoin falls, the spot position loses value while the futures short gains.\n\nThe investor has reduced net exposure from 2 Bitcoin to approximately 1 Bitcoin.\n\nThe hedge does not need to eliminate all risk.\n\nIt can be partial.\n\n### Hedge Ratio\n\nThe hedge ratio determines how much derivative exposure offsets the underlying position.\n\nA simplified hedge ratio is:\n\nDerivative exposure ÷ Spot exposure\n\nSuppose:\n\nSpot exposure: 100,000 units\n\nShort futures exposure: 60,000 units\n\nHedge ratio:\n\n60,000 ÷ 100,000 = 60 percent\n\nThe portfolio remains forty percent net long, ignoring basis and other risks.\n\nA hedge ratio can change as prices and position values change.\n\n### Full Hedge Versus Partial Hedge\n\nA full hedge attempts to offset nearly all directional price exposure.\n\nA partial hedge reduces but does not eliminate exposure.\n\nA full hedge may protect capital but also removes most gains if the asset rises.\n\nA partial hedge allows continued participation while reducing drawdown.\n\nThe appropriate hedge depends on:\n\nObjective\n\nTime horizon\n\nTax\n\nBasis\n\nFunding\n\nTransaction costs\n\nConfidence\n\nHedging is not free. It replaces part of the price risk with contract and execution costs.\n\n### Cross-Hedging\n\nA cross-hedge uses a derivative on one asset to reduce risk in another related asset.\n\nFor example, a portfolio of altcoins may be partially hedged using Bitcoin futures.\n\nThis may work when the assets are strongly correlated.\n\nThe hedge may fail when:\n\nCorrelations change\n\nOne token experiences a project-specific event\n\nAltcoins decline more than Bitcoin\n\nMarket liquidity fragments\n\nCross-hedging introduces basis risk between the portfolio and the hedge instrument.\n\n### Basis Risk\n\nBasis risk is the risk that the derivative and underlying exposure do not move as expected relative to each other.\n\nA futures hedge may be imperfect because:\n\nContract price differs from spot\n\nPortfolio contains different assets\n\nFunding changes\n\nExpiry affects pricing\n\nLiquidity differs\n\nIndex methodology differs\n\nThe hedge can reduce one risk while creating another.\n\n### Hedging Versus Selling\n\nAn investor can reduce exposure by selling part of the asset or by opening a short derivative.\n\nSelling may:\n\nSimplify the portfolio\n\nRemove funding and liquidation risk\n\nCreate custody or tax consequences\n\nEnd part of the asset exposure\n\nHedging may:\n\nPreserve ownership\n\nAvoid moving the underlying asset\n\nIntroduce margin and counterparty risk\n\nRequire active monitoring\n\nThe more complex solution is not automatically better.\n\n### Futures for Speculation\n\nA speculative futures position seeks profit from price movement rather than reducing an existing risk.\n\nThe trader may use leverage to increase exposure.\n\nSpeculation is not inherently inappropriate.\n\nIt should be recognised honestly.\n\nA position described as a hedge should have an underlying exposure to offset.\n\nWithout that exposure, the short or long contract is a directional trade.\n\nClear classification helps prevent risk from being disguised through professional terminology.\n\n### Futures for Portfolio Adjustment\n\nDerivatives can change portfolio exposure quickly without buying or selling every underlying asset.\n\nA portfolio manager may use futures to:\n\nReduce market beta\n\nIncrease temporary exposure\n\nHedge event risk\n\nProtect a liquidity reserve\n\nAdjust during exchange-transfer delays\n\nThe convenience must be balanced against:\n\nMargin\n\nFunding\n\nContract liquidity\n\nCounterparty concentration\n\nOperational complexity\n\n### Stop-Losses in Derivative Markets\n\nA stop-loss is especially important when leverage is used.\n\nThe stop should be placed according to the strategy’s invalidation point and used to calculate position size.\n\nIt should not be placed merely a small distance from the entry to support a larger leveraged position.\n\nThe stop trigger may use:\n\nMark price\n\nLast price\n\nIndex price\n\nThe trader should confirm the chosen reference.\n\nA stop order may still experience slippage.\n\n### Reduce-Only Exits\n\nDerivative exit orders should generally use reduce-only instructions when available.\n\nThis helps ensure that a stop or target closes the existing position rather than opening a new position in the opposite direction.\n\nThis becomes particularly important when:\n\nSeveral targets exist\n\nA position is reduced manually\n\nPartial fills occur\n\nMultiple devices or systems manage the account\n\nAfter closing, stale orders should still be verified and cancelled.','markdown',NULL,NULL,NULL,6,0,0,0,'',NULL,7,1785297600000 WHERE EXISTS (SELECT 1 FROM `courses` WHERE `id`='cognizen-crypto-mastery-foundations-production');
--> statement-breakpoint
INSERT OR IGNORE INTO `lessons` (`id`,`course_id`,`title`,`section_id`,`lesson_type`,`content`,`content_format`,`video_key`,`primary_asset_id`,`intro_asset_id`,`duration_minutes`,`is_preview`,`available_after_days`,`required_watch_percent`,`transcript`,`experience_json`,`position`,`updated_at`) SELECT 'cmf-module-3-07-lesson-08','cognizen-crypto-mastery-foundations-production','Bracket Orders and Adding Margin','cmf-module-3-07','text','### Bracket Orders\n\nA bracket order combines an entry with a protective stop and profit target.\n\nIt helps ensure that the risk plan becomes active immediately after entry.\n\nThe participant should confirm how the exchange handles:\n\nPartial entry fills\n\nStop quantity\n\nTarget quantity\n\nCancellation of the opposite exit\n\nReduce-only settings\n\nAutomation is useful only when the platform implements the intended logic correctly.\n\n### Funding and Holding Period\n\nFunding affects perpetual positions according to how long they remain open.\n\nA short-term position may experience little funding.\n\nA long-term position held through many intervals can accumulate significant costs or income.\n\nA trader should estimate funding under several scenarios rather than assume the current rate will remain unchanged.\n\nAn annualised funding rate based on one interval can be extremely misleading.\n\n### Funding Can Reverse\n\nFunding is variable.\n\nA long position may begin by receiving funding and later start paying it.\n\nA basis or funding strategy that depends on persistent positive rates may become unprofitable when positioning changes.\n\nThe trader should define:\n\nMinimum acceptable funding\n\nMaximum adverse funding\n\nExit conditions\n\nRebalancing procedure\n\nFunding income should never be treated as guaranteed interest.\n\n### Exchange Counterparty Risk\n\nCentralised derivatives trading requires confidence that the exchange can:\n\nHold collateral\n\nProcess withdrawals\n\nCalculate profit accurately\n\nMaintain the matching engine\n\nManage liquidations\n\nHonour profitable positions\n\nRisks include:\n\nInsolvency\n\nHacking\n\nFraud\n\nAccount freezing\n\nRegulatory action\n\nSystem outage\n\nMarket manipulation\n\nWithdrawal suspension\n\nA profitable derivative position is only as valuable as the platform’s ability and willingness to honour it.\n\n### Decentralised Perpetual Protocols\n\nDecentralised perpetual platforms use smart contracts, liquidity pools, order books or hybrid structures.\n\nThey may offer self-custodial or partially self-custodial trading.\n\nAdditional risks can include:\n\nSmart contract exploits\n\nOracle failure\n\nLiquidity-pool losses\n\nGovernance changes\n\nSequencer downtime\n\nBridge risk\n\nKeeper failure\n\nFront-end compromise\n\n“Decentralised” changes the counterparty structure. It does not eliminate counterparty-like dependencies.\n\n### Oracle Risk\n\nDecentralised derivative platforms rely heavily on price oracles.\n\nAn incorrect price may cause:\n\nUnfair liquidation\n\nMispriced profit or loss\n\nExcessive borrowing\n\nProtocol insolvency\n\nManipulated settlement\n\nA robust oracle may combine several sources and use safeguards against stale or abnormal data.\n\nThe user should understand what happens if the primary oracle becomes unavailable.\n\n### Liquidity-Pool Counterparties\n\nSome decentralised perpetual protocols use a liquidity pool as the trader’s counterparty.\n\nWhen traders profit, value may be paid from the pool.\n\nWhen traders lose, the pool gains.\n\nLiquidity providers may earn fees while accepting exposure to trader profit, market imbalance and protocol design.\n\nIf traders collectively earn large profits, the pool can experience stress.\n\nThe protocol should have mechanisms for:\n\nPosition limits\n\nDynamic fees\n\nRisk management\n\nOracle protection\n\nPool solvency\n\n### Exchange and Contract Liquidity\n\nA futures contract may be liquid even when the underlying token is less liquid, or the opposite may occur.\n\nBefore trading, examine:\n\nBid-ask spread\n\nOrder-book depth\n\nDaily volume\n\nOpen interest\n\nPosition limits\n\nLiquidation depth\n\nIndex quality\n\nA large open-interest number does not guarantee that a large position can be closed efficiently during stress.\n\n### Market Impact\n\nA large derivative order can move the contract price and influence the underlying spot market through arbitrage.\n\nThis can create:\n\nSlippage\n\nFunding changes\n\nTemporary basis distortion\n\nLiquidation triggers\n\nThe trader should compare position size with available depth rather than only total daily volume.\n\nDaily volume can include the same capital trading repeatedly.\n\n### Fees\n\nDerivative costs may include:\n\nMaker fee\n\nTaker fee\n\nFunding\n\nSettlement fee\n\nLiquidation fee\n\nWithdrawal fee\n\nBorrowing cost\n\nSpread\n\nSlippage\n\nA high-frequency leveraged strategy may generate substantial turnover.\n\nA small gross trading advantage can disappear after costs.\n\nPerformance should be evaluated after every expense.\n\n### Derivative Tax and Record-Keeping\n\nDerivative transactions may create tax obligations that differ from spot transactions.\n\nRelevant records can include:\n\nContract\n\nEntry and exit\n\nPosition size\n\nRealised profit or loss\n\nFunding payments\n\nTrading fees\n\nSettlement\n\nCollateral transfers\n\nLiquidation\n\nRules vary across jurisdictions.\n\nA trader should maintain complete records rather than relying solely on the exchange to preserve them indefinitely.\n\n### Psychological Effects of Leverage\n\nLeverage changes behaviour as well as arithmetic.\n\nA trader may:\n\nMonitor price constantly\n\nClose profitable positions too early\n\nMove stops to avoid liquidation\n\nAdd margin impulsively\n\nTake revenge trades\n\nIncrease size after losses\n\nThe position may be mathematically within the risk limit but emotionally unmanageable.\n\nIf ordinary price movement creates panic, the effective exposure is too large.\n\n### Adding Margin\n\nAdding margin can move the liquidation price farther away.\n\nIt does not improve the underlying trade thesis.\n\nA trader may add margin because:\n\nThe strategy remains valid\n\nThe original position was undercollateralised\n\nA planned adjustment rule applies\n\nIt becomes dangerous when used repeatedly to avoid accepting invalidation.\n\nAdding margin exposes more capital to the same losing position.\n\nThe revised total risk must be calculated.','markdown',NULL,NULL,NULL,6,0,0,0,'',NULL,8,1785297600000 WHERE EXISTS (SELECT 1 FROM `courses` WHERE `id`='cognizen-crypto-mastery-foundations-production');
--> statement-breakpoint
INSERT OR IGNORE INTO `lessons` (`id`,`course_id`,`title`,`section_id`,`lesson_type`,`content`,`content_format`,`video_key`,`primary_asset_id`,`intro_asset_id`,`duration_minutes`,`is_preview`,`available_after_days`,`required_watch_percent`,`transcript`,`experience_json`,`position`,`updated_at`) SELECT 'cmf-module-3-07-lesson-09','cognizen-crypto-mastery-foundations-production','Averaging Into Leveraged Positions and Example: Cash-and-Carry','cmf-module-3-07','text','### Averaging Into Leveraged Positions\n\nAdding to a leveraged losing position increases notional exposure and may create a misleading improvement in average entry.\n\nThe liquidation price can move in either direction depending on margin and additional exposure.\n\nA planned staged entry should define:\n\nMaximum total notional\n\nMaximum margin\n\nNew liquidation level\n\nCombined stop\n\nTotal portfolio risk\n\nUnlimited averaging can produce rapid ruin.\n\n### Position Sizing for Futures\n\nThe appropriate position size is determined by the planned loss, not the leverage setting.\n\nSuppose:\n\nTrading capital: 40,000 units\n\nMaximum risk: 1 percent\n\nRisk allowance: 400 units\n\nEntry: 2,000\n\nStop: 1,950\n\nRisk per token: 50\n\nPosition quantity:\n\n400 ÷ 50 = 8 tokens\n\nNotional exposure:\n\n8 × 2,000 = 16,000 units\n\nThe position represents less than one-times leverage relative to the total account, even if the platform allows much more.\n\nThe trader may use margin efficiency without increasing the planned loss.\n\n### Effective Leverage\n\nEffective leverage should be measured against total account equity, not only the margin assigned to one position.\n\nSuppose:\n\nAccount equity: 20,000 units\n\nPosition notional: 60,000 units\n\nEffective leverage:\n\n60,000 ÷ 20,000 = 3 times\n\nEven if the exchange interface labels the position ten-times because of isolated margin, the broader account’s economic exposure is three times.\n\nBoth measures are useful, but they answer different questions.\n\n### Portfolio-Level Derivative Exposure\n\nSeveral derivative positions should be combined.\n\nA portfolio might contain:\n\nLong Bitcoin futures\n\nLong Ether perpetuals\n\nLong altcoin perpetuals\n\nShort volatility exposure\n\nEach position may appear acceptable individually.\n\nTogether, they may depend on one risk-on market outcome.\n\nPortfolio analysis should include:\n\nNet directional exposure\n\nGross exposure\n\nCorrelation\n\nCollateral concentration\n\nExchange concentration\n\nLiquidation scenarios\n\n### Gross and Net Exposure\n\nGross exposure is the sum of the absolute values of long and short positions.\n\nNet exposure is the difference between longs and shorts.\n\nSuppose:\n\nLong positions: 150,000 units\n\nShort positions: 100,000 units\n\nGross exposure:\n\n150,000 + 100,000 = 250,000 units\n\nNet exposure:\n\n150,000 − 100,000 = 50,000 units long\n\nA low net exposure can conceal high gross leverage and substantial basis or correlation risk.\n\n### Stress Testing a Futures Position\n\nBefore entering, model several adverse conditions.\n\nConsider what happens if:\n\nPrice moves against the position by five, ten or twenty percent\n\nVolatility doubles\n\nFunding becomes highly adverse\n\nThe exchange goes offline\n\nThe stablecoin collateral depegs\n\nStop execution slips\n\nThe position cannot be reduced\n\nCorrelated positions fail together\n\nThe objective is not to predict the exact crisis.\n\nIt is to determine whether the position remains survivable when normal assumptions fail.\n\n### Example: Leveraged Long\n\nSuppose:\n\nAccount equity: 10,000 units\n\nLong notional exposure: 50,000 units\n\nEffective leverage: 5 times\n\nEntry price: 50,000\n\nAsset declines by 5 percent\n\nApproximate position loss:\n\n50,000 × 5 percent = 2,500 units\n\nLoss relative to account equity:\n\n2,500 ÷ 10,000 × 100 = 25 percent\n\nA five-percent market decline produces an approximate twenty-five-percent account loss before fees and funding.\n\n### Example: Short Position\n\nSuppose a trader shorts two tokens at 1,500.\n\nPosition notional:\n\n2 × 1,500 = 3,000 units\n\nPrice rises to 1,650.\n\nLoss:\n\n2 × (1,650 − 1,500) = 300 units\n\nIf only 600 units of margin were assigned, the price movement creates a fifty-percent loss relative to that margin before other costs.\n\n### Example: Funding Cost\n\nSuppose:\n\nPerpetual long notional: 200,000 units\n\nFunding rate: 0.015 percent per interval\n\nThree funding intervals occur each day\n\nFunding per interval:\n\n200,000 × 0.015 percent = 30 units\n\nDaily funding:\n\n30 × 3 = 90 units\n\nIf the rate remained unchanged for thirty days:\n\n90 × 30 = 2,700 units\n\nThe actual rate will vary, but the example shows how recurring funding can become material.\n\n### Example: Hedge\n\nSuppose an investor owns 5 Bitcoin in spot.\n\nThey want to reduce exposure temporarily by forty percent.\n\nRequired short hedge:\n\n5 × 40 percent = 2 Bitcoin\n\nThe investor shorts futures representing 2 Bitcoin.\n\nNet exposure becomes approximately:\n\n5 − 2 = 3 Bitcoin long\n\nThe hedge result will differ slightly because of basis, fees and contract mechanics.\n\n### Example: Cash-and-Carry\n\nSuppose:\n\nSpot Bitcoin price: 50,000\n\nThree-month futures price: 52,000\n\nA participant buys one Bitcoin in spot and shorts one futures contract representing one Bitcoin.\n\nIf both converge to 51,000 at expiry:\n\nSpot gain:\n\n51,000 − 50,000 = 1,000\n\nFutures gain:\n\n52,000 − 51,000 = 1,000\n\nGross combined gain:\n\n2,000 units\n\nThe original basis was 2,000.\n\nThis excludes all fees, financing, margin and counterparty costs.','markdown',NULL,NULL,NULL,6,0,0,0,'',NULL,9,1785297600000 WHERE EXISTS (SELECT 1 FROM `courses` WHERE `id`='cognizen-crypto-mastery-foundations-production');
--> statement-breakpoint
INSERT OR IGNORE INTO `lessons` (`id`,`course_id`,`title`,`section_id`,`lesson_type`,`content`,`content_format`,`video_key`,`primary_asset_id`,`intro_asset_id`,`duration_minutes`,`is_preview`,`available_after_days`,`required_watch_percent`,`transcript`,`experience_json`,`position`,`updated_at`) SELECT 'cmf-module-3-07-lesson-10','cognizen-crypto-mastery-foundations-production','Example: Liquidation Risk and Common Misunderstandings','cmf-module-3-07','text','### Example: Liquidation Risk\n\nSuppose a trader uses twenty-times leverage.\n\nThe initial margin is approximately five percent of notional exposure.\n\nAn adverse move of less than five percent can threaten most of the margin, and liquidation may occur before the full five-percent movement because maintenance margin and fees must remain available.\n\nA normal daily fluctuation can therefore close the position even when the longer-term strategy remains correct.\n\n### Futures and Perpetual Trading Process\n\nBegin by identifying the exact contract and reading its specifications.\n\nDetermine whether the contract is dated or perpetual, linear or inverse, and which asset provides collateral.\n\nCalculate the intended notional exposure and effective leverage.\n\nDefine the entry, stop, target and maximum capital risk.\n\nEstimate trading fees, funding and likely slippage.\n\nConfirm margin mode, trigger-price reference and reduce-only exits.\n\nFinally, model the effect of a sharp adverse move and platform outage.\n\nThe trade should not proceed if any essential contract rule remains unclear.\n\n### Futures and Perpetual Checklist\n\nBefore entering a derivative position, ask:\n\nIs this a dated future or perpetual contract?\n\nWhat does one contract represent?\n\nIs the contract linear or inverse?\n\nWhich asset provides collateral?\n\nWhat is the total notional exposure?\n\nWhat is the effective leverage against total account equity?\n\nIs isolated or cross margin being used?\n\nWhat is the maintenance margin?\n\nWhat is the approximate liquidation price?\n\nWhich price triggers liquidation?\n\nWhich price triggers the stop order?\n\nWhat is the current spread and market depth?\n\nWhat trading fees apply?\n\nWhat funding rate applies?\n\nHow frequently is funding exchanged?\n\nCould funding reverse?\n\nWhat is the futures basis?\n\nDoes the contract expire?\n\nHow will the position be rolled or settled?\n\nWhat is the strategy: speculation, hedge or relative value?\n\nWhat underlying exposure is being hedged, if any?\n\nWhere is the analytical invalidation level?\n\nHow much capital can be lost?\n\nWhat position quantity follows from that risk?\n\nAre exit orders reduce-only?\n\nWhat happens if the exchange becomes unavailable?\n\nWhat happens if collateral loses value?\n\nHow does the position interact with other derivatives?\n\nWhat is the gross and net portfolio exposure?\n\nCan the position survive a realistic volatility shock?\n\n### Common Futures and Perpetual Mistakes\n\nA common mistake is focusing on the leverage multiple rather than the actual notional exposure and acceptable loss. Traders select ten-times or fifty-times leverage first and only later consider risk.\n\nAnother error is using liquidation as the stop. Liquidation exists to protect the platform, not to execute the trader’s strategy efficiently.\n\nSome participants ignore funding because each payment appears small. Over a large position and long holding period, recurring funding can materially reduce returns.\n\nOthers describe speculative short positions as hedges even though no corresponding long exposure exists.\n\nA further mistake is assuming that a market-neutral basis trade has no risk. Exchange insolvency, margin calls, stablecoin failure and execution mismatch remain possible.\n\nFinally, derivative traders may misunderstand the contract denomination. They calculate position size in tokens while the contract uses a fixed currency multiplier or inverse formula.\n\n### Common Misunderstandings\n\n#### “Leverage Multiplies Profit but My Stop Controls All Loss”\n\nStops can slip or fail, and liquidation may occur before the intended exit.\n\n#### “A Perpetual Contract Is the Same as Owning the Asset”\n\nIt creates price exposure without ordinary ownership or withdrawal rights.\n\n#### “A Futures Price Shows Where the Market Predicts Spot Will Be at Expiry”\n\nThe price also reflects financing, leverage, supply, demand and arbitrage.\n\n#### “Positive Funding Means Price Must Fall”\n\nCrowded long positioning can continue while funding remains positive.\n\n#### “Negative Funding Means Price Must Rise”\n\nStrong bearish trends can persist despite shorts paying funding.\n\n#### “A Hedge Cannot Lose Money”\n\nThe hedge itself may lose while protecting another position, and it introduces basis and counterparty risk.\n\n#### “Cross Margin Is Safer Because Liquidation Is Farther Away”\n\nMore account capital is available to absorb the loss.\n\n#### “Market Neutral Means Capital Safe”\n\nDirectional risk may be reduced while platform, margin, liquidity and basis risks remain.\n\n#### “The Mark Price Is the Price at Which I Can Trade”\n\nIt is a valuation reference. Actual execution occurs through the available market.\n\n#### “An Insurance Fund Guarantees Every Profitable Position”\n\nExtreme losses can still produce automatic deleveraging, socialised loss or platform failure.\n\n#### “High Open Interest Confirms the Direction”\n\nOpen interest measures outstanding exposure, not whether longs or shorts will ultimately succeed.','markdown',NULL,NULL,NULL,6,0,0,0,'',NULL,10,1785297600000 WHERE EXISTS (SELECT 1 FROM `courses` WHERE `id`='cognizen-crypto-mastery-foundations-production');
--> statement-breakpoint
INSERT OR IGNORE INTO `lessons` (`id`,`course_id`,`title`,`section_id`,`lesson_type`,`content`,`content_format`,`video_key`,`primary_asset_id`,`intro_asset_id`,`duration_minutes`,`is_preview`,`available_after_days`,`required_watch_percent`,`transcript`,`experience_json`,`position`,`updated_at`) SELECT 'cmf-module-3-07-lesson-11','cognizen-crypto-mastery-foundations-production','Module Summary and Key Takeaway','cmf-module-3-07','text','### Module Summary\n\nFutures and perpetual contracts create cryptocurrency price exposure without requiring direct ownership of the underlying asset.\n\nA dated futures contract expires and converges toward its settlement price.\n\nA perpetual contract has no expiry and uses funding payments to encourage alignment with spot markets.\n\nDerivative positions can be long or short.\n\nTheir financial importance is determined by notional exposure, not only the collateral deposited.\n\nLeverage magnifies gains and losses relative to account equity.\n\nInitial margin allows a position to open, while maintenance margin determines how much equity must remain to avoid liquidation.\n\nIsolated margin limits collateral to one position.\n\nCross margin allows broader account equity to support several positions, increasing both efficiency and contagion risk.\n\nFutures may trade above spot in contango or below spot in backwardation. The difference is known as basis.\n\nBasis, funding and convergence support strategies such as cash-and-carry and funding-rate arbitrage, but these strategies remain exposed to exchange, margin, liquidity and collateral risks.\n\nPerpetual funding may be positive or negative and is generally calculated on full notional exposure.\n\nMark price, index price and last traded price serve different functions. A trader must know which one controls liquidation and stop triggers.\n\nLiquidation is an exchange risk process, not a planned trading exit.\n\nInsurance funds, partial liquidation and automatic deleveraging are designed to manage deficits, but they cannot remove platform risk.\n\nFutures can be used for speculation, hedging and relative-value strategies.\n\nA hedge reduces an existing exposure. Without an underlying position to offset, the derivative is a directional trade.\n\nThe most important derivative calculation is not the maximum leverage available.\n\nIt is the amount the portfolio will lose if the position reaches its predefined invalidation point.\n\n### Key Takeaway\n\nFutures and perpetual contracts do not reduce market risk. They reshape and often magnify it.\n\nThe contract may offer efficient long, short or hedging exposure, but it also introduces margin, funding, liquidation and counterparty dependencies.\n\nBegin with the maximum loss the portfolio can tolerate. Then calculate the position and use only the leverage required to create that exposure.\n\nNever allow the leverage setting on an exchange to decide how much risk your capital should carry.\n\nThe next module is 3.8: Options Fundamentals and Strategic Uses.','markdown',NULL,NULL,NULL,3,0,0,0,'',NULL,11,1785297600000 WHERE EXISTS (SELECT 1 FROM `courses` WHERE `id`='cognizen-crypto-mastery-foundations-production');
--> statement-breakpoint
INSERT OR IGNORE INTO `lessons` (`id`,`course_id`,`title`,`section_id`,`lesson_type`,`content`,`content_format`,`video_key`,`primary_asset_id`,`intro_asset_id`,`duration_minutes`,`is_preview`,`available_after_days`,`required_watch_percent`,`transcript`,`experience_json`,`position`,`updated_at`) SELECT 'cmf-module-3-07-lesson-12','cognizen-crypto-mastery-foundations-production','Check your understanding','cmf-module-3-07','text','### Check your understanding\n\nAnswer these questions to self-assess your understanding before moving on.\n\n1. What is a derivative?\n\n2. How does a futures contract differ from spot ownership?\n\n3. What is the difference between a dated future and a perpetual contract?\n\n4. How does a long position generate profit?\n\n5. How does a short position generate profit?\n\n6. What is contract size?\n\n7. How is notional exposure calculated?\n\n8. How is leverage calculated?\n\n9. Why does leverage not improve the accuracy of a market signal?\n\n10. What is initial margin?\n\n11. What is maintenance margin?\n\n12. How does isolated margin differ from cross margin?\n\n13. What is portfolio margin?\n\n14. What is the difference between realised and unrealised profit?\n\n15. How is return on margin calculated?\n\n16. What is a linear contract?\n\n17. What is an inverse contract?\n\n18. How does coin-margined collateral change risk?\n\n19. What is futures expiry?\n\n20. What is futures basis?\n\n21. What is contango?\n\n22. What is backwardation?\n\n23. Why do futures converge toward spot at expiry?\n\n24. What is annualised basis?\n\n25. How does a cash-and-carry strategy work?\n\n26. What risks remain in a market-neutral basis trade?\n\n27. What is roll yield?\n\n28. What does the futures term structure show?\n\n29. What is a calendar spread?\n\n30. Why do perpetual contracts use funding?\n\n31. Who generally pays when funding is positive?\n\n32. Why is funding calculated on notional exposure?\n\n33. Can a predicted funding rate change?\n\n34. What is funding-rate arbitrage?\n\n35. What is the mark price?\n\n36. How does the index price differ from the last traded price?\n\n37. What is liquidation?\n\n38. Why should liquidation never be used as the planned stop?\n\n39. What is a bankruptcy price?\n\n40. What is the purpose of an insurance fund?\n\n41. What is automatic deleveraging?\n\n42. How does a liquidation cascade develop?\n\n43. What does open interest measure?\n\n44. How does open interest differ from volume?\n\n45. What may rising price and falling open interest suggest?\n\n46. What is a hedge ratio?\n\n47. How does a partial hedge differ from a full hedge?\n\n48. What is cross-hedging?\n\n49. What is basis risk?\n\n50. Why may selling an asset be simpler than hedging it?\n\n51. What is the difference between gross and net exposure?\n\n52. Why can a low net exposure still involve high risk?\n\n53. How should a futures position be sized?\n\n54. Why can adding margin be dangerous?\n\n55. What should be included in a derivative stress test?','markdown',NULL,NULL,NULL,6,0,0,0,'',NULL,12,1785297600000 WHERE EXISTS (SELECT 1 FROM `courses` WHERE `id`='cognizen-crypto-mastery-foundations-production');
--> statement-breakpoint
INSERT OR IGNORE INTO `course_sections` (`id`,`course_id`,`title`,`position`,`created_at`) SELECT 'cmf-module-3-08','cognizen-crypto-mastery-foundations-production','Module 3.8: Options Fundamentals and Strategic Uses',9,1785297600000 WHERE EXISTS (SELECT 1 FROM `courses` WHERE `id`='cognizen-crypto-mastery-foundations-production');
