INSERT OR IGNORE INTO `lessons` (`id`,`course_id`,`title`,`section_id`,`lesson_type`,`content`,`content_format`,`video_key`,`primary_asset_id`,`intro_asset_id`,`duration_minutes`,`is_preview`,`available_after_days`,`required_watch_percent`,`transcript`,`experience_json`,`position`,`updated_at`) SELECT 'cmf-module-3-09-lesson-01','cognizen-crypto-mastery-foundations-production','The Greeks as a Risk Language and Delta and Moneyness','cmf-module-3-09','text','### Learning Objectives\n\nBy the end of this module, you should understand how delta, gamma, theta, vega and rho interact to shape an option’s changing risk profile. You should be able to explain why an option position can gain or lose value even when the underlying asset barely moves, and why the same strategy may behave very differently as expiry approaches.\n\nYou should also be able to interpret implied-volatility skew and term structure, distinguish directional option trades from volatility trades and evaluate several advanced strategies, including vertical spreads, calendar spreads, butterflies, condors, risk reversals and ratio spreads.\n\nMost importantly, you should be able to analyse a multi-leg option position as one combined exposure, identify its maximum profit and loss where these are defined, and recognise the hidden risks that may remain behind apparently limited-risk or market-neutral structures.\n\n### Introduction\n\nAn option is not simply a leveraged bet on whether a cryptocurrency will rise or fall.\n\nIts value changes according to several forces operating simultaneously.\n\nA call option may increase because the underlying asset rises. It may also increase because implied volatility rises, even when the underlying price remains unchanged.\n\nThe same call may lose value because time passes, because implied volatility falls or because the market movement occurs too slowly.\n\nThis makes option trading fundamentally different from ordinary spot or futures trading.\n\nA spot investor focuses mainly on price direction.\n\nA futures trader must also consider leverage, margin, funding and liquidation.\n\nAn options trader must consider direction, movement size, time, volatility, strike selection, expiry, liquidity and the changing sensitivity of the option itself.\n\nThe option Greeks help organise these risks.\n\nThey do not predict what will happen. They estimate how an option may respond when one factor changes while the others are assumed to remain constant.\n\nIn real markets, several factors change together. Price moves, implied volatility adjusts and time passes continuously. The Greeks also change as the option’s moneyness and remaining life change.\n\nAdvanced option strategies combine several calls and puts to reshape these exposures.\n\nA spread may reduce premium cost but cap potential profit. A calendar spread may benefit from differences in time decay but become vulnerable to volatility changes. A short iron condor may earn premium in a stable market but suffer when price moves beyond its expected range.\n\nThe purpose of combining options is not to create risk-free profit.\n\nIt is to choose which risks to accept, which to reduce and which to transfer to another market participant.\n\n### The Greeks as a Risk Language\n\nThe Greeks are measures used to describe how an option’s value may respond to changes in market conditions.\n\nThe principal Greeks are:\n\n| Greek | Primary sensitivity |\n| --- | --- |\n| Delta | Change in the underlying asset’s price |\n| Gamma | Change in delta |\n| Theta | Passage of time |\n| Vega | Change in implied volatility |\n| Rho | Change in interest rates |\n\nThese measures are calculated using option-pricing models.\n\nThey are estimates based on assumptions rather than fixed contractual values.\n\nAn option’s payoff at expiry is defined by the contract. Its market value before expiry is determined by traders, liquidity and expectations. The Greeks help approximate that evolving market behaviour.\n\n### Delta in Greater Detail\n\nDelta estimates how much an option’s price may change for a small movement in the underlying asset, assuming other factors remain unchanged.\n\nA call normally has positive delta. It tends to gain when the underlying rises.\n\nA put normally has negative delta. It tends to gain when the underlying falls.\n\nSuppose a Bitcoin call has a delta of 0.60. If Bitcoin rises by 1,000 units, the option may gain approximately:\n\n0.60 × 1,000 = 600 units\n\nThis is an approximation before considering gamma, volatility and time.\n\nIf Bitcoin moves substantially, the delta itself changes.\n\n### Delta and Moneyness\n\nA deeply in-the-money call generally has a delta closer to one. Its price increasingly resembles direct ownership of the underlying asset.\n\nA far-out-of-the-money call generally has a delta closer to zero. Small movements in the underlying may have little effect because the strike remains distant.\n\nAn at-the-money call often has a delta near 0.50, although the exact figure depends on volatility, time and the pricing model.\n\nFor puts, the relationship is negative.\n\nA deeply in-the-money put may have a delta near negative one, while a far-out-of-the-money put may have a delta near zero.','markdown',NULL,NULL,NULL,6,0,0,0,'',NULL,1,1785297600000 WHERE EXISTS (SELECT 1 FROM `courses` WHERE `id`='cognizen-crypto-mastery-foundations-production');
--> statement-breakpoint
INSERT OR IGNORE INTO `lessons` (`id`,`course_id`,`title`,`section_id`,`lesson_type`,`content`,`content_format`,`video_key`,`primary_asset_id`,`intro_asset_id`,`duration_minutes`,`is_preview`,`available_after_days`,`required_watch_percent`,`transcript`,`experience_json`,`position`,`updated_at`) SELECT 'cmf-module-3-09-lesson-02','cognizen-crypto-mastery-foundations-production','Delta Exposure at Portfolio Level and Gamma Scalping','cmf-module-3-09','text','### Delta Exposure at Portfolio Level\n\nDelta can be used to estimate a portfolio’s directional exposure.\n\nSuppose a trader owns ten call contracts, each with:\n\nDelta: 0.40\n\nContract multiplier: 0.1 Bitcoin\n\nDelta exposure per contract:\n\n0.40 × 0.1 = 0.04 Bitcoin\n\nFor ten contracts:\n\n0.04 × 10 = 0.4 Bitcoin\n\nThe position initially behaves approximately like a long exposure of 0.4 Bitcoin.\n\nThis exposure is not constant.\n\nIf Bitcoin rises and the calls move further into the money, delta may increase. If Bitcoin falls, delta may decline.\n\n### Delta Is Not a Fixed Hedge Ratio\n\nA trader may hedge a call position by shorting an amount of the underlying equivalent to its current delta.\n\nIf the call portfolio has a delta of positive 0.4 Bitcoin, the trader may short approximately 0.4 Bitcoin.\n\nThe portfolio is then approximately delta neutral at that moment.\n\nOnce the underlying moves, gamma causes delta to change. The hedge becomes incomplete.\n\nMaintaining delta neutrality requires repeated adjustment.\n\nThis is called dynamic hedging.\n\nIt involves transaction costs, funding and execution risk.\n\n### Delta and Probability\n\nDelta is sometimes used as a rough proxy for the probability that an option will expire in the money.\n\nA call with delta of 0.25 may be described informally as having an approximately twenty-five-percent chance of finishing in the money.\n\nThis interpretation is limited.\n\nDelta is primarily a sensitivity measure. Any probability interpretation depends on the pricing model and assumptions regarding volatility and market returns.\n\nThe probability of finishing in the money is also different from the probability of earning a profit.\n\nAn option can finish slightly in the money while failing to recover the premium paid.\n\n### Gamma\n\nGamma measures the rate at which delta changes when the underlying asset moves.\n\nSuppose a call has:\n\nDelta: 0.50\n\nGamma: 0.04\n\nIf the underlying rises by one unit, delta may increase approximately from 0.50 to 0.54.\n\nIf the underlying falls by one unit, delta may decline approximately toward 0.46.\n\nThis relationship is approximate and most reliable for small movements.\n\nGamma explains why option exposure is curved rather than linear.\n\nA futures position generally maintains relatively constant directional sensitivity. An option’s sensitivity changes as the market moves.\n\n### Positive Gamma\n\nLong calls and long puts generally have positive gamma.\n\nFor a long call, delta increases as the underlying rises and decreases as the underlying falls.\n\nThis is favourable convexity.\n\nThe option becomes more responsive as the movement becomes profitable and less responsive as the movement becomes unfavourable.\n\nFor a long put, the absolute value of negative delta increases as the underlying falls.\n\nPositive gamma is valuable during large movement.\n\nThe buyer pays for this convexity through the premium and negative theta.\n\n### Negative Gamma\n\nShort options generally carry negative gamma.\n\nA short call becomes increasingly short as the underlying rises.\n\nA short put becomes increasingly long the underlying as it falls, creating growing losses.\n\nNegative gamma can appear comfortable during stable markets. Small movements allow time decay to benefit the seller.\n\nDuring a rapid move, the directional risk expands against the position.\n\nThis is why strategies that sell options can generate many small gains and occasional severe losses.\n\n### Gamma and Expiry\n\nGamma is often greatest for at-the-money options close to expiry.\n\nNear expiry, a small price movement can determine whether an option finishes with or without intrinsic value.\n\nDelta may therefore change extremely quickly.\n\nAn at-the-money call can move from low directional sensitivity to behaviour resembling the underlying asset over a short period.\n\nThis is known as gamma risk.\n\nShort-dated option positions require close attention because their exposure can change faster than the trader expects.\n\n### Gamma Scalping\n\nGamma scalping is a dynamic strategy used by a trader who owns positive gamma.\n\nThe trader may begin with a delta-neutral long option position.\n\nAs the underlying rises, delta becomes more positive. The trader sells some underlying exposure to return toward neutrality.\n\nAs the underlying falls, delta becomes less positive or more negative. The trader buys underlying exposure.\n\nThe process can result in repeatedly selling after rises and buying after declines.\n\nThis can generate trading gains when realised volatility is sufficiently high.\n\nHowever, those gains must overcome:\n\nOption premium\n\nTheta decay\n\nSpread\n\nFees\n\nFunding\n\nSlippage\n\nImperfect hedge adjustments\n\nGamma scalping is not automatic profit from market movement.','markdown',NULL,NULL,NULL,6,0,0,0,'',NULL,2,1785297600000 WHERE EXISTS (SELECT 1 FROM `courses` WHERE `id`='cognizen-crypto-mastery-foundations-production');
--> statement-breakpoint
INSERT OR IGNORE INTO `lessons` (`id`,`course_id`,`title`,`section_id`,`lesson_type`,`content`,`content_format`,`video_key`,`primary_asset_id`,`intro_asset_id`,`duration_minutes`,`is_preview`,`available_after_days`,`required_watch_percent`,`transcript`,`experience_json`,`position`,`updated_at`) SELECT 'cmf-module-3-09-lesson-03','cognizen-crypto-mastery-foundations-production','Theta and The Greeks Interact','cmf-module-3-09','text','### Theta\n\nTheta estimates the effect of time passing on option value.\n\nFor a long option, theta is generally negative.\n\nSuppose an option has theta of negative five units per day. If all other conditions remain unchanged, the option may lose approximately five units of value as one day passes.\n\nIn practice, other conditions never remain perfectly constant.\n\nThe underlying moves and implied volatility changes.\n\nTheta provides a way to estimate the cost of waiting.\n\n### Time Decay Is Not Linear\n\nTime value does not normally decline at the same rate throughout the option’s life.\n\nA long-dated option may lose time value relatively gradually.\n\nAs expiry approaches, decay often accelerates, particularly for options near the current market price.\n\nFar-out-of-the-money options may also lose value rapidly when the probability of reaching the strike becomes small.\n\nA trader cannot assume that an option with half its original time remaining should retain half its original time value.\n\n### Theta and Option Buyers\n\nAn option buyer faces a timing requirement.\n\nIt is not enough for the underlying eventually to move in the predicted direction.\n\nThe movement must occur before too much time value disappears.\n\nA trader may buy a call based on a valid three-month market thesis but choose an option expiring in two weeks.\n\nThe thesis can ultimately prove correct while the option expires without value.\n\nExpiry selection should match the expected timing of the market view.\n\n### Theta and Option Sellers\n\nOption sellers generally benefit from time decay.\n\nIf the market remains within a suitable range, the option’s extrinsic value declines and the seller may buy it back more cheaply or allow it to expire.\n\nThis apparent consistency can create excessive confidence.\n\nThe seller is receiving theta because they carry negative gamma and often negative vega.\n\nA large movement or volatility increase can overwhelm many days of accumulated time decay.\n\n### Vega\n\nVega estimates sensitivity to changes in implied volatility.\n\nSuppose an option has vega of twenty.\n\nIf implied volatility rises by one percentage point, the option may gain approximately twenty units, assuming other factors remain constant.\n\nIf implied volatility falls by one point, the option may lose approximately twenty units.\n\nLong options generally have positive vega.\n\nShort options generally have negative vega.\n\nVega is particularly important for longer-dated options because more remaining time makes future uncertainty more valuable.\n\n### Vega and Maturity\n\nLonger-dated options generally carry greater vega than short-dated options.\n\nAn increase in expected long-term volatility can therefore have a larger effect on a six-month option than on an option expiring tomorrow.\n\nShort-dated options can still react strongly to volatility changes around immediate events.\n\nTheir absolute vega may be lower, but their premium can change dramatically in percentage terms.\n\n### Vega and Event Risk\n\nImplied volatility often increases before an uncertain event.\n\nExamples include a regulatory ruling, network upgrade, legal decision or major economic announcement.\n\nA trader who buys an option early may benefit from the rise in implied volatility even before the event.\n\nAfter the event, uncertainty decreases and implied volatility may collapse.\n\nThe option can then lose vega-related value immediately.\n\nThis volatility crush can affect both calls and puts.\n\n### Rho\n\nRho measures an option’s sensitivity to interest rates.\n\nFor many short-dated cryptocurrency options, rho is less influential than delta, gamma, theta and vega.\n\nIt becomes more relevant for longer-dated options.\n\nCryptocurrency option pricing may also be influenced by factors that resemble interest rates, including:\n\nStablecoin lending rates\n\nFutures basis\n\nFunding costs\n\nCollateral yield\n\nBorrowing costs\n\nTraditional option models may not capture every digital asset financing condition perfectly.\n\n### Higher-Order Greeks\n\nAdvanced option analysis may use additional measures.\n\nVanna describes how delta changes as implied volatility changes, or how vega changes as the underlying moves.\n\nVolga, sometimes called vomma, describes how vega changes as implied volatility changes.\n\nCharm estimates how delta changes as time passes.\n\nThese measures become relevant in complex volatility portfolios and dealer hedging.\n\nFor most individual participants, understanding the principal Greeks and their interaction is more important than calculating every higher-order measure.\n\n### The Greeks Interact\n\nThe Greeks should not be evaluated separately as though only one factor changes.\n\nSuppose a trader owns an at-the-money call before an important event.\n\nAfter the event:\n\nThe underlying rises\n\nDelta produces a gain\n\nGamma increases directional sensitivity\n\nTime has passed, creating theta loss\n\nImplied volatility falls, creating vega loss\n\nThe final result depends on the combined effect.\n\nThe call can lose despite a favourable underlying move when the rise is too small to offset theta and volatility crush.','markdown',NULL,NULL,NULL,6,0,0,0,'',NULL,3,1785297600000 WHERE EXISTS (SELECT 1 FROM `courses` WHERE `id`='cognizen-crypto-mastery-foundations-production');
--> statement-breakpoint
INSERT OR IGNORE INTO `lessons` (`id`,`course_id`,`title`,`section_id`,`lesson_type`,`content`,`content_format`,`video_key`,`primary_asset_id`,`intro_asset_id`,`duration_minutes`,`is_preview`,`available_after_days`,`required_watch_percent`,`transcript`,`experience_json`,`position`,`updated_at`) SELECT 'cmf-module-3-09-lesson-04','cognizen-crypto-mastery-foundations-production','Option Exposure Changes With Price and Vertical Spreads Revisited','cmf-module-3-09','text','### Option Exposure Changes With Price\n\nConsider an out-of-the-money call.\n\nBefore a rally, it may have low delta and limited directional sensitivity.\n\nAs the underlying rises toward the strike, delta and gamma become more important.\n\nIf the option moves deeply into the money, delta approaches one and the position behaves more like the underlying asset.\n\nThe option’s risk profile evolves throughout the trade.\n\nA strategy should not be managed according to the Greeks that existed only at entry.\n\n### Implied Volatility Surface\n\nImplied volatility differs across strikes and expiry dates.\n\nThe complete relationship is called the implied volatility surface.\n\nOne dimension reflects strike or moneyness.\n\nAnother reflects time to expiry.\n\nThe surface reveals how the market prices different forms of uncertainty.\n\nFor example, far-downside puts may carry high implied volatility because investors are willing to pay more for crash protection.\n\nFar-upside calls may also become expensive during speculative periods.\n\nThe surface changes continuously as demand, supply and market risk change.\n\n### Volatility Skew\n\nSkew describes how implied volatility changes across strikes for the same expiry.\n\nA downside skew means lower-strike puts trade at higher implied volatility than comparable calls.\n\nThis is common when participants fear large declines.\n\nAn upside call skew may develop when demand for speculative upside is unusually strong.\n\nSkew affects strategy pricing.\n\nA protective put may be expensive because many investors seek the same protection.\n\nA risk reversal may provide insight into whether calls or puts are relatively more expensive.\n\n### Risk Reversal\n\nA risk reversal combines a call and a put with the same expiry, commonly using out-of-the-money strikes.\n\nA bullish risk reversal may involve:\n\nBuying an out-of-the-money call\n\nSelling an out-of-the-money put\n\nThe premium received from the put helps finance the call.\n\nThe position creates bullish exposure but accepts significant downside obligation.\n\nIf the underlying falls below the put strike, losses can become substantial.\n\nA bearish risk reversal reverses the structure.\n\nRisk reversals are also used as market indicators. The difference in implied volatility between comparable calls and puts can show whether the market is paying more for upside or downside exposure.\n\n### Volatility Term Structure\n\nThe term structure compares implied volatility across expiries.\n\nSuppose one-week options have implied volatility of 120 percent while three-month options have implied volatility of 80 percent.\n\nThe market may be pricing a major immediate event followed by lower expected uncertainty.\n\nIf longer expiries have higher volatility, the market may be pricing persistent future uncertainty.\n\nTerm structure is important for calendar spreads because those strategies trade the relative value of options with different maturities.\n\n### Forward Volatility\n\nForward volatility is the volatility implied for a future period between two option expiries.\n\nFor example, the market prices one-month and three-month options. From those values, a model can estimate the volatility implied for the period after the first month and before the third month.\n\nThis is advanced and model dependent.\n\nThe key concept is that a longer-dated volatility number contains expectations for several future periods rather than one uniform rate.\n\n### Volatility Risk Premium\n\nOptions often price implied volatility above the volatility that is later realised.\n\nOne reason is that option buyers are willing to pay for insurance and convexity.\n\nThe difference can create a volatility risk premium for option sellers.\n\nThis does not mean selling options is automatically profitable.\n\nThe seller earns a premium for carrying:\n\nTail risk\n\nNegative gamma\n\nMargin risk\n\nLiquidity risk\n\nModel uncertainty\n\nOne severe event can erase a long period of premium income.\n\n### Long Volatility\n\nA long-volatility position benefits when market movement or implied volatility exceeds expectations.\n\nExamples include:\n\nLong straddle\n\nLong strangle\n\nLong options combined with dynamic hedging\n\nCertain calendar structures\n\nLong-volatility positions generally pay theta.\n\nThey require enough movement, volatility expansion or both to compensate for the premium.\n\n### Short Volatility\n\nA short-volatility position benefits when movement is smaller than the market priced or when implied volatility declines.\n\nExamples include:\n\nShort straddle\n\nShort strangle\n\nIron condor\n\nCovered call\n\nCash-secured put\n\nOption-selling vault\n\nShort-volatility positions often earn small, regular gains.\n\nThey can suffer sudden losses during large movement.\n\nThe risk is especially severe when leverage or naked options are involved.\n\n### Vertical Spreads Revisited\n\nA vertical spread combines options with the same expiry and different strikes.\n\nA debit spread requires a net premium payment.\n\nA credit spread produces a net premium receipt.\n\nThe second option limits both risk and reward.\n\nVertical spreads can reduce the effect of:\n\nHigh option premium\n\nTime decay\n\nImplied volatility\n\nThey also cap the strategy’s potential benefit from an extreme move.','markdown',NULL,NULL,NULL,6,0,0,0,'',NULL,4,1785297600000 WHERE EXISTS (SELECT 1 FROM `courses` WHERE `id`='cognizen-crypto-mastery-foundations-production');
--> statement-breakpoint
INSERT OR IGNORE INTO `lessons` (`id`,`course_id`,`title`,`section_id`,`lesson_type`,`content`,`content_format`,`video_key`,`primary_asset_id`,`intro_asset_id`,`duration_minutes`,`is_preview`,`available_after_days`,`required_watch_percent`,`transcript`,`experience_json`,`position`,`updated_at`) SELECT 'cmf-module-3-09-lesson-05','cognizen-crypto-mastery-foundations-production','Bull Put Spread and Iron Butterfly','cmf-module-3-09','text','### Bull Put Spread\n\nA bull put spread is a bullish credit strategy.\n\nIt commonly involves:\n\nSelling a higher-strike put\n\nBuying a lower-strike put\n\nSame expiry\n\nSuppose:\n\nSell 100-strike put for 8\n\nBuy 85-strike put for 3\n\nNet credit:\n\n8 − 3 = 5\n\nStrike difference:\n\n100 − 85 = 15\n\nMaximum profit:\n\n5\n\nMaximum loss:\n\n15 − 5 = 10\n\nThe maximum profit occurs when the underlying remains at or above 100 at expiry.\n\nThe purchased lower-strike put limits the downside compared with a naked short put.\n\n### Bear Call Spread\n\nA bear call spread is a bearish or neutral credit strategy.\n\nIt commonly involves:\n\nSelling a lower-strike call\n\nBuying a higher-strike call\n\nSuppose:\n\nSell 100-strike call for 9\n\nBuy 115-strike call for 4\n\nNet credit:\n\n9 − 4 = 5\n\nMaximum profit is five.\n\nMaximum loss:\n\n15 strike width − 5 credit = 10\n\nThe strategy profits fully when the underlying remains at or below the short-call strike at expiry.\n\n### Credit Spreads Are Not Automatically Conservative\n\nA defined maximum loss makes a credit spread easier to size than a naked option.\n\nHowever, the maximum loss may be several times larger than the premium received.\n\nA strategy earning one unit while risking four units requires a sufficiently high success rate.\n\nFrequent small gains can create complacency.\n\nThe position should be assessed through expectancy rather than the probability of keeping the credit.\n\n### Calendar Spreads\n\nA calendar spread uses options with the same or similar strike but different expiry dates.\n\nA long calendar commonly involves:\n\nSelling a near-term option\n\nBuying a longer-term option\n\nThe strategy may benefit when the near-term option decays faster than the longer-dated option.\n\nIt may also benefit from higher volatility in the longer-dated contract.\n\nThe position is sensitive to:\n\nUnderlying price near the strike\n\nRelative implied volatilities\n\nTime decay\n\nMovement before the short option expires\n\nCalendar spreads are not purely time-decay trades. Their risk depends strongly on volatility term structure.\n\n### Calendar Spread Example\n\nSuppose an asset trades near 100.\n\nA trader:\n\nSells a one-month 100-strike call\n\nBuys a three-month 100-strike call\n\nIf the underlying remains near 100 when the short call expires, the short option may lose most of its time value while the longer option retains substantial value.\n\nIf the underlying moves far away from 100, the position may perform differently.\n\nA strong rise can create assignment or directional exposure. A sharp fall can reduce the value of both calls.\n\n### Diagonal Spreads\n\nA diagonal spread uses different strikes and different expiries.\n\nFor example:\n\nBuy a longer-dated lower-strike call\n\nSell a shorter-dated higher-strike call\n\nThis combines characteristics of a vertical spread and calendar spread.\n\nA diagonal can be used to create directional exposure while selling shorter-term time value.\n\nIt introduces more variables and requires active management when the short option approaches expiry.\n\n### Poor Man’s Covered Call\n\nA strategy sometimes described as a poor man’s covered call uses a deep-in-the-money, longer-dated call instead of holding the underlying asset.\n\nThe trader then sells shorter-dated calls against it.\n\nThe long call acts as a partial replacement for the asset.\n\nThe strategy requires less capital than ordinary spot ownership.\n\nIt introduces:\n\nExpiry risk\n\nLong-call time decay\n\nDelta mismatch\n\nVolatility sensitivity\n\nAssignment and roll risk\n\nThe long call may not offset the short call perfectly.\n\n### Butterfly Spread\n\nA standard long call butterfly uses three strikes.\n\nA typical structure is:\n\nBuy one lower-strike call\n\nSell two middle-strike calls\n\nBuy one higher-strike call\n\nSame expiry\n\nEqual strike spacing\n\nSuppose the strikes are 90, 100 and 110.\n\nThe strategy generally benefits when the underlying finishes near 100 at expiry.\n\nMaximum loss is limited to the net premium paid.\n\nMaximum profit occurs near the middle strike.\n\nThe butterfly expresses a precise view that price will finish near a selected level.\n\n### Butterfly Characteristics\n\nA long butterfly is usually:\n\nLimited risk\n\nLimited reward\n\nSensitive to the final price location\n\nOften short volatility around the centre\n\nVulnerable when price moves far beyond the wings\n\nAlthough the debit may be small, the probability of achieving the maximum payoff can also be low.\n\nThe attractive payoff diagram at the middle strike should not be confused with a high probability of earning that payoff.\n\n### Iron Butterfly\n\nAn iron butterfly uses both calls and puts.\n\nA common short iron butterfly involves:\n\nSelling an at-the-money call\n\nSelling an at-the-money put\n\nBuying an out-of-the-money call\n\nBuying an out-of-the-money put\n\nIt receives a net credit.\n\nMaximum profit occurs when the underlying finishes near the middle strike.\n\nThe protective wings limit maximum loss.\n\nThe position is generally short volatility and benefits from time decay.\n\nA large move in either direction creates losses.','markdown',NULL,NULL,NULL,6,0,0,0,'',NULL,5,1785297600000 WHERE EXISTS (SELECT 1 FROM `courses` WHERE `id`='cognizen-crypto-mastery-foundations-production');
--> statement-breakpoint
INSERT OR IGNORE INTO `lessons` (`id`,`course_id`,`title`,`section_id`,`lesson_type`,`content`,`content_format`,`video_key`,`primary_asset_id`,`intro_asset_id`,`duration_minutes`,`is_preview`,`available_after_days`,`required_watch_percent`,`transcript`,`experience_json`,`position`,`updated_at`) SELECT 'cmf-module-3-09-lesson-06','cognizen-crypto-mastery-foundations-production','Condor Spread and Dispersion Concepts','cmf-module-3-09','text','### Condor Spread\n\nA condor uses four strikes.\n\nA long condor seeks a payoff within a defined area while limiting risk.\n\nAn iron condor is more commonly used as a premium-selling strategy.\n\nA short iron condor generally combines:\n\nBull put spread below the market\n\nBear call spread above the market\n\nThe strategy profits when the underlying remains between the short strikes at expiry.\n\nMaximum profit is the net credit.\n\nMaximum loss is the width of one spread minus the credit.\n\n### Iron Condor Example\n\nSuppose the underlying trades near 100.\n\nThe trader:\n\nBuys 80 put\n\nSells 90 put\n\nSells 110 call\n\nBuys 120 call\n\nAssume the net credit is four units.\n\nEach wing is ten units wide.\n\nMaximum profit:\n\n4 units\n\nMaximum loss:\n\n10 − 4 = 6 units\n\nThe strategy earns the full credit if the underlying finishes between 90 and 110.\n\nIt loses when price moves sufficiently beyond either side.\n\n### Iron Condor Risk\n\nIron condors are popular because they offer defined risk and can profit from time decay.\n\nThey remain short volatility.\n\nA sudden large movement can cause the spread to lose rapidly.\n\nManaging the position may require:\n\nClosing one side\n\nRolling strikes\n\nReducing exposure\n\nAccepting the predefined loss\n\nAdjustments do not remove loss. They realise or transfer risk into a new structure.\n\n### Ratio Spreads\n\nA ratio spread uses unequal numbers of bought and sold options.\n\nFor example, a call ratio spread may involve:\n\nBuying one call\n\nSelling two higher-strike calls\n\nThe premium can be low or even produce a credit.\n\nThe strategy may profit if the underlying rises moderately toward the short strikes.\n\nIf the asset rises far beyond them, the extra uncovered short call can create very large or unlimited loss.\n\nRatio spreads can appear attractive because of low initial cost.\n\nTheir tail exposure must be understood fully.\n\n### Backspreads\n\nA backspread generally buys more options than it sells.\n\nA call backspread may involve:\n\nSelling one lower-strike call\n\nBuying two higher-strike calls\n\nThe position can benefit from a large upward move and may have limited risk in some lower-price scenarios.\n\nIt is often long gamma and long volatility.\n\nThe position may lose when price finishes in an unfavourable middle area.\n\nBackspreads are event or tail-movement strategies rather than ordinary bullish calls.\n\n### Broken-Wing Butterfly\n\nA broken-wing butterfly uses unequal distances between strikes.\n\nThis changes the payoff distribution and may reduce or eliminate premium on one side.\n\nThe strategy can be designed to favour one direction.\n\nIts asymmetry makes the risk less intuitive than a standard butterfly.\n\nThe trader should calculate the payoff at prices below, between and above every strike.\n\n### Box Spread\n\nA box spread combines a bull call spread and bear put spread using the same strikes and expiry.\n\nUnder ideal pricing, it creates a fixed future payoff.\n\nThe difference between the box price and future payoff reflects financing conditions.\n\nIn practice, risks include:\n\nExecution mismatch\n\nFees\n\nSettlement\n\nAssignment\n\nPlatform default\n\nPoor liquidity\n\nTax treatment\n\nA theoretical arbitrage is not risk free when implemented through a fallible platform.\n\n### Synthetic Long and Synthetic Short\n\nA synthetic long position combines:\n\nLong call\n\nShort put\n\nSame strike and expiry\n\nThe payoff resembles a long futures contract.\n\nA synthetic short combines:\n\nLong put\n\nShort call\n\nThe payoff resembles a short futures contract.\n\nThese structures can be useful when option pricing differs from futures.\n\nThey also create short-option margin and assignment risk.\n\nThe option labels do not make the exposure limited risk.\n\n### Put-Call Parity\n\nPut-call parity describes a theoretical relationship between calls, puts, the underlying asset and financing for options with the same strike and expiry.\n\nA simplified conceptual form is:\n\nCall − Put ≈ Underlying − Present value of strike\n\nThe exact relationship depends on settlement, interest rates and contract design.\n\nIf prices deviate significantly, arbitrage traders may trade combinations to restore alignment.\n\nIn cryptocurrency markets, platform risk, collateral yield, borrowing limits and fragmented liquidity can prevent perfect parity.\n\n### Conversion and Reversal Strategies\n\nA conversion generally combines:\n\nLong underlying\n\nLong put\n\nShort call\n\nUsing the same strike and expiry, this can create a fixed-like payoff similar to lending.\n\nA reversal uses the opposite positions.\n\nThese strategies may exploit option mispricing relative to the underlying.\n\nThey remain exposed to:\n\nBorrowing\n\nCustody\n\nSettlement\n\nMargin\n\nExchange failure\n\nExecution mismatch\n\nTheoretical pricing relationships do not remove operational risk.\n\n### Dispersion Concepts\n\nDispersion trading compares options on an index with options on its components.\n\nThe strategy may express a view about correlation rather than general market volatility.\n\nIn digital assets, a trader might compare volatility of a broad cryptocurrency index with volatility in individual assets.\n\nThis is highly advanced and faces challenges including:\n\nWeak index products\n\nUneven liquidity\n\nChanging correlations\n\nToken-specific events\n\nRebalancing\n\nPlatform fragmentation\n\nThe key lesson is that option strategies can trade relationships such as correlation, not only price direction.','markdown',NULL,NULL,NULL,6,0,0,0,'',NULL,6,1785297600000 WHERE EXISTS (SELECT 1 FROM `courses` WHERE `id`='cognizen-crypto-mastery-foundations-production');
--> statement-breakpoint
INSERT OR IGNORE INTO `lessons` (`id`,`course_id`,`title`,`section_id`,`lesson_type`,`content`,`content_format`,`video_key`,`primary_asset_id`,`intro_asset_id`,`duration_minutes`,`is_preview`,`available_after_days`,`required_watch_percent`,`transcript`,`experience_json`,`position`,`updated_at`) SELECT 'cmf-module-3-09-lesson-07','cognizen-crypto-mastery-foundations-production','Correlation and Options and Margin and Multi-Leg Positions','cmf-module-3-09','text','### Correlation and Options\n\nPortfolio volatility depends on both individual asset volatility and correlation.\n\nWhen correlations rise, a diversified portfolio can experience larger combined movement.\n\nIndex option pricing may reflect expected correlation among components.\n\nDuring crises, correlations often increase.\n\nAn option hedge designed using ordinary correlation may provide insufficient protection when all assets decline together.\n\n### Volatility Trading Without Direction\n\nA trader can attempt to isolate volatility by hedging delta.\n\nFor example, a long straddle may be adjusted regularly to remain approximately delta neutral.\n\nThe trader then seeks to benefit from realised movement relative to option cost.\n\nThis does not remove all directional risk.\n\nDelta changes continuously, hedges occur with delay and markets can gap.\n\nThe position also remains exposed to theta, vega, liquidity and model error.\n\n### Volatility Carry\n\nA short-volatility trader may attempt to collect the difference between implied and realised volatility.\n\nThe trade may produce regular gains when markets remain stable.\n\nThe risk appears when realised volatility suddenly exceeds expectations.\n\nA robust volatility-carry strategy should account for:\n\nTail hedges\n\nPosition limits\n\nVolatility regime\n\nLiquidity\n\nMargin expansion\n\nCorrelation shock\n\nSelling volatility without a tail-risk framework can create hidden leverage.\n\n### Volatility Regime Selection\n\nOption strategy should match the volatility environment.\n\nWhen implied volatility is low relative to expected future movement, long-volatility structures may be attractive.\n\nWhen implied volatility is very high and the participant believes actual movement will be smaller, defined-risk short-volatility structures may be considered.\n\nThe labels “high” and “low” must be relative to:\n\nThe asset’s history\n\nUpcoming events\n\nRealised volatility\n\nOther expiries\n\nOther strikes\n\nLow implied volatility can fall further. High implied volatility can become much higher.\n\n### Direction and Volatility Together\n\nAn option thesis should specify both direction and volatility where relevant.\n\nA trader can be:\n\nBullish and long volatility\n\nBullish and short volatility\n\nBearish and long volatility\n\nBearish and short volatility\n\nDirection neutral and long volatility\n\nDirection neutral and short volatility\n\nA long call is bullish and generally long volatility.\n\nA bull put spread is bullish but generally short volatility.\n\nThe same directional opinion can therefore be expressed through very different risk profiles.\n\n### Strategy Selection Example\n\nSuppose a trader expects a moderate rise and believes implied volatility is expensive.\n\nBuying a call may overpay for volatility.\n\nA bull call spread reduces the premium and vega exposure while capping upside.\n\nA bull put spread earns premium but accepts downside risk.\n\nA covered call may suit an investor already holding the asset but caps gains.\n\nThe “best” strategy depends on more than bullishness.\n\nIt depends on expected magnitude, volatility, time and loss tolerance.\n\n### Options Around Breakouts\n\nA trader expecting a breakout may buy a straddle or strangle.\n\nThe position can benefit from movement in either direction.\n\nHowever, implied volatility often rises before a widely observed breakout.\n\nThe options may already price a substantial move.\n\nIf the eventual breakout is smaller than expected, both options can lose value.\n\nA cheaper alternative may use a directional spread after confirmation, accepting the risk of entering later.\n\n### Options Around Mean Reversion\n\nA trader expecting price to remain inside a range may consider a defined-risk short-volatility strategy such as an iron condor.\n\nThe strategy earns premium while price remains between the short strikes.\n\nIf the range breaks, losses can develop quickly.\n\nThe option structure should be closed or managed according to the regime invalidation rather than held merely because time decay remains positive.\n\n### Options for Trend Following\n\nA long-dated call can provide trend exposure with premium-defined risk.\n\nA call spread can reduce cost while capping profit.\n\nA trader can also use a trailing exit on the option or underlying asset.\n\nThe expiry must provide enough time for the trend to develop.\n\nRepeatedly buying short-dated calls within a long-term trend can produce large cumulative theta losses.\n\n### Options for Hedging Leveraged Positions\n\nA futures trader may buy an option to limit extreme loss.\n\nFor example, a leveraged long futures position can be paired with a put.\n\nThe put may gain during a severe decline.\n\nHowever, the futures position can still be liquidated before the option hedge is monetised unless margin and execution are managed correctly.\n\nThe hedge must be sized, accessible and held on a platform capable of honouring it.\n\n### Margin and Multi-Leg Positions\n\nPlatforms may recognise the offsetting risk of multi-leg strategies and reduce margin requirements.\n\nA call spread requires less margin than a naked short call because the purchased call limits maximum loss.\n\nMargin treatment depends on:\n\nPlatform model\n\nContract settlement\n\nStrike relationship\n\nExpiry\n\nPortfolio margin rules\n\nA platform error, leg mismatch or early assignment can temporarily remove the hedge.\n\nThe trader should understand the risk of each leg independently and as a combination.','markdown',NULL,NULL,NULL,6,0,0,0,'',NULL,7,1785297600000 WHERE EXISTS (SELECT 1 FROM `courses` WHERE `id`='cognizen-crypto-mastery-foundations-production');
--> statement-breakpoint
INSERT OR IGNORE INTO `lessons` (`id`,`course_id`,`title`,`section_id`,`lesson_type`,`content`,`content_format`,`video_key`,`primary_asset_id`,`intro_asset_id`,`duration_minutes`,`is_preview`,`available_after_days`,`required_watch_percent`,`transcript`,`experience_json`,`position`,`updated_at`) SELECT 'cmf-module-3-09-lesson-08','cognizen-crypto-mastery-foundations-production','Legging Risk and Scenario Grid','cmf-module-3-09','text','### Legging Risk\n\nLegging risk occurs when the components of a multi-leg strategy are not executed simultaneously.\n\nSuppose a trader intends to create a call spread.\n\nThey buy the first call. Before selling the second call, the market moves and the premium changes.\n\nThe final spread cost becomes worse than expected.\n\nOn exit, one leg may fill while the other remains open.\n\nThe trader is temporarily exposed to a different risk profile.\n\nComplex orders should use combined spread execution where sufficiently liquid.\n\n### Assignment Risk in Multi-Leg Strategies\n\nAmerican-style short options can be assigned before expiry.\n\nIf one leg of a spread is assigned while the protective leg remains open, the trader may acquire an unintended underlying or short position.\n\nEuropean-style cash-settled contracts reduce early-assignment complexity but retain settlement risk.\n\nThe participant must understand whether assignment is possible and how the platform handles it.\n\n### Liquidity Across Legs\n\nA strategy is only as executable as its least liquid leg.\n\nA four-leg iron condor may show an attractive theoretical payoff.\n\nIf one wing has a very wide spread, entry and exit costs may consume much of the premium.\n\nThe participant should examine:\n\nBid and ask for each leg\n\nCombined spread quote\n\nAvailable quantity\n\nOpen interest\n\nExpected slippage\n\nComplexity can multiply trading costs.\n\n### Closing Before Expiry\n\nMulti-leg positions do not need to be held until expiry.\n\nA trader may close when:\n\nA percentage of maximum profit is achieved\n\nImplied volatility changes\n\nThe market regime changes\n\nRisk increases near expiry\n\nThe original thesis is invalidated\n\nLiquidity remains adequate\n\nWaiting for the final small portion of potential profit can expose the position to disproportionate gamma risk.\n\n### Managing Short-Volatility Positions\n\nA short-volatility position can be managed by:\n\nClosing at a predefined profit\n\nClosing after a loss threshold\n\nReducing size when volatility rises\n\nBuying additional protection\n\nRolling the threatened side\n\nClosing the entire structure\n\nRolling a losing option does not remove the loss.\n\nIt realises the existing position and creates a new one.\n\nThe new structure should be evaluated independently.\n\n### Rolling Spreads\n\nA spread may be rolled to:\n\nLater expiry\n\nDifferent strikes\n\nBoth\n\nA credit may be received during the roll, but the trader may also widen the period of risk or increase maximum loss.\n\nThe relevant calculation is not whether the roll produces a credit.\n\nIt is the combined realised loss, new exposure and remaining maximum risk.\n\n### Early Profit-Taking\n\nShort premium strategies often close after earning part of the maximum possible credit.\n\nFor example, a trader may close after capturing half the premium.\n\nThis reduces the time during which the strategy remains exposed to a sudden adverse move.\n\nIt also gives up remaining theta income.\n\nThe rule should be based on tested strategy behaviour rather than an arbitrary desire to avoid discomfort.\n\n### Stop-Losses on Spreads\n\nSpread prices may have wide or unstable quotes.\n\nA stop based on the spread’s displayed price can trigger on poor market data.\n\nSome traders manage the position according to:\n\nUnderlying price\n\nShort strike\n\nDelta\n\nMaximum loss percentage\n\nMarket regime\n\nImplied volatility\n\nThe maximum possible loss should remain acceptable even if the planned exit cannot be executed at the desired price.\n\n### Pin and Expiry Risk\n\nAs expiry approaches, a multi-leg position can change rapidly when the underlying trades near one of its strikes.\n\nA small movement may cause:\n\nDelta shift\n\nAssignment\n\nExercise\n\nSudden profit change\n\nLarge hedge requirement\n\nClosing before expiry can reduce this operational uncertainty.\n\nThe cost is surrendering remaining time value or paying the spread.\n\n### Options Position Sizing\n\nLong options should be sized assuming the premium can be lost completely.\n\nDefined-risk spreads should be sized using their maximum loss rather than the credit received.\n\nShort uncovered options require stress testing far beyond ordinary historical movements.\n\nA portfolio should also aggregate exposures across strategies.\n\nSeveral positions may all be:\n\nLong delta\n\nShort volatility\n\nConcentrated in one expiry\n\nDependent on one exchange\n\nCollateralised by one stablecoin\n\nThe number of strategy names does not determine diversification.\n\n### Greek Exposure at Portfolio Level\n\nAn option portfolio may be summarised through net Greeks.\n\nA portfolio could have:\n\nPositive delta\n\nNegative gamma\n\nPositive theta\n\nNegative vega\n\nThis might describe a bullish premium-selling portfolio.\n\nIt benefits from moderate upward movement and time decay but may lose during a sharp move or volatility increase.\n\nNet Greeks provide a snapshot.\n\nBecause the Greeks change, stress scenarios are still required.\n\n### Scenario Grid\n\nA scenario grid estimates the portfolio value under combinations of:\n\nUnderlying price movement\n\nImplied-volatility change\n\nPassage of time\n\nFor example, a trader may calculate the position after:\n\nPrice falls ten percent\n\nPrice remains unchanged\n\nPrice rises ten percent\n\ncombined with:\n\nIV falls ten points\n\nIV remains unchanged\n\nIV rises ten points\n\nThis reveals risks hidden by an expiry payoff diagram.','markdown',NULL,NULL,NULL,6,0,0,0,'',NULL,8,1785297600000 WHERE EXISTS (SELECT 1 FROM `courses` WHERE `id`='cognizen-crypto-mastery-foundations-production');
--> statement-breakpoint
INSERT OR IGNORE INTO `lessons` (`id`,`course_id`,`title`,`section_id`,`lesson_type`,`content`,`content_format`,`video_key`,`primary_asset_id`,`intro_asset_id`,`duration_minutes`,`is_preview`,`available_after_days`,`required_watch_percent`,`transcript`,`experience_json`,`position`,`updated_at`) SELECT 'cmf-module-3-09-lesson-09','cognizen-crypto-mastery-foundations-production','Stress Testing Beyond the Greeks and A Practical Advanced Options Process','cmf-module-3-09','text','### Stress Testing Beyond the Greeks\n\nThe Greeks are local estimates and may be unreliable during extreme changes.\n\nStress testing should include:\n\nLarge price gaps\n\nVolatility doubling\n\nLiquidity disappearing\n\nStablecoin depeg\n\nExchange outage\n\nMargin increase\n\nShort assignment\n\nHedge failure\n\nA strategy that appears controlled under small modelled movements may behave very differently during a crisis.\n\n### Maximum Loss Is Conditional on Platform Performance\n\nA vertical spread may have a defined theoretical maximum loss.\n\nThe actual financial outcome can differ because of:\n\nExchange insolvency\n\nSettlement error\n\nOne leg failing to execute\n\nEarly assignment\n\nCollateral depeg\n\nContract dispute\n\nSmart contract exploit\n\nDefined risk refers to the contractual payoff under functioning market infrastructure.\n\nIt does not eliminate operational and counterparty risk.\n\n### Options Journal\n\nAn options journal should record more than entry and exit price.\n\nIt should include:\n\nUnderlying\n\nStrategy\n\nStrikes\n\nExpiry\n\nContract multiplier\n\nPremium\n\nImplied volatility\n\nVolatility rank or percentile\n\nDelta, gamma, theta and vega\n\nMarket regime\n\nExpected movement\n\nEvent risk\n\nMaximum profit and loss\n\nBreak-even points\n\nExit or adjustment rules\n\nActual execution costs\n\nAfter closing, the trader should determine whether the result was caused by direction, volatility, time, execution or strategy design.\n\n### Example: Bull Call Spread\n\nSuppose a cryptocurrency trades at 100.\n\nThe trader expects a moderate rise over two months.\n\nThey:\n\nBuy a 100-strike call for 12\n\nSell a 120-strike call for 5\n\nNet debit:\n\n12 − 5 = 7\n\nMaximum loss:\n\n7\n\nMaximum spread value:\n\n120 − 100 = 20\n\nMaximum profit:\n\n20 − 7 = 13\n\nBreak-even at expiry:\n\n100 + 7 = 107\n\nThe spread reduces cost compared with the long call but gives up gains above 120.\n\n### Example: Bull Put Spread\n\nSuppose the asset trades at 100 and the trader expects it to remain above 90.\n\nThey:\n\nSell 90 put for 6\n\nBuy 80 put for 2\n\nNet credit:\n\n6 − 2 = 4\n\nMaximum profit:\n\n4\n\nMaximum loss:\n\n10 strike width − 4 credit = 6\n\nBreak-even:\n\n90 − 4 = 86\n\nThe strategy can earn the maximum credit even if price does not rise.\n\nIt loses if price declines substantially.\n\n### Example: Calendar Spread\n\nSuppose the asset trades at 100.\n\nThe trader expects near-term stability but greater movement later.\n\nThey:\n\nSell a one-month 100 call for 5\n\nBuy a three-month 100 call for 11\n\nNet debit:\n\n6\n\nIf price remains near 100 at the first expiry, the short call may decay quickly while the longer call retains substantial time value.\n\nIf price moves sharply away, the result depends on delta, volatility and the remaining value of both options.\n\nThe payoff cannot be understood through the net debit alone.\n\n### Example: Iron Condor\n\nSuppose the trader expects price to remain between 90 and 110.\n\nThey create:\n\nLong 80 put\n\nShort 90 put\n\nShort 110 call\n\nLong 120 call\n\nNet credit: 3 units.\n\nWing width: 10 units.\n\nMaximum profit:\n\n3\n\nMaximum loss:\n\n10 − 3 = 7\n\nLower break-even:\n\n90 − 3 = 87\n\nUpper break-even:\n\n110 + 3 = 113\n\nThe strategy has a relatively high probability zone but risks more than the premium earned.\n\n### Example: Long Straddle and Volatility Crush\n\nSuppose an asset trades at 100 before a major decision.\n\nThe at-the-money call costs 9 and the put costs 8.\n\nTotal premium:\n\n17\n\nAfter the announcement, price rises to 110.\n\nThe direction was bullish, but the movement is smaller than the upper expiry break-even of 117.\n\nImplied volatility also falls sharply.\n\nThe straddle may lose value despite the ten-percent movement.\n\nThe event occurred, but the option market had priced an even larger move.\n\n### Example: Ratio Spread Risk\n\nSuppose the trader:\n\nBuys one 100-strike call\n\nSells two 120-strike calls\n\nThe position may perform well if price rises toward 120.\n\nAbove a sufficiently high price, the extra short call creates growing loss.\n\nThe strategy may have a low initial cost, but the upside risk is not limited.\n\nA cheap entry does not imply a safe payoff.\n\n### A Practical Advanced Options Process\n\nBegin with the market thesis. State whether the view concerns direction, volatility, time or a combination.\n\nExamine the volatility surface. Determine whether the relevant strikes and expiry appear expensive or inexpensive relative to alternatives and history.\n\nSelect a strategy whose payoff matches the expected movement. Do not choose a complicated structure merely because it offers a low premium or attractive maximum return.\n\nCalculate the maximum profit, maximum loss and expiry break-even points. Then examine the Greeks and model how the position may behave before expiry.\n\nReview liquidity in every leg. Estimate spread, fees and the difficulty of exiting.\n\nFinally, stress-test a larger-than-expected movement and ensure that the complete loss remains acceptable.','markdown',NULL,NULL,NULL,6,0,0,0,'',NULL,9,1785297600000 WHERE EXISTS (SELECT 1 FROM `courses` WHERE `id`='cognizen-crypto-mastery-foundations-production');
--> statement-breakpoint
INSERT OR IGNORE INTO `lessons` (`id`,`course_id`,`title`,`section_id`,`lesson_type`,`content`,`content_format`,`video_key`,`primary_asset_id`,`intro_asset_id`,`duration_minutes`,`is_preview`,`available_after_days`,`required_watch_percent`,`transcript`,`experience_json`,`position`,`updated_at`) SELECT 'cmf-module-3-09-lesson-10','cognizen-crypto-mastery-foundations-production','Advanced Options Checklist and Common Misunderstandings','cmf-module-3-09','text','### Advanced Options Checklist\n\nBefore entering a multi-leg option strategy, ask:\n\nIs the thesis directional, volatility based, time based or relative value?\n\nWhich price movement and timing would make the strategy successful?\n\nWhat is the current implied volatility?\n\nHow does IV compare across strikes and expiries?\n\nIs downside put protection unusually expensive?\n\nIs speculative call demand creating upside skew?\n\nWhat is the volatility term structure?\n\nIs a major event included in the option premium?\n\nWhat are the position’s net delta, gamma, theta and vega?\n\nHow will those Greeks change as price moves?\n\nIs the strategy long or short volatility?\n\nIs it long or short gamma?\n\nHow much theta is gained or lost daily?\n\nWhat is the maximum theoretical profit?\n\nWhat is the maximum theoretical loss?\n\nAre those limits dependent on all legs remaining intact?\n\nWhat are the break-even points at expiry?\n\nCan the position be profitable before reaching those break-even levels?\n\nHow liquid is every option leg?\n\nCan the strategy be executed as one combination?\n\nWhat legging risk exists?\n\nIs early assignment possible?\n\nWhat happens near expiry if price is close to a strike?\n\nWhich collateral and margin rules apply?\n\nCan margin requirements increase?\n\nWhat is the platform or smart contract risk?\n\nHow does the strategy interact with the rest of the portfolio?\n\nAre several positions concentrated in the same volatility exposure?\n\nWhat event invalidates the thesis?\n\nHow and when will the position be closed, adjusted or rolled?\n\nIs the full realistic loss acceptable?\n\n### Common Advanced Options Mistakes\n\nThe first mistake is selecting a strategy by its name rather than by its exposures. An iron condor sounds sophisticated, but economically it is a defined-risk short-volatility position.\n\nAnother error is focusing only on the expiry payoff. Before expiry, the position can move significantly because of delta, gamma, theta and vega.\n\nTraders may also view a credit as profit at entry. The premium is received immediately, but the obligation remains until the position is closed or expires.\n\nA further mistake is assuming that multiple legs automatically reduce risk. They may limit one part of the payoff while introducing assignment, liquidity and execution complexity.\n\nSome participants roll losing positions repeatedly without calculating the cumulative realised loss and the new maximum exposure.\n\nFinally, traders may rely on current Greeks during a stress event. The Greeks can change rapidly and may underestimate nonlinear behaviour after a large market movement.\n\n### Common Misunderstandings\n\n#### “A Delta-Neutral Position Has No Market Risk”\n\nDelta neutrality is temporary and does not remove gamma, vega, theta, liquidity or gap risk.\n\n#### “Positive Theta Means the Position Earns Money Every Day”\n\nAdverse price or volatility changes can exceed the estimated time decay.\n\n#### “Positive Gamma Guarantees Profit From Volatility”\n\nRealised movement must be sufficient to overcome premium, theta and hedging costs.\n\n#### “High Implied Volatility Means Options Should Always Be Sold”\n\nVolatility can rise further, and realised movement may exceed the already high expectation.\n\n#### “Low Implied Volatility Makes Options Cheap”\n\nLow IV may be justified when little movement is likely, and time decay still applies.\n\n#### “A Credit Spread Cannot Lose More Than the Credit”\n\nMaximum loss is generally the strike width minus the credit, multiplied by contract size.\n\n#### “An Iron Condor Is Market Neutral”\n\nIt may begin with limited directional exposure but carries significant short-volatility and gamma risk.\n\n#### “A Calendar Spread Is Only a Theta Strategy”\n\nIt is also highly sensitive to volatility term structure and underlying-price location.\n\n#### “A Butterfly Has a High Reward Because Its Debit Is Small”\n\nIts maximum payoff may require the asset to finish near one precise strike.\n\n#### “A Covered Call Creates Income Without Additional Risk”\n\nIt sells upside participation while leaving most underlying downside risk intact.\n\n#### “Rolling an Option Avoids Realising a Loss”\n\nThe old position is closed and a new position is opened.\n\n#### “Defined Risk Means No Operational Risk”\n\nPlatform, settlement, collateral and execution failures remain possible.','markdown',NULL,NULL,NULL,5,0,0,0,'',NULL,10,1785297600000 WHERE EXISTS (SELECT 1 FROM `courses` WHERE `id`='cognizen-crypto-mastery-foundations-production');
--> statement-breakpoint
INSERT OR IGNORE INTO `lessons` (`id`,`course_id`,`title`,`section_id`,`lesson_type`,`content`,`content_format`,`video_key`,`primary_asset_id`,`intro_asset_id`,`duration_minutes`,`is_preview`,`available_after_days`,`required_watch_percent`,`transcript`,`experience_json`,`position`,`updated_at`) SELECT 'cmf-module-3-09-lesson-11','cognizen-crypto-mastery-foundations-production','Module Summary and Key Takeaway','cmf-module-3-09','text','### Module Summary\n\nThe option Greeks provide a language for describing changing option risk.\n\nDelta measures directional sensitivity.\n\nGamma measures how quickly delta changes.\n\nTheta estimates the effect of time passing.\n\nVega measures sensitivity to implied volatility.\n\nRho measures sensitivity to interest rates.\n\nThe Greeks interact. A favourable directional movement may be offset by time decay or volatility decline.\n\nPositive-gamma positions generally benefit from large movement and pay theta.\n\nNegative-gamma positions generally receive theta but can lose rapidly during extreme movement.\n\nThe implied volatility surface shows how volatility is priced across strikes and expiries.\n\nSkew reveals whether the market is paying more for downside protection or upside speculation.\n\nTerm structure compares expected volatility across time.\n\nAdvanced option strategies combine several contracts to reshape exposure.\n\nVertical spreads limit both risk and reward.\n\nCalendar and diagonal spreads trade differences in time decay and volatility across expiries.\n\nButterflies and condors seek payoffs within defined price areas.\n\nIron condors and iron butterflies are defined-risk short-volatility strategies.\n\nRatio spreads and backspreads create asymmetric exposure and can contain significant tail risk.\n\nRisk reversals combine calls and puts to create directional exposure and can also reveal relative option pricing.\n\nMulti-leg strategies should always be analysed as complete positions.\n\nThe apparent benefit of one leg may be offset by obligations elsewhere.\n\nAdvanced options strategy is not about adding complexity.\n\nIt is about choosing precisely which combination of direction, volatility, time and tail risk the portfolio is prepared to carry.\n\n### Key Takeaway\n\nAdvanced option strategies do not eliminate uncertainty.\n\nThey redistribute it.\n\nEvery spread, butterfly, condor or volatility position changes the portfolio’s exposure to price, time, volatility and extreme movement.\n\nBefore entering, identify the net Greeks, maximum loss, liquidity and conditions under which the payoff changes rapidly.\n\nDo not ask only what the strategy can earn.\n\nAsk which risk another participant is paying you to accept—and whether your portfolio can survive when that risk arrives.\n\nThe next module is 3.10: Derivatives Positioning, Funding and Liquidation Analysis.','markdown',NULL,NULL,NULL,3,0,0,0,'',NULL,11,1785297600000 WHERE EXISTS (SELECT 1 FROM `courses` WHERE `id`='cognizen-crypto-mastery-foundations-production');
--> statement-breakpoint
INSERT OR IGNORE INTO `lessons` (`id`,`course_id`,`title`,`section_id`,`lesson_type`,`content`,`content_format`,`video_key`,`primary_asset_id`,`intro_asset_id`,`duration_minutes`,`is_preview`,`available_after_days`,`required_watch_percent`,`transcript`,`experience_json`,`position`,`updated_at`) SELECT 'cmf-module-3-09-lesson-12','cognizen-crypto-mastery-foundations-production','Check your understanding','cmf-module-3-09','text','### Check your understanding\n\nAnswer these questions to self-assess your understanding before moving on.\n\n1. What does delta measure?\n\n2. Why does an option’s delta change?\n\n3. How can delta be used to estimate portfolio directional exposure?\n\n4. Why is delta neutrality temporary?\n\n5. What does gamma measure?\n\n6. Why is gamma often high near expiry?\n\n7. What does positive gamma provide to an option buyer?\n\n8. Why is negative gamma dangerous during large market movement?\n\n9. What is gamma scalping?\n\n10. Which costs must gamma-scalping gains overcome?\n\n11. What does theta measure?\n\n12. Why does time decay often accelerate near expiry?\n\n13. How does theta affect option buyers and sellers differently?\n\n14. What does vega measure?\n\n15. Why do longer-dated options generally have greater vega?\n\n16. What is volatility crush?\n\n17. Why can a call lose value after favourable news?\n\n18. What is an implied volatility surface?\n\n19. What is volatility skew?\n\n20. What does an expensive downside put skew suggest?\n\n21. What is volatility term structure?\n\n22. What is the volatility risk premium?\n\n23. How does a bull put spread work?\n\n24. How is maximum loss calculated for a credit spread?\n\n25. What is a calendar spread?\n\n26. Why is a calendar spread sensitive to more than time decay?\n\n27. What is a diagonal spread?\n\n28. What is a butterfly spread designed to achieve?\n\n29. How does an iron butterfly differ from a conventional butterfly?\n\n30. How does an iron condor generate profit?\n\n31. Why can an iron condor lose during a breakout?\n\n32. What is a ratio spread?\n\n33. Why can a call ratio spread have unlimited risk?\n\n34. What is a backspread?\n\n35. What is a synthetic long position?\n\n36. What does put-call parity describe?\n\n37. What is legging risk?\n\n38. Why can early assignment change a spread’s risk?\n\n39. Why should every leg’s liquidity be examined?\n\n40. What is pin risk?\n\n41. How can an option portfolio be evaluated using net Greeks?\n\n42. Why is an expiry payoff diagram insufficient for pre-expiry risk?\n\n43. What should a scenario grid test?\n\n44. Why can a position with defined theoretical loss still suffer operational loss?\n\n45. How should a long option position be sized?\n\n46. How should a credit spread be sized?\n\n47. What should an advanced options journal record?\n\n48. Why does receiving premium not mean the profit has already been earned?\n\n49. How does strategy selection depend on both direction and volatility?\n\n50. Why does complexity not necessarily improve an option strategy?','markdown',NULL,NULL,NULL,6,0,0,0,'',NULL,12,1785297600000 WHERE EXISTS (SELECT 1 FROM `courses` WHERE `id`='cognizen-crypto-mastery-foundations-production');
--> statement-breakpoint
INSERT OR IGNORE INTO `course_sections` (`id`,`course_id`,`title`,`position`,`created_at`) SELECT 'cmf-module-3-10','cognizen-crypto-mastery-foundations-production','Module 3.10: Derivatives Positioning, Funding and Liquidation Analysis',11,1785297600000 WHERE EXISTS (SELECT 1 FROM `courses` WHERE `id`='cognizen-crypto-mastery-foundations-production');
