INSERT OR IGNORE INTO `lessons` (`id`,`course_id`,`title`,`section_id`,`lesson_type`,`content`,`content_format`,`video_key`,`primary_asset_id`,`intro_asset_id`,`duration_minutes`,`is_preview`,`available_after_days`,`required_watch_percent`,`transcript`,`experience_json`,`position`,`updated_at`) SELECT 'cmf-module-3-11-lesson-01','cognizen-crypto-mastery-foundations-production','What Is On-Chain Data? and The Blockchain as an Accounting Record','cmf-module-3-11','text','### Learning Objectives\n\nBy the end of this module, you should understand what on-chain analysis is, how blockchain data differs from exchange and market data, and why public ledgers can provide insight into network activity and asset-holder behaviour.\n\nYou should be able to distinguish transactions, addresses, wallets and entities; explain the difference between raw blockchain data and interpreted metrics; and understand the importance of data cleaning, entity identification and network-specific context.\n\nYou should also be able to describe how on-chain analysis may contribute to fundamental analysis, market-cycle assessment, risk management and transaction monitoring without treating blockchain activity as a precise forecast of future prices.\n\n### Introduction\n\nMost traditional financial activity occurs inside private databases.\n\nBanks, payment processors, custodians and exchanges maintain internal records of balances and transactions. The public normally sees only selected reports, aggregated statistics or information released by regulators and companies.\n\nPublic blockchains operate differently.\n\nThey record transactions on a distributed ledger that can usually be inspected by anyone. Depending on the network, an observer may be able to examine transaction values, wallet addresses, smart contract interactions, token transfers, fees and the movement of assets between different parts of the ecosystem.\n\nThis creates a new field of analysis.\n\nOn-chain analysis is the study of blockchain data to understand network activity, asset movement and participant behaviour.\n\nIt can help analysts investigate questions such as:\n\nHow actively is a blockchain being used?\n\nAre assets moving toward or away from exchanges?\n\nAre long-term holders selling?\n\nIs network activity increasing?\n\nAre users interacting with decentralised applications?\n\nIs a large proportion of token supply concentrated among a small number of holders?\n\nAre market participants realising profits or losses?\n\nThese questions can provide useful information that is not visible on an ordinary price chart.\n\nHowever, on-chain transparency has important limitations.\n\nA blockchain address does not automatically represent one person. One organisation may control thousands of addresses. One address may represent an exchange holding assets for millions of customers.\n\nA transfer to an exchange may indicate a possible intention to sell, but it may also represent custody restructuring, collateral movement or an internal exchange transaction.\n\nOn-chain data is observable.\n\nParticipant intention usually is not.\n\nThe discipline therefore requires careful interpretation, humility and an understanding of how each blockchain operates.\n\n### What Is On-Chain Data?\n\nOn-chain data is information recorded directly on a blockchain.\n\nDepending on the network, it may include the sending and receiving addresses, amount transferred, transaction fee, confirmation time and smart contract called.\n\nIt may also reveal the creation or destruction of tokens, staking activity, decentralised exchange swaps, lending deposits, governance votes and non-fungible token transfers.\n\nOnce confirmed, this information becomes part of the blockchain’s historical record.\n\nAnalysts can access it through:\n\nBlockchain nodes\n\nBlock explorers\n\nData-indexing platforms\n\nAnalytics services\n\nApplication programming interfaces\n\nSpecialised databases\n\nThe raw data is highly detailed.\n\nIts usefulness depends on how it is organised and interpreted.\n\n### On-Chain Analysis Versus Market Analysis\n\nMarket analysis studies variables produced by trading venues.\n\nThese may include:\n\nPrice\n\nVolume\n\nBid-ask spread\n\nOrder-book depth\n\nOpen interest\n\nFunding\n\nLiquidations\n\nOn-chain analysis studies activity occurring on the blockchain itself.\n\nThese may include:\n\nAsset transfers\n\nWallet balances\n\nActive addresses\n\nTransaction counts\n\nNetwork fees\n\nExchange-related flows\n\nSmart contract usage\n\nToken-holder behaviour\n\nThe two datasets overlap but are not identical.\n\nA purchase on a centralised exchange may change beneficial ownership without creating an immediate blockchain transaction. The exchange may simply update customer balances inside its own database.\n\nThe asset may move on-chain only when a deposit or withdrawal occurs.\n\nThis means exchange trading activity can be substantial while blockchain transfer activity remains relatively stable.\n\nConversely, a large on-chain transfer may occur without representing a market purchase or sale.\n\nThe asset may simply move between wallets controlled by the same entity.\n\n### The Blockchain as an Accounting Record\n\nA blockchain can be understood as a shared accounting system.\n\nIt records changes in ownership or control according to the rules of the network.\n\nOn Bitcoin, the ledger tracks units associated with unspent transaction outputs.\n\nOn account-based networks such as Ethereum, the system updates balances and smart contract states.\n\nThe blockchain does not normally record a person’s legal identity directly.\n\nIt records cryptographic addresses and transactions.\n\nAn analyst must therefore move from three different layers:\n\nThe technical transaction\n\nThe address or group of addresses involved\n\nThe possible economic entity and purpose behind the activity\n\nThe first layer may be objectively observable.\n\nThe second and third require increasing interpretation.','markdown',NULL,NULL,NULL,6,0,0,0,'',NULL,1,1785297600000 WHERE EXISTS (SELECT 1 FROM `courses` WHERE `id`='cognizen-crypto-mastery-foundations-production');
--> statement-breakpoint
INSERT OR IGNORE INTO `lessons` (`id`,`course_id`,`title`,`section_id`,`lesson_type`,`content`,`content_format`,`video_key`,`primary_asset_id`,`intro_asset_id`,`duration_minutes`,`is_preview`,`available_after_days`,`required_watch_percent`,`transcript`,`experience_json`,`position`,`updated_at`) SELECT 'cmf-module-3-11-lesson-02','cognizen-crypto-mastery-foundations-production','Transactions and UTXO and Account-Based Models','cmf-module-3-11','text','### Transactions\n\nA transaction is an instruction submitted to the blockchain.\n\nIt may transfer an asset, interact with a smart contract, delegate stake or perform another function permitted by the network.\n\nA transaction normally includes a unique identifier known as a transaction hash.\n\nThe record may also show:\n\nBlock number\n\nTimestamp\n\nSender\n\nRecipient\n\nAmount\n\nFee\n\nConfirmation status\n\nInput data\n\nOn smart contract networks, one user transaction can generate several internal actions.\n\nFor example, a decentralised exchange swap may involve transfers between the user, a router contract and one or more liquidity pools.\n\nCounting only the outer transaction may fail to capture the complete economic activity.\n\n### Addresses, Wallets and Entities\n\nThese terms are often used interchangeably, but they are not identical.\n\nAn address is a blockchain destination associated with cryptographic control.\n\nA wallet is software or hardware used to manage keys and interact with one or more addresses.\n\nAn entity is the person, company, protocol, exchange or organisation believed to control an address or group of addresses.\n\nOne wallet application may create many addresses.\n\nOne exchange may control thousands or millions of addresses.\n\nOne person may use several wallets, exchanges and blockchain networks.\n\nFor this reason, a count of addresses is not the same as a count of users.\n\n### Address Clustering\n\nAddress clustering is the process of grouping addresses that may be controlled by the same entity.\n\nOn Bitcoin, analysts may use transaction structure and spending behaviour to identify possible relationships between addresses.\n\nOn account-based networks, analysts may examine funding sources, repeated interaction patterns and known labels.\n\nClustering can improve the interpretation of blockchain activity.\n\nFor example, a transfer between two addresses owned by the same exchange should not necessarily be interpreted as a customer deposit or withdrawal.\n\nClustering is probabilistic.\n\nIncorrect clustering can cause misleading conclusions about ownership, flows and concentration.\n\n### Entity Labelling\n\nAnalytics providers may label addresses associated with known entities such as:\n\nExchanges\n\nCustodians\n\nMining pools\n\nValidators\n\nProtocol treasuries\n\nBridges\n\nStablecoin issuers\n\nInvestment funds\n\nFraudulent schemes\n\nLabels may come from public disclosures, transaction patterns, test deposits or other investigative methods.\n\nA label can be outdated or incomplete.\n\nAn exchange may change its wallet structure. A protocol may migrate contracts. An address may serve more than one purpose.\n\nEntity labels should therefore be treated as maintained datasets rather than permanent blockchain facts.\n\n### Raw Data and Derived Metrics\n\nRaw blockchain data consists of the original transactions, blocks and contract states.\n\nDerived metrics transform that data into more understandable indicators.\n\nExamples include:\n\nDaily active addresses\n\nExchange inflows\n\nAverage transaction value\n\nRealised capitalisation\n\nHolder age distribution\n\nNetwork-value ratios\n\nSupply in profit\n\nStaking participation\n\nEvery derived metric depends on a methodology.\n\nThe methodology determines:\n\nWhich transactions are counted\n\nWhich addresses are excluded\n\nHow entities are clustered\n\nWhich time period is used\n\nHow token movements are valued\n\nHow contract activity is interpreted\n\nTwo analytics platforms may publish different values for the same named metric because they use different methods.\n\n### Data Cleaning\n\nBlockchain activity contains noise.\n\nA network may record:\n\nExchange internal transfers\n\nSpam transactions\n\nAutomated bots\n\nAirdrop claims\n\nContract maintenance\n\nArbitrage\n\nWash activity\n\nToken migrations\n\nA raw transaction count can rise dramatically without indicating meaningful user adoption.\n\nData cleaning attempts to remove or classify activity that would otherwise distort the metric.\n\nThis process can improve accuracy but introduces judgement.\n\nAn analyst should ask not only what a metric shows, but also what the provider included or excluded.\n\n### Network-Specific Interpretation\n\nOn-chain metrics cannot always be compared directly across blockchains.\n\nA transaction on Bitcoin differs economically from a transaction on Ethereum or a high-throughput smart contract network.\n\nOne network may encourage users to combine several actions into one transaction.\n\nAnother may generate many small transactions because fees are low.\n\nSome networks execute transactions through rollups or secondary layers and later submit aggregated data to a base chain.\n\nOthers may use different account, staking or fee structures.\n\nA higher transaction count does not automatically mean greater economic activity or adoption.\n\nMetrics must be interpreted within the architecture of the network.\n\n### UTXO and Account-Based Models\n\nBitcoin uses an unspent transaction output, or UTXO, model.\n\nA wallet does not simply contain one balance entry. It controls individual outputs created by earlier transactions.\n\nWhen those outputs are spent, new outputs are created.\n\nThis structure allows analysts to study the age and movement of individual coin units.\n\nEthereum and many other networks use an account-based model.\n\nBalances and contract states are updated directly within accounts.\n\nThe two models produce different analytical opportunities and require different methodologies.','markdown',NULL,NULL,NULL,6,0,0,0,'',NULL,2,1785297600000 WHERE EXISTS (SELECT 1 FROM `courses` WHERE `id`='cognizen-crypto-mastery-foundations-production');
--> statement-breakpoint
INSERT OR IGNORE INTO `lessons` (`id`,`course_id`,`title`,`section_id`,`lesson_type`,`content`,`content_format`,`video_key`,`primary_asset_id`,`intro_asset_id`,`duration_minutes`,`is_preview`,`available_after_days`,`required_watch_percent`,`transcript`,`experience_json`,`position`,`updated_at`) SELECT 'cmf-module-3-11-lesson-03','cognizen-crypto-mastery-foundations-production','Smart Contract Activity and Token Burns','cmf-module-3-11','text','### Smart Contract Activity\n\nOn a programmable blockchain, a transaction may do far more than send tokens.\n\nA user may:\n\nSwap assets\n\nDeposit collateral\n\nBorrow funds\n\nProvide liquidity\n\nStake tokens\n\nMint an NFT\n\nVote in governance\n\nBridge assets\n\nOn-chain analysis can therefore examine the use of individual applications and protocols.\n\nHowever, smart contract activity must be interpreted carefully.\n\nA high volume of transactions may be generated by arbitrage bots rather than unique users.\n\nA rise in locked assets may result from higher token prices rather than new deposits.\n\nThe economic meaning behind the contract activity matters.\n\n### Active Addresses\n\nAn active address is generally an address that participated in a transaction during a specified period.\n\nSome metrics count senders.\n\nOthers count both senders and receivers.\n\nSome attempt to remove exchange or contract addresses.\n\nActive-address growth may suggest increasing network participation.\n\nIt may also result from:\n\nOne entity creating many addresses\n\nBot activity\n\nAirdrops\n\nSpam\n\nInternal exchange movement\n\nAddress-management practices\n\nActive addresses are a useful activity measure, but not a precise count of people.\n\n### New Addresses\n\nNew-address metrics count addresses appearing on-chain for the first time.\n\nA sustained rise may suggest new users or new applications.\n\nIt can also occur because existing users generate new addresses for privacy, custody or operational reasons.\n\nOn Bitcoin, good privacy practice may involve using a new address for each transaction.\n\nA single user can therefore produce many new addresses.\n\nThe metric is more meaningful when combined with transaction value, retention and other indicators of genuine network engagement.\n\n### Transaction Count\n\nTransaction count measures the number of recorded transactions during a period.\n\nAn increase may indicate greater use.\n\nYet one high-value settlement transaction can have more economic significance than thousands of low-value automated transfers.\n\nTransaction count should be evaluated alongside:\n\nTransaction value\n\nFees\n\nActive users\n\nContract type\n\nNetwork capacity\n\nSpam controls\n\nA network can increase transaction count by lowering costs without necessarily increasing valuable economic activity.\n\n### Transaction Volume\n\nOn-chain transaction volume attempts to measure the value transferred through the blockchain.\n\nThis may be reported in:\n\nNative asset units\n\nStablecoin value\n\nNational-currency equivalent\n\nRaw transfer volume can be inflated by assets moving repeatedly between related addresses.\n\nAnalytics providers may attempt to calculate adjusted transfer volume by excluding known internal or repetitive transfers.\n\nThe adjustment method matters.\n\nA large transfer volume does not prove that the network generated equivalent economic value.\n\n### Average and Median Transaction Value\n\nAverage transaction value is calculated by dividing total transfer value by transaction count.\n\nIt can be distorted by a small number of extremely large transactions.\n\nMedian transaction value identifies the middle transaction and may better reflect typical use.\n\nComparing average with median can reveal whether activity is dominated by large institutional transfers or many smaller transactions.\n\nNeither measure identifies the purpose of the transfers.\n\n### Network Fees\n\nNetwork fees are payments made to miners, validators or other transaction processors.\n\nFee levels can reveal demand for limited block space.\n\nRising fees may indicate greater network usage.\n\nThey may also indicate congestion, speculation or inefficient network capacity.\n\nHigh fees can benefit network security or token economics in some designs.\n\nThey can also make the network too expensive for ordinary users.\n\nFee analysis should therefore consider both demand and accessibility.\n\n### Fee Revenue\n\nFor some networks, transaction fees represent revenue paid to validators, token holders or protocol participants.\n\nAnalysts may compare fee generation with:\n\nMarket capitalisation\n\nToken issuance\n\nValidator rewards\n\nApplication revenue\n\nUser activity\n\nA network generating meaningful fees may demonstrate economic demand for its services.\n\nHigh fees during one speculative event may not be sustainable.\n\nThe destination of those fees also matters.\n\nThey may be burned, distributed or retained by intermediaries.\n\n### Issuance and Supply Changes\n\nBlockchains may create new units through mining, staking rewards or other issuance mechanisms.\n\nThey may also destroy units through token burns or fee-burning systems.\n\nOn-chain analysis can track:\n\nNew issuance\n\nBurned supply\n\nNet supply growth\n\nStaked or locked supply\n\nCirculating supply\n\nSupply change affects scarcity.\n\nIt does not determine price by itself.\n\nDemand, liquidity and distribution remain essential.\n\n### Token Burns\n\nA token burn permanently removes units from usable supply, usually by sending them to an inaccessible address or reducing supply through contract logic.\n\nBurns may occur automatically or through governance decisions.\n\nA burn can reduce future supply.\n\nIts economic importance depends on its size relative to:\n\nCurrent circulation\n\nNew issuance\n\nToken unlocks\n\nDemand\n\nA project can burn tokens while issuing even more elsewhere.\n\nThe relevant measure is net supply change.','markdown',NULL,NULL,NULL,6,0,0,0,'',NULL,3,1785297600000 WHERE EXISTS (SELECT 1 FROM `courses` WHERE `id`='cognizen-crypto-mastery-foundations-production');
--> statement-breakpoint
INSERT OR IGNORE INTO `lessons` (`id`,`course_id`,`title`,`section_id`,`lesson_type`,`content`,`content_format`,`video_key`,`primary_asset_id`,`intro_asset_id`,`duration_minutes`,`is_preview`,`available_after_days`,`required_watch_percent`,`transcript`,`experience_json`,`position`,`updated_at`) SELECT 'cmf-module-3-11-lesson-04','cognizen-crypto-mastery-foundations-production','Staking Data and Realised Price','cmf-module-3-11','text','### Staking Data\n\nProof-of-stake networks allow holders to commit assets to network security.\n\nOn-chain data may show:\n\nTotal amount staked\n\nValidator count\n\nValidator concentration\n\nEntry and exit queues\n\nStaking rewards\n\nSlashing events\n\nA high staking rate can reduce liquid supply and indicate confidence in the network.\n\nIt can also create concentration, liquidity and governance risks.\n\nAssets described as staked may still remain economically liquid through staking derivatives.\n\nThe headline staking percentage does not reveal the complete market impact.\n\n### Holder Distribution\n\nHolder-distribution analysis examines how token supply is divided among addresses or entities.\n\nAn asset may appear decentralised because it has many addresses while most supply is controlled by a small number of insiders, custodians or protocols.\n\nConcentration can create risks including:\n\nMarket manipulation\n\nGovernance dominance\n\nSudden selling\n\nLiquidity shocks\n\nLarge addresses may also represent exchanges holding assets for many customers.\n\nEntity identification is therefore essential before describing one address as one whale.\n\n### Whales\n\nThe term whale generally refers to an entity controlling a large asset position.\n\nAnalysts often monitor whale transfers because large holders may influence liquidity.\n\nA large transfer can attract attention, but its meaning is uncertain.\n\nIt may represent:\n\nExchange deposit\n\nWithdrawal\n\nCustody migration\n\nCollateral\n\nInternal restructuring\n\nSale\n\nPurchase\n\nOver-the-counter settlement\n\nA whale alert is evidence that assets moved.\n\nIt is not proof of an intended trade.\n\n### Exchange Inflows\n\nExchange inflows measure assets transferred into addresses believed to belong to exchanges.\n\nThey are often interpreted as potential selling supply because holders may deposit assets to trade.\n\nA large inflow can increase the probability of selling.\n\nIt can also represent:\n\nCollateral deposit\n\nMarket-making inventory\n\nInternal transfer\n\nDerivative settlement\n\nCustody service\n\nThe effect depends on the asset, exchange and broader market context.\n\nA single large inflow should not automatically be treated as bearish.\n\n### Exchange Outflows\n\nExchange outflows measure assets leaving recognised exchange addresses.\n\nThey are often interpreted as movement into self-custody and reduced immediate selling supply.\n\nThis may support a long-term accumulation thesis.\n\nHowever, an outflow can also reflect:\n\nExchange wallet reorganisation\n\nInstitutional custody transfer\n\nCollateral deployment\n\nDeFi activity\n\nMovement to another venue\n\nSustained net outflows combined with other evidence may be more informative than one transaction.\n\n### Exchange Net Flow\n\nExchange net flow is commonly calculated as:\n\nInflows − Outflows\n\nA positive net flow means more assets entered recognised exchange addresses than left.\n\nA negative net flow means more left than entered.\n\nThe metric may be noisy because large internal wallet movements can dominate the result.\n\nAnalysts often use moving averages or longer periods to identify sustained trends.\n\n### Exchange Balances\n\nExchange-balance metrics estimate how much supply is held in known exchange wallets.\n\nA declining balance may suggest that more assets are moving into self-custody or long-term storage.\n\nA rising balance may indicate greater readily tradable supply.\n\nThe interpretation depends on accurate exchange labels.\n\nIt may also be affected by changes in custody structure and the growth of exchange-traded investment products or institutional custodians.\n\n### Holder Age\n\nOn UTXO-based networks, analysts can estimate how long individual units have remained unmoved.\n\nCoins that have not moved for years may be classified as long-term holdings.\n\nRecently moved coins may be associated with more active market participants.\n\nHolder-age analysis can reveal changes in the behaviour of older and newer supply.\n\nIt does not identify the legal owner or guarantee that unmoved assets are intentionally held.\n\nSome may be lost or inaccessible.\n\n### Coin Days\n\nA coin-day measure combines asset quantity with the length of time it remained unmoved.\n\nOne coin held for one day creates one coin day.\n\nTen coins held for one hundred days create one thousand coin days.\n\nWhen older coins move, a larger number of coin days is destroyed.\n\nThis can indicate that long-dormant supply has become active.\n\nA movement by old coins may represent selling, custody changes or other activity.\n\nThe destination and market context remain important.\n\n### Long-Term and Short-Term Holders\n\nSome analytical frameworks classify holders according to how long their assets have remained unmoved.\n\nLong-term holders are generally considered less likely to sell in response to ordinary volatility.\n\nShort-term holders may be more sensitive to price changes.\n\nThese classifications are statistical conventions rather than direct knowledge of investor intention.\n\nA long-held coin can be sold suddenly.\n\nA recently acquired coin may be intended for permanent storage.\n\n### Realised Price\n\nRealised price is an on-chain valuation concept.\n\nInstead of valuing every coin at the current market price, it values units according to the price when they last moved on-chain.\n\nThe combined value is divided by circulating supply to estimate an average on-chain cost basis.\n\nThis differs from ordinary market price.\n\nRealised price can provide insight into whether the average moved unit is currently in profit or loss.\n\nIts meaning depends on the network and methodology.\n\nLost coins, exchange transfers and non-economic transactions can affect the result.','markdown',NULL,NULL,NULL,6,0,0,0,'',NULL,4,1785297600000 WHERE EXISTS (SELECT 1 FROM `courses` WHERE `id`='cognizen-crypto-mastery-foundations-production');
--> statement-breakpoint
INSERT OR IGNORE INTO `lessons` (`id`,`course_id`,`title`,`section_id`,`lesson_type`,`content`,`content_format`,`video_key`,`primary_asset_id`,`intro_asset_id`,`duration_minutes`,`is_preview`,`available_after_days`,`required_watch_percent`,`transcript`,`experience_json`,`position`,`updated_at`) SELECT 'cmf-module-3-11-lesson-05','cognizen-crypto-mastery-foundations-production','Realised Capitalisation and Metcalfe’s Law and Network Effects','cmf-module-3-11','text','### Realised Capitalisation\n\nRealised capitalisation values each unit at the price at which it last moved, rather than at today’s price.\n\nIt may provide a different perspective on the capital stored in the network.\n\nMarket capitalisation can rise dramatically when the latest traded price increases, even if only a small amount of supply traded at that level.\n\nRealised capitalisation changes when assets move at new prices.\n\nIt can therefore respond more slowly than market capitalisation.\n\nThis metric is especially associated with transparent UTXO networks.\n\n### Market Value to Realised Value\n\nMarket Value to Realised Value, commonly called MVRV, compares market capitalisation with realised capitalisation.\n\nA simplified formula is:\n\nMVRV = Market capitalisation ÷ Realised capitalisation\n\nA high ratio may indicate that holders collectively have large unrealised profits.\n\nA low ratio may indicate that market value is close to or below the estimated aggregate cost basis.\n\nAnalysts sometimes use extreme historical values to study market cycles.\n\nThe metric does not guarantee a top or bottom.\n\nMarket structure, adoption and valuation regimes can change.\n\n### Supply in Profit and Loss\n\nOn-chain models may estimate the proportion of supply held above or below its last-moved price.\n\nA unit is considered in profit when the current market price exceeds the price at which it last moved.\n\nIt is considered in loss when current price is lower.\n\nHigh supply in profit can create potential selling pressure because many holders can realise gains.\n\nIt can also occur throughout a strong bull market.\n\nHigh supply in loss can signal stress, but losses may persist during prolonged bear markets.\n\n### Realised Profit and Loss\n\nRealised profit occurs when an asset moves at a higher market price than when it previously moved.\n\nRealised loss occurs when it moves at a lower price.\n\nAggregating these movements can provide insight into whether participants are taking profit or capitulating.\n\nLarge realised profits may appear during strong rallies.\n\nLarge realised losses may occur during panic.\n\nNot every transfer represents an actual sale, so these metrics rely on assumptions.\n\n### Spent Output Profit Ratio\n\nThe Spent Output Profit Ratio, or SOPR, is an on-chain metric often used for UTXO assets.\n\nIt compares the price at which spent outputs are moved with the price at which they were previously created.\n\nA value above one suggests that moved coins are, on average, being transferred at a profit.\n\nA value below one suggests movement at a loss.\n\nValues near one indicate movement near break-even.\n\nSOPR may help analyse profit-taking and capitulation.\n\nIt does not confirm that every movement was a market sale.\n\n### Dormancy\n\nDormancy uses the average age of moved coins or coin days destroyed relative to transaction volume.\n\nA rise may indicate that older supply is becoming active.\n\nA decline may suggest that transactions are dominated by recently moved coins.\n\nDormancy can help distinguish long-term holder movement from short-term circulation.\n\nThe metric can be distorted by large custody transfers involving old coins.\n\n### HODL Waves\n\nHODL waves group supply according to the length of time since units last moved.\n\nThey show how much supply has remained inactive for periods such as:\n\nLess than one month\n\nSeveral months\n\nOne year\n\nMultiple years\n\nThe distribution can help analysts study long-term accumulation and spending.\n\nThe name is informal, but the underlying metric is based on holder age.\n\nGrowth in older bands may indicate that supply is maturing into longer-term holdings.\n\n### Network Value Metrics\n\nAnalysts may compare network valuation with measures of activity.\n\nOne example is the Network Value to Transactions ratio.\n\nA simplified form is:\n\nNetwork value ÷ Transaction volume\n\nThe idea resembles comparing a company’s valuation with its economic throughput.\n\nA high ratio may suggest that valuation is large relative to transaction activity.\n\nA low ratio may suggest greater activity relative to value.\n\nThe metric is sensitive to how transaction volume is adjusted and whether transfers genuinely represent economic settlement.\n\n### Network Value to Transactions Signal\n\nSome frameworks smooth transaction volume to reduce noise and compare it with current network value.\n\nThis may produce a more stable signal than raw daily activity.\n\nThe methodology remains important.\n\nDifferent smoothing periods and adjusted-volume calculations can create different conclusions.\n\nNo valuation ratio should be used as a standalone timing indicator.\n\n### Metcalfe’s Law and Network Effects\n\nMetcalfe’s Law proposes that the value of a network may grow approximately with the square of the number of connected users.\n\nThe concept is often applied to digital networks.\n\nBlockchain analysts may compare asset value with active users or addresses.\n\nThe relationship is not exact.\n\nNot all users contribute equal value, and one address is not necessarily one user.\n\nThe law is better understood as a general network-effect principle than a precise valuation formula.','markdown',NULL,NULL,NULL,6,0,0,0,'',NULL,5,1785297600000 WHERE EXISTS (SELECT 1 FROM `courses` WHERE `id`='cognizen-crypto-mastery-foundations-production');
--> statement-breakpoint
INSERT OR IGNORE INTO `lessons` (`id`,`course_id`,`title`,`section_id`,`lesson_type`,`content`,`content_format`,`video_key`,`primary_asset_id`,`intro_asset_id`,`duration_minutes`,`is_preview`,`available_after_days`,`required_watch_percent`,`transcript`,`experience_json`,`position`,`updated_at`) SELECT 'cmf-module-3-11-lesson-06','cognizen-crypto-mastery-foundations-production','Stablecoin On-Chain Data and The Difference Between Correlation and Causation','cmf-module-3-11','text','### Stablecoin On-Chain Data\n\nStablecoins play a major role in cryptocurrency settlement, collateral and trading.\n\nOn-chain analysis may track:\n\nSupply growth\n\nRedemptions\n\nExchange balances\n\nBridge flows\n\nProtocol deposits\n\nLarge issuer transactions\n\nStablecoin supply expansion may indicate growing digital liquidity.\n\nIt may also reflect movement between stablecoin types or changes in collateral demand.\n\nA reduction in supply can signal redemptions, risk reduction or migration to other instruments.\n\n### DeFi On-Chain Data\n\nDecentralised finance creates extensive on-chain activity.\n\nAnalysts may examine:\n\nTotal value locked\n\nTrading volume\n\nLending deposits\n\nBorrowing\n\nInterest rates\n\nCollateral ratios\n\nLiquidations\n\nProtocol revenue\n\nThese metrics can reveal protocol usage and financial risk.\n\nThey must be adjusted for asset-price changes.\n\nA protocol’s locked value can rise because the deposited tokens became more expensive, even when no additional tokens were deposited.\n\n### Total Value Locked\n\nTotal Value Locked, or TVL, estimates the value of assets deposited in a protocol or set of protocols.\n\nIt is commonly used as a measure of DeFi adoption.\n\nTVL can be misleading because:\n\nAssets may be counted more than once\n\nToken prices change\n\nBorrowed funds may be redeposited\n\nIncentives attract temporary capital\n\nBridge assets introduce dependencies\n\nTVL should be considered alongside revenue, user activity and capital stability.\n\n### Protocol Revenue\n\nA protocol may earn fees from trading, lending, liquidation or other services.\n\nAnalysts should distinguish between:\n\nFees paid by users\n\nRevenue retained by the protocol\n\nRewards distributed to liquidity providers\n\nToken incentives paid to users\n\nHigh user fees do not necessarily create value for the governance token.\n\nThe token must have a credible mechanism for capturing part of the economic activity.\n\n### Bridge Flows\n\nBridges move assets or representations of assets between blockchain networks.\n\nLarge bridge inflows may indicate capital entering an ecosystem.\n\nOutflows may indicate migration elsewhere.\n\nBridge analysis requires attention to:\n\nWrapped assets\n\nCustodial structures\n\nSmart contract security\n\nNative issuance\n\nDouble counting\n\nAn asset bridged to another network may remain locked on the original network while a representation is created elsewhere.\n\n### Layer 2 Data\n\nLayer 2 systems process transactions away from a base blockchain and later submit data or proofs to it.\n\nActivity may include:\n\nUser transactions\n\nSequencer batches\n\nBridge deposits\n\nBridge withdrawals\n\nFees\n\nProof submissions\n\nAnalysing only the base chain may underestimate end-user activity.\n\nAnalysing only Layer 2 transaction count may ignore the security and settlement dependence on the base layer.\n\nBoth layers should be considered together.\n\n### NFT and Gaming Activity\n\nNon-fungible token and blockchain gaming activity can produce large transaction counts.\n\nRelevant metrics may include:\n\nUnique buyers and sellers\n\nSales volume\n\nFloor price\n\nHolder concentration\n\nRoyalty revenue\n\nIn-game transactions\n\nWash trading and incentive farming can distort activity.\n\nA high sales volume may be generated by participants trading assets between related wallets to earn rewards.\n\nAdjusted user and revenue metrics are more informative than headline volume alone.\n\n### Governance Activity\n\nOn-chain governance records may reveal:\n\nProposal creation\n\nVotes\n\nDelegation\n\nVoter participation\n\nConcentration of voting power\n\nHigh participation can indicate an engaged community.\n\nLow participation may allow a small group to control decisions.\n\nLarge delegated positions may belong to exchanges or service providers voting on behalf of customers.\n\nToken voting does not necessarily represent broad democratic participation.\n\n### Treasury Analysis\n\nMany blockchain projects and decentralised organisations hold on-chain treasuries.\n\nTreasury analysis may examine:\n\nAsset composition\n\nStablecoin reserves\n\nNative-token concentration\n\nSpending rate\n\nGrant payments\n\nDiversification\n\nRunway\n\nA treasury dominated by its own token may appear valuable during a bull market but lose value rapidly during a decline.\n\nA strong treasury should be evaluated according to liquid and usable resources rather than headline market value alone.\n\n### On-Chain Security Monitoring\n\nOn-chain data can also be used for risk and security analysis.\n\nAnalysts may monitor:\n\nLarge unexplained transfers\n\nContract upgrades\n\nAdmin-key actions\n\nOracle changes\n\nBridge withdrawals\n\nGovernance attacks\n\nExploit-related movements\n\nRapid detection can help users reduce exposure.\n\nThe challenge is distinguishing legitimate maintenance from malicious action.\n\nContext and verified communication remain necessary.\n\n### On-Chain Analysis and Privacy\n\nPublic blockchain data can create privacy concerns.\n\nAlthough addresses are pseudonymous, activity may be linked to identity through:\n\nExchange records\n\nPublic donations\n\nNFT profiles\n\nReused addresses\n\nMerchant payments\n\nInvestigations\n\nOnce an address is associated with an identity, its historical activity may become visible.\n\nAnalysts should use blockchain data responsibly and avoid unsupported claims about individuals.\n\nOn-chain transparency does not remove legal, ethical or privacy obligations.\n\n### The Difference Between Correlation and Causation\n\nAn on-chain metric may correlate with price without causing it.\n\nFor example, exchange outflows may rise during a bull market.\n\nThe outflows may support reduced selling supply.\n\nThey may also occur because rising prices increase investor confidence.\n\nBoth variables may be responding to a third factor.\n\nA historical relationship should not be treated as a permanent causal mechanism.\n\nThe analyst should explain the possible economic connection and test whether it remains consistent across different market regimes.','markdown',NULL,NULL,NULL,6,0,0,0,'',NULL,6,1785297600000 WHERE EXISTS (SELECT 1 FROM `courses` WHERE `id`='cognizen-crypto-mastery-foundations-production');
--> statement-breakpoint
INSERT OR IGNORE INTO `lessons` (`id`,`course_id`,`title`,`section_id`,`lesson_type`,`content`,`content_format`,`video_key`,`primary_asset_id`,`intro_asset_id`,`duration_minutes`,`is_preview`,`available_after_days`,`required_watch_percent`,`transcript`,`experience_json`,`position`,`updated_at`) SELECT 'cmf-module-3-11-lesson-07','cognizen-crypto-mastery-foundations-production','Lagging and Leading Metrics and A Practical On-Chain Analysis Process','cmf-module-3-11','text','### Lagging and Leading Metrics\n\nSome on-chain metrics respond after market movement.\n\nRealised profit may increase because price has already risen.\n\nLarge realised losses may occur after a decline.\n\nThese are partly lagging indicators.\n\nOther metrics may provide earlier context.\n\nA sudden increase in exchange inflows can precede selling, although it does not guarantee it.\n\nThe leading or lagging nature of a metric depends on how it is used and the timeframe being studied.\n\n### On-Chain Data and Market Timing\n\nOn-chain analysis is generally more useful for understanding structural conditions than for predicting short-term candles.\n\nIt may help identify:\n\nLong-term accumulation\n\nProfit-taking\n\nCapitulation\n\nSupply concentration\n\nNetwork adoption\n\nLeverage risk\n\nExchange pressure\n\nIt is less reliable for deciding the exact hour or day of an entry.\n\nShort-term market timing usually requires price, volume, liquidity and derivatives information in addition to on-chain evidence.\n\n### On-Chain Analysis and Fundamental Value\n\nOn-chain activity can contribute to fundamental analysis.\n\nA network with rising genuine users, fees, settlement value and developer activity may demonstrate increasing utility.\n\nHowever, high activity does not automatically make the token valuable.\n\nThe analyst must determine:\n\nWhether the token is necessary\n\nHow supply changes\n\nWho receives fees\n\nWhether activity is subsidised\n\nWhether users are genuine\n\nWhether competitors provide the service more efficiently\n\nNetwork success and token-holder return are related only when the token captures economic value.\n\n### Combining On-Chain and Technical Analysis\n\nTechnical analysis shows where price is trading and how market structure is changing.\n\nOn-chain analysis may help explain whether holder behaviour and network activity support that movement.\n\nSuppose price breaks major resistance.\n\nIf exchange balances decline, long-term holders remain inactive and genuine network activity rises, the breakout may have stronger structural support.\n\nIf price rises while old holders transfer large supply to exchanges and activity is dominated by speculation, the market may be more vulnerable.\n\nNeither combination guarantees an outcome.\n\nThe evidence improves scenario quality.\n\n### Combining On-Chain and Derivatives Analysis\n\nDerivatives metrics reveal leverage and positioning.\n\nOn-chain data may show movement of actual assets.\n\nA rally supported by spot exchange outflows and moderate derivatives leverage differs from one driven by rising open interest and extreme funding.\n\nDuring a decline, large exchange inflows combined with long liquidations may indicate both voluntary and forced selling.\n\nIf exchange inflows slow after open interest collapses, the pressure may be stabilising.\n\nThe two datasets provide different views of the same market.\n\n### Combining On-Chain and Macroeconomic Analysis\n\nNetwork activity can improve while market price declines because global financial conditions are unfavourable.\n\nHigher interest rates, reduced liquidity or broad risk aversion can outweigh positive on-chain fundamentals in the short term.\n\nConversely, abundant global liquidity can lift weak projects despite limited genuine use.\n\nOn-chain strength should therefore be evaluated within the broader capital-market regime.\n\n### Time Horizons\n\nDifferent on-chain metrics operate over different time horizons.\n\nA whale transfer may influence the market over hours or days.\n\nExchange-balance trends may develop over months.\n\nHolder-age distribution and realised capitalisation may provide multi-year cycle context.\n\nThe metric should match the decision.\n\nA long-term investor should not abandon a thesis because of one exchange deposit.\n\nA short-term trader should not ignore immediate price structure because a multi-year metric appears attractive.\n\n### Common Data Errors\n\nOn-chain analysis can be weakened by several data errors.\n\nDouble counting can occur when assets are deposited into one protocol and then reused elsewhere.\n\nEntity labels can become outdated.\n\nToken prices used for valuation can be manipulated or illiquid.\n\nBridge assets can be counted on several networks.\n\nSmart contract upgrades can change the meaning of the data.\n\nA reliable analyst checks methodology, source quality and whether the metric remains comparable over time.\n\n### Confirmation Bias\n\nThe transparency of blockchain data creates many possible metrics.\n\nAn analyst can often find one that supports a preferred opinion.\n\nA bullish participant may focus on exchange outflows.\n\nA bearish participant may focus on old coins moving.\n\nBoth may ignore contradictory evidence.\n\nA disciplined process identifies the relevant metrics before examining the result and includes evidence that could invalidate the thesis.\n\n### False Precision\n\nOn-chain dashboards often display exact numbers with several decimal places.\n\nThe calculation may still depend on uncertain address labels and behavioural assumptions.\n\nPrecision in presentation does not guarantee accuracy in interpretation.\n\nThe correct language is often:\n\n“The data suggests,”\n\nrather than:\n\n“The data proves.”\n\n### A Practical On-Chain Analysis Process\n\nBegin by defining the question.\n\nDo not start with dozens of indicators.\n\nIf the question concerns network adoption, examine genuine users, transaction value, fees and application activity.\n\nIf the question concerns possible selling pressure, examine exchange flows, holder age and realised profit.\n\nIf the question concerns valuation, examine supply, realised value, fee generation and network activity.\n\nNext, check the methodology and network structure.\n\nDetermine what the metric counts, excludes and assumes.\n\nCompare the current reading with its own history and the current market regime.\n\nFinally, combine the on-chain evidence with price, liquidity, derivatives and fundamental context.\n\nThe conclusion should state both the supporting evidence and the main uncertainty.','markdown',NULL,NULL,NULL,6,0,0,0,'',NULL,7,1785297600000 WHERE EXISTS (SELECT 1 FROM `courses` WHERE `id`='cognizen-crypto-mastery-foundations-production');
--> statement-breakpoint
INSERT OR IGNORE INTO `lessons` (`id`,`course_id`,`title`,`section_id`,`lesson_type`,`content`,`content_format`,`video_key`,`primary_asset_id`,`intro_asset_id`,`duration_minutes`,`is_preview`,`available_after_days`,`required_watch_percent`,`transcript`,`experience_json`,`position`,`updated_at`) SELECT 'cmf-module-3-11-lesson-08','cognizen-crypto-mastery-foundations-production','Example: Exchange Inflow and Common On-Chain Analysis Mistakes','cmf-module-3-11','text','### Example: Exchange Inflow\n\nSuppose an old wallet transfers a large quantity of Bitcoin to a recognised exchange.\n\nThis creates a possible selling-risk signal.\n\nA responsible analysis would ask:\n\nIs the address label reliable?\n\nIs the transfer internal?\n\nDid the assets move into a deposit or custody wallet?\n\nHas price reacted?\n\nAre other long-term holders also depositing?\n\nIs spot selling volume increasing?\n\nWhat percentage of normal market liquidity does the transfer represent?\n\nThe transfer becomes more meaningful when several independent forms of evidence confirm that actual selling is occurring.\n\n### Example: Exchange Outflow Trend\n\nSuppose exchange balances decline steadily for several months.\n\nAt the same time, long-term holder supply increases and price remains above major support.\n\nThis may suggest accumulation and reduced immediate market supply.\n\nHowever, the outflows could partly represent migration to institutional custodians or decentralised protocols.\n\nThe interpretation is constructive but not conclusive.\n\n### Example: Rising Active Addresses\n\nSuppose active addresses double after a token launches a major rewards programme.\n\nTransaction count and fees also rise.\n\nThe activity may appear to demonstrate adoption.\n\nFurther investigation reveals that users create many wallets to qualify for incentives.\n\nWhen the rewards end, activity collapses.\n\nThe original data was real.\n\nThe interpretation of sustainable adoption was wrong.\n\n### Example: Network Fees and Value Capture\n\nSuppose a blockchain generates high transaction fees.\n\nMost fees are paid to validators, while the native token is also required for network security and part of the fees is burned.\n\nThis may create a plausible link between usage and token value.\n\nAnother protocol may generate high application fees while the governance token receives none of them.\n\nIn that case, network success may not translate directly into value for the token holder.\n\n### Example: Capitulation\n\nSuppose price falls sharply below the estimated realised price.\n\nSupply in loss rises, long-term holders begin realising losses and exchange inflows increase.\n\nThe data may indicate capitulation.\n\nA strong reversal is still not guaranteed.\n\nThe market may remain below aggregate cost basis for an extended period.\n\nPrice stabilisation and reduced selling pressure would provide additional confirmation.\n\n### On-Chain Analysis Checklist\n\nBefore relying on an on-chain metric, ask:\n\nWhich blockchain and asset are being analysed?\n\nWhat exact question is the metric intended to answer?\n\nIs the metric based on raw transactions or a derived model?\n\nHow does the provider define the metric?\n\nAre exchange, contract or internal transfers excluded?\n\nIs one address being mistaken for one user?\n\nHas entity clustering been applied?\n\nHow reliable and current are the address labels?\n\nCould bots, spam or incentives be distorting activity?\n\nIs the network UTXO based or account based?\n\nDoes Layer 2 activity affect the interpretation?\n\nIs transaction value adjusted for internal movement?\n\nAre token prices and supply figures reliable?\n\nCould bridge assets be double counted?\n\nHow does the current reading compare with the metric’s own history?\n\nIs the relationship consistent across several market cycles?\n\nIs the metric leading, coincident or lagging?\n\nWhat alternative explanations exist?\n\nDoes price and liquidity confirm the interpretation?\n\nDoes derivatives positioning support or contradict it?\n\nWhat evidence would invalidate the conclusion?\n\nIs the analysis describing probability or claiming certainty?\n\n### Common On-Chain Analysis Mistakes\n\nA frequent mistake is treating addresses as users. This can dramatically overstate network adoption.\n\nAnother error is assuming that every exchange inflow represents an immediate intention to sell and every outflow represents long-term accumulation.\n\nAnalysts may compare transaction counts across networks without considering differences in architecture, fees and automated activity.\n\nSome use total value locked without adjusting for token-price appreciation or repeated collateral use.\n\nA further mistake is applying Bitcoin-specific metrics directly to tokens with different issuance, ownership and contract structures.\n\nFinally, participants may select whichever on-chain indicator supports their existing market view while ignoring contradictory data.','markdown',NULL,NULL,NULL,5,0,0,0,'',NULL,8,1785297600000 WHERE EXISTS (SELECT 1 FROM `courses` WHERE `id`='cognizen-crypto-mastery-foundations-production');
--> statement-breakpoint
INSERT OR IGNORE INTO `lessons` (`id`,`course_id`,`title`,`section_id`,`lesson_type`,`content`,`content_format`,`video_key`,`primary_asset_id`,`intro_asset_id`,`duration_minutes`,`is_preview`,`available_after_days`,`required_watch_percent`,`transcript`,`experience_json`,`position`,`updated_at`) SELECT 'cmf-module-3-11-lesson-09','cognizen-crypto-mastery-foundations-production','Common Misunderstandings and Key Takeaway','cmf-module-3-11','text','### Common Misunderstandings\n\n#### “The Blockchain Shows Exactly Who Is Buying and Selling”\n\nIt shows addresses and transfers. Identity and intent usually require inference.\n\n#### “One Address Equals One Investor”\n\nOne investor can control many addresses, and one exchange address can represent many investors.\n\n#### “A Transfer to an Exchange Means the Asset Will Be Sold”\n\nIt increases possible selling availability but can have several other purposes.\n\n#### “Exchange Outflows Are Always Bullish”\n\nThey can represent custody changes, collateral deployment or exchange restructuring.\n\n#### “More Transactions Mean More Adoption”\n\nBots, spam and incentive farming can inflate activity.\n\n#### “High Fees Prove a Network Is Successful”\n\nThey may show strong demand, but they can also make the network unusable for many participants.\n\n#### “High TVL Means a Protocol Is Safe”\n\nTVL says little by itself about smart contract, liquidity or governance risk.\n\n#### “Realised Price Is the True Value of the Asset”\n\nIt is an estimated aggregate on-chain cost basis, not an objective fair value.\n\n#### “MVRV Identifies Exact Tops and Bottoms”\n\nHistorical extremes provide context but cannot guarantee future turning points.\n\n#### “Whale Transfers Predict Price”\n\nThey reveal large movements without proving the economic purpose.\n\n#### “On-Chain Data Cannot Be Manipulated”\n\nThe ledger may be accurate while activity is generated strategically through bots, incentives or related wallets.\n\n#### “An Exact Dashboard Number Is Objectively Correct”\n\nDerived metrics depend on classification, filtering and valuation assumptions.\n\n#### “On-Chain Analysis Replaces Technical Analysis”\n\nIt provides a different layer of evidence and is generally strongest when combined with price and market data.\n\n### Module Summary\n\nOn-chain analysis studies activity recorded on public blockchains.\n\nIt can provide insight into asset movement, network usage, holder behaviour, supply changes, protocol activity and financial risk.\n\nRaw blockchain data includes transactions, addresses, balances, fees and smart contract interactions.\n\nDerived metrics transform that data into indicators such as active addresses, exchange flows, realised capitalisation, MVRV, supply in profit and holder-age distributions.\n\nThe transformation from raw data to a useful metric requires filtering, entity clustering and methodological assumptions.\n\nAn address is not the same as a user.\n\nA wallet may control many addresses, and one exchange address may represent millions of customers.\n\nOn-chain metrics must be interpreted according to the architecture of the network.\n\nBitcoin’s UTXO structure supports different forms of holder-age analysis from account-based smart contract networks.\n\nCommon activity measures include transaction count, transfer value, active addresses and fees.\n\nThese metrics can be distorted by bots, spam, incentives, internal movements and differences in network design.\n\nExchange inflows and outflows may help evaluate possible selling pressure and movement into self-custody.\n\nThey do not reveal intention with certainty.\n\nHolder and valuation metrics can provide insight into aggregate cost basis, realised profit, loss and long-term supply behaviour.\n\nThey are more useful for structural and cycle analysis than for exact short-term timing.\n\nDeFi analysis may include TVL, protocol fees, borrowing, collateral and liquidations.\n\nHeadline values should be adjusted for token prices, repeated collateral use and temporary incentives.\n\nOn-chain analysis is most powerful when it begins with a clear question, uses transparent methodology and is combined with price, liquidity, derivatives and fundamental evidence.\n\nBlockchain data provides unusual transparency.\n\nIt does not remove uncertainty.\n\nThe analyst’s task is to convert observable transactions into cautious economic interpretation without claiming to know more than the data can reveal.\n\n### Key Takeaway\n\nA blockchain records transactions with unusual transparency, but it does not record human intention.\n\nOn-chain analysis can show that assets moved, that network activity changed or that holders are realising profits and losses.\n\nIt cannot automatically tell you why those events occurred or what price will do next.\n\nBegin with the raw evidence, understand how the metric was constructed and consider alternative explanations.\n\nUse on-chain data to improve the quality of your market and network analysis—not to create certainty where none exists.\n\nThe next module is 3.12: Blockchain Activity and Network Health.','markdown',NULL,NULL,NULL,5,0,0,0,'',NULL,9,1785297600000 WHERE EXISTS (SELECT 1 FROM `courses` WHERE `id`='cognizen-crypto-mastery-foundations-production');
--> statement-breakpoint
INSERT OR IGNORE INTO `lessons` (`id`,`course_id`,`title`,`section_id`,`lesson_type`,`content`,`content_format`,`video_key`,`primary_asset_id`,`intro_asset_id`,`duration_minutes`,`is_preview`,`available_after_days`,`required_watch_percent`,`transcript`,`experience_json`,`position`,`updated_at`) SELECT 'cmf-module-3-11-lesson-10','cognizen-crypto-mastery-foundations-production','Check your understanding','cmf-module-3-11','text','### Check your understanding\n\nAnswer these questions to self-assess your understanding before moving on.\n\n1. What is on-chain analysis?\n\n2. How does on-chain data differ from exchange-market data?\n\n3. What information may a blockchain transaction contain?\n\n4. How does an address differ from a wallet?\n\n5. What is an entity in on-chain analysis?\n\n6. Why is one address not the same as one user?\n\n7. What is address clustering?\n\n8. What is entity labelling?\n\n9. Why can different providers report different values for the same metric?\n\n10. What is the difference between raw blockchain data and a derived metric?\n\n11. Why is data cleaning necessary?\n\n12. Why should transaction counts not be compared directly across every blockchain?\n\n13. How does the UTXO model differ from an account-based model?\n\n14. What is an active address?\n\n15. Why can active-address growth overstate user growth?\n\n16. What does transaction count measure?\n\n17. Why can median transaction value be more informative than the average?\n\n18. What can rising network fees indicate?\n\n19. Why can high fees also be negative for a network?\n\n20. What is net token issuance?\n\n21. Why should burns be compared with new issuance?\n\n22. What can staking data reveal?\n\n23. Why can a high staking ratio create concentration or liquidity concerns?\n\n24. What does holder-distribution analysis measure?\n\n25. Why can exchange addresses distort holder-concentration statistics?\n\n26. What is a whale?\n\n27. Why does a whale transfer not prove an intended sale?\n\n28. What are exchange inflows?\n\n29. What are exchange outflows?\n\n30. How is exchange net flow calculated?\n\n31. What can declining exchange balances suggest?\n\n32. What is holder age?\n\n33. What are coin days?\n\n34. What does realised price attempt to estimate?\n\n35. How does realised capitalisation differ from market capitalisation?\n\n36. What does MVRV compare?\n\n37. What is supply in profit?\n\n38. What is realised loss?\n\n39. What does SOPR measure?\n\n40. What are HODL waves?\n\n41. What does the Network Value to Transactions ratio compare?\n\n42. Why is Metcalfe’s Law not a precise blockchain valuation formula?\n\n43. What can stablecoin on-chain data reveal?\n\n44. What is total value locked?\n\n45. Why can TVL be double counted?\n\n46. Why does protocol fee generation not necessarily create value for a governance token?\n\n47. What do bridge flows show?\n\n48. Why must Layer 2 activity be considered separately from base-layer activity?\n\n49. How can incentive programmes distort user metrics?\n\n50. What can governance data reveal about control?\n\n51. Why can a treasury dominated by its own token be risky?\n\n52. How can on-chain data support security monitoring?\n\n53. What privacy risks arise from public blockchain records?\n\n54. Why does correlation between an on-chain metric and price not prove causation?\n\n55. Why are many on-chain metrics more suitable for structural analysis than short-term timing?\n\n56. How can on-chain and derivatives data complement one another?\n\n57. What is confirmation bias in on-chain analysis?\n\n58. What does false precision mean?\n\n59. Why should an analyst begin with a specific question?\n\n60. What evidence should be combined with on-chain metrics before reaching a conclusion?','markdown',NULL,NULL,NULL,6,0,0,0,'',NULL,10,1785297600000 WHERE EXISTS (SELECT 1 FROM `courses` WHERE `id`='cognizen-crypto-mastery-foundations-production');
--> statement-breakpoint
INSERT OR IGNORE INTO `course_sections` (`id`,`course_id`,`title`,`position`,`created_at`) SELECT 'cmf-module-3-12','cognizen-crypto-mastery-foundations-production','Module 3.12: Blockchain Activity and Network Health',13,1785297600000 WHERE EXISTS (SELECT 1 FROM `courses` WHERE `id`='cognizen-crypto-mastery-foundations-production');
